<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 376 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">14:00 - 14:30</td>
    <td><strong>Soft Matter and Data Repositories, a Personal View</strong>, Kurt Kremer (Max Planck Institute for Polymer Research, Germany) <a href="" id="abstract-2237-dialog-link-376"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 376 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2237-dialog-376" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG F1, 14:00 - 14:30</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>Soft Matter and Data Repositories, a Personal View</strong>; Kurt Kremer (Max Planck Institute for Polymer Research, Germany)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
Compared to many low molecular weight materials soft matter is not that perfectly characterized. E.g. polydispersity directly affects material properties. Furthermore chemical variation, for both synthetic and biological soft matter, is huge. Thus there are two options to provide data repositories, i.e. by experiment or simulation and quantum chemistry or by combination of both. I will present some thoughts of how, mainly based on theoretical work, they might be extended to form a basis of generally applicable data repositories.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 376 -->
