<tr id="0"><td colspan="2"><h3 class="datum">Monday, June 1, 2015</h3></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><h4 class="raum">HG E1.2</h4></td></tr><!-- begin single abstract programm entry 265 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">13:00 - 13:30</td>
    <td><strong>From Genomes to Systems Biology</strong>, Ioannis Xenarios (Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics, Switzerland) <a href="" id="abstract-2237-dialog-link-265"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 265 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2237-dialog-265" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG E1.2, 13:00 - 13:30</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>From Genomes to Systems Biology</strong>; Ioannis Xenarios (Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics, Switzerland)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: Team members (Vital-IT and Swiss-Prot, Switzerland)</i>
<br />
<br />
From the part list genes, proteins and chemical compounds to the complex dynamics of biological systems, computational approaches are critical. In this presentation I'll describe the challenges linking the genotypes to the phenotypes and the ability/inability to reconstruct what we understand of the biological system. I'll take examples in the field of immunology and more 'simple' model organism to explain the methodologies used to both characterize a system and also to predict novel regulations or unexpected combination of perturbation. 
</div>
