<!-- not showing 244 (too early) -->
<tr id="sentinel"><td>&nbsp;</td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><h3 class="datum">Monday, June 1, 2015</h3></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2"><h4 class="raum">HG F3</h4></td></tr><!-- begin single abstract programm entry 280 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">15:30 - 16:00</td>
    <td><strong>Data Assimilation in Geodynamical Modelling: Methods and Applications</strong>, Alik Ismail-Zadeh (Karlsruhe Institute of Technology, Germany) <a href="" id="abstract-2239-dialog-link-280"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 280 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2239-dialog-280" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG F3, 15:30 - 16:00</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>Data Assimilation in Geodynamical Modelling: Methods and Applications</strong>; Alik Ismail-Zadeh (Karlsruhe Institute of Technology, Germany)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
Present geophysical, geochemical, and geodetic observations together with geological information provide a clue to understanding dynamics of the Earth interior in the past. Assimilation of present observations allows to constrain mantle temperature/composition and flow in the past using dynamical models. Quantitative tools are required to assimilate the data and hence to solve inverse retrospective problems in geodynamics. The basic inversion methods (adjoint and quasi-reversibility) including the methodologies uncertainties and requirements for HPC, and two case studies related to mantle/lithosphere dynamics and to a volcanic lava flow will be presented and discussed.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 280 -->
