<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 247 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">16:30 - 17:00</td>
    <td><strong>Does it pay to get a Reverse Mortgage?</strong>, Valentina Michelangeli (Bank of Italy, Italy) <a href="" id="abstract-2239-dialog-link-247"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 247 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2239-dialog-247" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG F30, 16:30 - 17:00</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>Does it pay to get a Reverse Mortgage?</strong>; Valentina Michelangeli (Bank of Italy, Italy)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
This paper uses data on single households from the Health and Retirement Study (HRS) to study the economic gains or losses associated with reverse mortgages. These data are examined within a dynamic structural life-cycle model featuring consumption, housing, and mobility decisions with uncertainty about both life span and mobility. I develop and apply new methods for solution and estimation based on a combination of four state-of-the-art mathematical programming tools. I find that reverse mortgages provide liquidity and a
form of longevity insurance; however, moving becomes a risky proposition.

</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 247 -->
