<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 455 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">CLI-06</td>
    <td><strong>Tuning a Global Climate Model - a Costly Hunt in Parameter Space</strong>, Doris Folini (ETH Zurich, Switzerland) <a href="" id="cts-abstract-2267-dialog-link-455"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 455 -->
<div style="display:none" id="cts-abstract-2267-dialog-455" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Poster Session, Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>17:30 - 20:00</strong>
<br />
<br />
CLI-06
<br />
<strong>Tuning a Global Climate Model - a Costly Hunt in Parameter Space</strong>, Doris Folini (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)
<br /><br />
<i>Co-authors: Martin Wild (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</i>
<br />
<br />
Global climate models have to rely on parameterizations for a number of sub-grid-scale processes. Associated free parameters have to be adjusted such as to obtain a 'physically meaningful climate', a process referred to as 'model tuning'. We report on the tuning of one specific global climate model: MPI-ESM-HAM, the Max Planck Earth System Model (MPI-ESM) coupled to the Hamburg Aerosol Module (HAM). And we carve out some questions related to the fact that model tuning is, in essence, an expensive search in a parameter space, where the parameter space and the score function are not necessarily well defined 'ab initio'.

</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 455 -->
