<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 454 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">MAT-17</td>
    <td><strong>Self-Assembly of Water-Methanol Mixtures at the Surface of Graphite</strong>, Daniele Giofrè (EPFL, Switzerland) <a href="" id="cts-abstract-2267-dialog-link-454"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 454 -->
<div style="display:none" id="cts-abstract-2267-dialog-454" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Poster Session, Monday, June 1, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>17:30 - 20:00</strong>
<br />
<br />
MAT-17
<br />
<strong>Self-Assembly of Water-Methanol Mixtures at the Surface of Graphite</strong>, Daniele Giofrè (EPFL, Switzerland)
<br /><br />
<i>Co-authors: Michele Ceriotti (EPFL, Switzerland)</i>
<br />
<br />
AFM experiments observed the formation of regular, striped patterns at the interface between a methanol/water solution and a graphite surface. The time scale for the formation of these patterns is beyond direct observation by atomistic simulations. Nevertheless, molecular dynamics shows segregation of methanol at the interface, and a high degree of topological and geometric order in the H-bond network. The regular pattern can then be explained as a regular array of defects originating due to the small mismatch between the periodicity of the substrate and the characteristic length-scale of the H-bond patterns. 
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 454 -->
