<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 282 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">14:00 - 14:30</td>
    <td><strong>TRAPHIC: an Efficient Radiative Transfer Method for SPH Simulations with Many Sources</strong>, Alireza Rahmati (University of Zurich, Switzerland) <a href="" id="abstract-2253-dialog-link-282"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 282 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2253-dialog-282" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Tuesday, June 2, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG E3, 14:00 - 14:30</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>TRAPHIC: an Efficient Radiative Transfer Method for SPH Simulations with Many Sources</strong>; Alireza Rahmati (University of Zurich, Switzerland)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
I will talk about the radiative transfer (RT) code TRAPHIC (TRAnsport of PHotons In Cones). TRAPHIC is a multi-frequency RT code for use in Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) simulations. It solves the time-dependent RT equation by tracing photon packets emitted by source particles at the speed of light and in a photon-conserving manner through the simulation box. 
While the unique design of TRAPHIC makes it ideal for cosmological simulations with large number of sources, it is a general purpose ionizing RT code, and as I will show with several examples, has already been successfully employed in a range of problems.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 282 -->
