<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 358 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">14:00 - 14:30</td>
    <td><strong>Shared Memory Parallelization Strategies for Matrix-free Finite Element Operator Evaluation</strong>, Martin Kronbichler (Technische Universität München, Germany) <a href="" id="abstract-2253-dialog-link-358"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 358 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2253-dialog-358" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Tuesday, June 2, 2015</strong>
<br />
<strong>HG E1.2, 14:00 - 14:30</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>Shared Memory Parallelization Strategies for Matrix-free Finite Element Operator Evaluation</strong>; Martin Kronbichler (Technische Universität München, Germany)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: Katharina Kormann (Technische Universität München, Germany)</i>
<br />
<br />
Matrix-free finite element operator evaluation for quadratic and higher order hexahedral bases has been shown to be faster per degree of freedom than sparse matrix-vector products for linear elements. The key to success is substituting a memory intensive kernel by fast tensorial integration in a way that suits modern hardware. Our shared-memory implementation dynamically schedules integration tasks on non-conflicting cells and faces, offering coloring, partitioning, and more abstract flow graph concepts. Results show that hardware trends with a growing number of cores per memory controller and widening vector units require particular emphasis on memory access patterns into solution vectors.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 358 -->
