<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 872 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">11:30 - 12:00</td>
    <td><strong>Subcritical Convection in a Rotating Sphere Using an Hybrid 2D/3D Model</strong>, Celine Guervilly (Newcastle University, United Kingdom) <a href="" id="abstract-2431-dialog-link-872"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 872 -->
<div style="display:none" id="abstract-2431-dialog-872" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Thursday, June 9, 2016</strong>
<br />
<strong>Garden 1A, 11:30 - 12:00</strong>
<br /><br />
<strong>Subcritical Convection in a Rotating Sphere Using an Hybrid 2D/3D Model</strong>; Celine Guervilly (Newcastle University, United Kingdom)
<br />
<br />
<i>Co-Authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
We study thermal convection driven by internal heating in a rotating sphere for low Prandtl numbers. Our model assumes that the velocity is invariant along the axis of rotation due to the rapid rotation of the system, while the temperature is computed in 3D. We find the presence of two dynamical branches: a weak branch that is connected to the linear onset of convection and a strong branch with large values of the convective and zonal velocities. 
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 872 -->
<script type="text/javascript">
$(document).ready(
