<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 1092 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap">CLI-02</td>
    <td><strong>Climate Change Simulations at Kilometer-Scale Resolution</strong>, Nikolina Ban (ETH Zurich, Switzerland) <a href="" id="cts-abstract-2461-dialog-link-1092"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 1092 -->
<div style="display:none" id="cts-abstract-2461-dialog-1092" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Poster Session, Thursday, June 9, 2016</strong>
<br />
<strong>17:30 - 19:30</strong>
<br />
<br />
CLI-02
<br />
<strong>Climate Change Simulations at Kilometer-Scale Resolution</strong>, Nikolina Ban (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)
<br /><br />
<i>Co-authors: Juerg Schmidli (Goethe University of Frankfurt, Germany); Christoph Schär (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</i>
<br />
<br />
The recent increase of the computational power enables running of climate simulations at the kilometer-scale resolution. This modeling approach is able to explicitly resolve deep convection (i.e., thunderstorms and rain showers), and thus allows reducing some of the key uncertainties in current climate models.
 
Here we present analyses of decade-long climate change simulations at horizontal resolution of 2.2km across a greater Alpine region. The simulations have been conducted on a Cray XE6 system using a setup with 2000 cores on a computation mesh of 500x500x60 grid points. The results show great improvement in the simulation of summer precipitation, and demonstrate the importance of kilometer-scale resolution in climate change projections.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 1092 -->
