<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 1093 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap"> MAT-07</td>
    <td><strong>Nuclear Quantum Effects on Calculated Aqueous Redox Properties</strong>, Vladimir Rybkin (ETH Zurich, Switzerland) <a href="" id="cts-abstract-2466-dialog-link-1093"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 1093 -->
<div style="display:none" id="cts-abstract-2466-dialog-1093" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Poster Session, Thursday, June 9, 2016</strong>
<br />
<strong> 17:30 - 19:30</strong>
<br />
<br />
 MAT-07
<br />
<strong>Nuclear Quantum Effects on Calculated Aqueous Redox Properties</strong>, Vladimir Rybkin (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)
<br /><br />
<i>Co-authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
Nuclear quantum effects neglected in most applications have been recently shown to have a significant influence on the calculated band structures of bulk liquids and solids and might thus be very significant for electrochemical properties.
We have calculated thermodynamic integrals as well as vertical ionization potentials (VIP) and vertical electron affinities (VEA) for two redox pairs, CO2/CO2- and HO2/HO2-, using DFT-driven thermodynamic integration using the classical and the quantum generalized Langevin equation colored-noise thermostats. It has been found that quantum nuclear effects lead to noticeable shifts in both VIP and VEA: the former is reduced, whereas the latter is increased for both pairs. As a consequence, significant effect cancellation is observed for the thermodynamic integrals computed with the classical and the quantum thermostats.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 1093 -->
