<!-- begin single abstract programm entry 1110 -->
<tr>
    <td style="white-space: nowrap"> PHY-05</td>
    <td><strong>Polarized Radiative Transfer in Discontinuous Media</strong>, Gioele Janett (Istituto Ricerche Solari Locarno, Switzerland) <a href="" id="cts-abstract-2467-dialog-link-1110"><u>Abstract</u></a></td>
</tr>

<!-- begin abstract detail popup 1110 -->
<div style="display:none" id="cts-abstract-2467-dialog-1110" title="Abstract">
<br />
<strong>Poster Session, Thursday, June 9, 2016</strong>
<br />
<strong>17:30 - 19:30</strong>
<br />
<br />
 PHY-05
<br />
<strong>Polarized Radiative Transfer in Discontinuous Media</strong>, Gioele Janett (Istituto Ricerche Solari Locarno, Switzerland)
<br /><br />
<i>Co-authors: </i>
<br />
<br />
Radiation hydrodynamic simulations of stellar atmosphere frequently
show shock fronts, contact discontinues, or steep gradients across
which radiative transfer needs to be computed in post-processing
steps. In view of applications to magnetohydrodynamic models of the
solar atmosphere, we have developed a new method for integrating
the equation of radiative transfer for polarized light across a
discontinuous atmosphere, using piecewise continuous reconstruction
and slope limiters. In this poster, we present a comparison of results
obtained with our new method and with more conventional methods.
</div>
<!-- end abstract detail popup 1110 -->
