CSM-13 Parallelization of Graph Partitioning using Metis and OpenMP
Presenter:
Rodrigo Pinto Coelho (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)
Track(s):
Computer Science & Applied Mathematics
+ Abstract
+ Presentation
Algorithms that find optimal partitions for highly unstructured graphs have a wide range of applications. These applications include load balancing in super-computers, fill-reducing orderings of sparse matrices and design of very large scale integrated circuits (VLSI). METIS is a well-known set of serial programs developed by the Karypis Lab designed to solve this problem. However, METIS was not originally designed to run in multiple processors. In this project we will use OpenMP (Open Multi-Processing), an API managed by the nonprofit consortium OpenMP Architecture Review Board, to parallelize METIS. We will then compare the parallelized version with the original METIS to gain an understanding of the performance improvements that can be obtained.
