EMD-01 Scalable MCMC Algorithm for the Accurate Estimation of Exponential Random Graph Models
Presenter:
Maksym Byshkin (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)
Track(s):
Emerging Domains in HPC
+ Abstract
The increase in the number and size of large network data sets requires novel efficient methods for their analysis. Exponential Random Graph Models (ERGMs) are a general form of probability distribution widely applicable to the analysis of social and other networks. The scope of ERGMs is limited by the fact that existing estimation approaches rely on iterative computational methods that carry out large number of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) simulations to draw equilibrium network configurations. Estimation approaches include Bayesian, maximum likelihood and the method of moments. We propose an accurate estimation approach, based on network properties at MCMC equilibrium, and design a simple and efficient algorithm that estimates model parameters several orders of magnitude faster than existing algorithms. *Generous support from the Swiss National Platform of Advanced Scientific Computing (PASC) is gratefully acknowledged.
19:00 - 21:00
ENG-01 A Multiscale Model for the Simulation of Sediment Impact Erosion of Metallic Targets
Presenter:
Sebastián Leguizamón (EPFL, Switzerland)
Track(s):
Engineering
+ Abstract
+ Presentation
Erosion damage in hydraulic turbines is a common problem caused by the impact of small sediments entrained in the fluid. The current state-of-the-art simulations rely on CFD particle tracking coupled with erosion correlations that introduce great uncertainty and lack generality. A novel multiscale model of erosion is presented which avoids the use of correlations by explicitly simulating the sediment impacts. The problem is decoupled into its two dominant scales, each of which is solved using the Finite Volume Particle Method. On the microscale, the erosion rate is calculated by means of multi-particle impact simulations which include all the thermomechanical modeling required in the solid. On the macroscale, the sediment flux and impact condition distributions on the target are modeled through particle tracking in the fluid. Finally, a sequential multiscale algorithm allows reproducing the original coupled problem. The proposed model is validated against experimental data with satisfactory results.
19:00 - 21:00
ENG-02 GPU-SPHEROS: A GPU-Accelerated Versatile Solver Based on the Finite Volume Particle Method
Presenter:
Siamak Alimirzazadeh (EPFL, Switzerland)
Track(s):
Engineering
+ Abstract
+ Presentation
The aim of the present research is to speed up a Finite Volume Particle Method (FVPM) solver utilizing GPU many-core architecture. FVPM is a conservative and consistent particle-based method which inherits interesting features of both Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics and grid-based Finite Volume Method. SPHEROS is a versatile FVPM solver which has been developed at EPFL-LMH, for hydrodynamic simulation of hydraulic turbines and sediment erosion simulation. SPHEROS is able to handle the interaction between fluid, solid, and sediment. In order to accelerate SPHEROS, GPU-SPHEROS has been developed in CUDA featuring Thrust library and highly optimized kernels for both compute-bound and memory-bound algorithms. Up to now, remarkable speedup has been achieved for some parts including particle neighbor search and computing fluxes and forces and we are now focusing our efforts on the identified bottlenecks. The bottlenecks are mostly located in the computation of particles interaction vectors, which is based on spherical-support kernels.
19:00 - 21:00
LS-01 Aortic Valve Hemodynamics Using Variational Transfer Immersed Boundary Method
Presenter:
Barna Errol Mario Becsek (University of Bern, Switzerland)
Track(s):
Life Sciences
+ Abstract
+ Presentation
We present the hemodynamics of a bioprosthetic heart valve. The heart valve is embedded in a parametric representation of the aortic root. We make use of sophisticated finer-reinforced material models for both the aortic tissue as well as the leaflet tissue. We obtain results by employing our in-house library for FSI problems. Following the concept of the Immersed Boundary Method, we discretize the respective domains with either finite elements or finite differences. Interchange of the discrete fields is performed with a variational transfer library. To manage stiffness of our coupled system we introduce accuracy based time step control through an embedded Runge-Kutta scheme. All parts of our code are MPI parallel and being adapted to today’s hybrid node supercomputers. We wish to provide this framework as an FSI library for other researchers in the future.
