	</script><div class="title">C++ Template Mixins in Salvus: A Platform for Multiscale Waveform Modeling and Inversion</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michael Afanasiev (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa251","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Afanasiev","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Recent years have been witness to the application of waveform inversion to new and exciting domains, ranging from non-destructive testing to global seismology. Often, each new application brings with it novel wave propagation physics, spatial and temporal discretizations, and models of variable complexity. Adapting existing software to these novel applications often requires a significant investment of time, and acts as a barrier to progress. To combat these problems we have introduced Salvus, a software package designed to solve large-scale full-waveform inverse problems, with a focus on both flexibility and performance. Salvus bridges the gap between research and production codes with a design based on C++ template mixins that separates the physical equations from the numerical core. In this presentation we outline how we have exploited both dynamic and static polymorphism to retain run-time flexibility, while still benefiting from compile-time template resolution. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa253"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
