	</script><div class="title">Immersive Wave Experimentation: Extreme Low-Latency and HPC Requirements Enabled by FPGA Technology</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dirk-Jan van Manen (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa253","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dirk-Jan","last_name":"van Manen","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Immersive experimentation is a new paradigm for wave-based laboratory experimentation aimed at overcoming lab-size and corresponding frequency-range related limitations that plague conventional wave propagation experimentation. Using so-called exact boundary conditions, a physical experimentation domain can be immersed in an arbitrarily large numerical domain in such a way that the waves in the physical domain drive the “simulation” in the numerical domain and vice-versa, in real-time. Waves propagating towards the walls of the experimentation domain are sensed by dense receiver arrays and extrapolated to the boundary ahead of time where they are actively cancelled using dense source arrays. Outgoing waves are also extrapolated through the numerical domain using pre-computed Green’s functions and re-emitted into the experimentation domain, enabling multiple scattering interactions between the laboratory and numerical domain. We present the system enabling the implementation of this unique laboratory at ETH, with a focus on the extreme low-latency and HPC requirements. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa254"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa254","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Petascale Computation of Multi-Physics Seismic Simulations - and Beyond","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Capturing the observed complexity of earthquake sources in concurrence with seismic wave propagation simulations is an inherently multi-scale, multi-physics problem. Here I present earthquake scenarios resolving high-detail dynamic rupture evolution and high frequency ground motion. The up to multi-PetaFLOP simulations are performed with SeisSol (www.seissol.org), an open-source software package based on an ADER-Discontinuous Galerkin (DG) scheme solving the seismic wave equations in elastic, viscoelastic, and viscoplastic media with high-order accuracy in time and space on tetrahedral unstructured meshes. SeisSol has been optimized on all software levels obtaining up to 44% peak performance on full-machine production runs on some of the largest supercomputers worldwide. It features MPI+OpenMP parallelization overlapping communication and computation, cluster-based local time stepping and asynchronous parallel input\/output schemes. I conclude with an outlook on ExaHyPE (www.exahype.eu) a flexible engine to solve hyperbolic systems of Partial Differential Equations via explicit ADER-DG or Finite Volume schemes on future exascale hardware.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa254","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alice-Agnes","last_name":"Gabriel","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa254","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alice-Agnes","last_name":"Gabriel","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Petascale Computation of Multi-Physics Seismic Simulations - and Beyond</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alice-Agnes Gabriel (Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa254","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alice-Agnes","last_name":"Gabriel","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Capturing the observed complexity of earthquake sources in concurrence with seismic wave propagation simulations is an inherently multi-scale, multi-physics problem. Here I present earthquake scenarios resolving high-detail dynamic rupture evolution and high frequency ground motion. The up to multi-PetaFLOP simulations are performed with SeisSol (www.seissol.org), an open-source software package based on an ADER-Discontinuous Galerkin (DG) scheme solving the seismic wave equations in elastic, viscoelastic, and viscoplastic media with high-order accuracy in time and space on tetrahedral unstructured meshes. SeisSol has been optimized on all software levels obtaining up to 44% peak performance on full-machine production runs on some of the largest supercomputers worldwide. It features MPI+OpenMP parallelization overlapping communication and computation, cluster-based local time stepping and asynchronous parallel input/output schemes. I conclude with an outlook on ExaHyPE (www.exahype.eu) a flexible engine to solve hyperbolic systems of Partial Differential Equations via explicit ADER-DG or Finite Volume schemes on future exascale hardware. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess198-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess198" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS02 Exascale Solver for Application-Driven Science (1/2): Domain Decomposition</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 205</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg 