	</script><div class="title">Parallel Nonlinear Domain Decomposition in Multiscale Problems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Oliver Rheinbach (TU Bergakademie Freiberg, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa145","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliver","last_name":"Rheinbach","affiliation":"TU Bergakademie Freiberg","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> For a few decades, Newton-Krylov algorithms with suitable preconditioners such as domain decomposition (DD) or multigrid (MG) methods (Newton-Krylov-DD or Newton-Krylov-MG) have been the workhorse for the parallel solution of nonlinear implicit problems. In these methods, the problem is first linearized and then decomposed into parallel problems on subdomains. In nonlinear domain decomposition methods, however, the nonlinear problem is decomposed before Newton linearization, which increases the concurrency of the algorithm. We discuss recent nonlinear domain decomposition of the FETI-DP (Finite Element Tearing and Interconnecting) or BDDC (Balancing Domain Decomposition by Constraints) type to solve nonlinear hyperelasticity or plasticity problems and combine them with efficient AMG (Algebraic Multigrid) methods. We then apply these methods within a highly parallel two-scale numerical homogenization scheme using millions of MPI ranks for the simulation of micro-heterogeneous materials. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa115"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa115","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"FETI Based Solvers for Exascale Computations in Mechanics","scientific_track":"","abstract":"This contribution presents the Hybrid Total FETI (HTFETI) domain decomposition method implemented in the in-house library ESPRESO (http:\/\/espreso.it4i.cz). ESPRESO is designed to run on massively parallel machines with hundreds of thousands of CPU cores and can exploit modern many-core accelerators. HTFETI is a multilevel FETI method and is scalable for cases where classical FETI method fails due to the large number of subdomains and resulting large coarse problem. The penalty is that the resulting linear system requires more iterations for the same domain decomposition when compared to the FETI method. This negative effect can be partially reduced using transformation of the basis realized by additional Lagrange multipliers. This is an alternative to the approach which modifies the subdomain stiffness matrices which can generate higher filling of the Cholesky factors and increases both the memory requirements and the processing time.","begin_time":"13:30","begin_timestamp":"1522236600","end_time":"14:00","end_timestamp":"1522238400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa115","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tom\u00e1\u0161","last_name":"Kozubek","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa115","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tom\u00e1\u0161","last_name":"Kozubek","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa115","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tom\u00e1\u0161","last_name":"Brzobohat\u00fd","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa115","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexandros","last_name":"Markopoulos","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa115","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Lubom\u00edr","last_name":"\u0158\u00edha","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">FETI Based Solvers for Exascale Computations in Mechanics</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Tomáš Kozubek (TU Ostrava, Czech Republic)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa115","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tom\u00e1\u0161","last_name":"Kozubek","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> This contribution presents the Hybrid Total FETI (HTFETI) domain decomposition method implemented in the in-house library ESPRESO (http://espreso.it4i.cz). ESPRESO is designed to run on massively parallel machines with hundreds of thousands of CPU cores and can exploit modern many-core accelerators. HTFETI is a multilevel FETI method and is scalable for cases where classical FETI method fails due to the large number of subdomains and resulting large coarse problem. The penalty is that the resulting linear system requires more iterations for the same domain decomposition when compared to the FETI method. This negative effect can be partially reduced using transformation of the basis realized by additional Lagrange multipliers. This is an alternative to the approach which modifies the subdomain stiffness matrices which can generate higher filling of the Cholesky factors and increases both the memory requirements and the processing time. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa146"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa146","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Recent Advances in Multilevel Domain Decomposition: Large Scales, Heterogeneous Problems, and Unfitted Finite Elements","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this work, we present an object-oriented (OO) software framework for the development of highly-scalable multilevel domain decomposition methods. Our motivation here is not only to show the excellent scalability results of the preconditioners resulting from the framework, but also to present its customization to challenging applications. In particular, we will show that slightly simple modifications of the algorithm, with a coarse space definition based on the physical coefficients in the underlying PDE, leads to robust methods for heterogeneous problems for some PDE problems. On the other hand, we consider the application of these preconditioners to unfitted methods, which can destroy the condition number of the linear systems to be solved, depending on the location of the cell cuts. We show how to make these preconditioners robust also for embedded boundary methods for coercive PDEs by a proper modification of the inter-subdomain constraints.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa146","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Santiago","last_name":"Badia","affiliation":"Polytechnic University of Catalonia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa146","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Santiago","last_name":"Badia","affiliation":"Polytechnic University of Catalonia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa146","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alberto","last_name":"Mart\u00edn","affiliation":"Polytechnic University of Catalonia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Cia