	</script><div class="title">Recent Advances in Multilevel Domain Decomposition: Large Scales, Heterogeneous Problems, and Unfitted Finite Elements</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Santiago Badia (Polytechnic University of Catalonia, Spain)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa146","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Santiago","last_name":"Badia","affiliation":"Polytechnic University of Catalonia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this work, we present an object-oriented (OO) software framework for the development of highly-scalable multilevel domain decomposition methods. Our motivation here is not only to show the excellent scalability results of the preconditioners resulting from the framework, but also to present its customization to challenging applications. In particular, we will show that slightly simple modifications of the algorithm, with a coarse space definition based on the physical coefficients in the underlying PDE, leads to robust methods for heterogeneous problems for some PDE problems. On the other hand, we consider the application of these preconditioners to unfitted methods, which can destroy the condition number of the linear systems to be solved, depending on the location of the cell cuts. We show how to make these preconditioners robust also for embedded boundary methods for coercive PDEs by a proper modification of the inter-subdomain constraints. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa110"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa110","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"GPU-Accelerated Matrix-Free Methods in Geophysics: Case Studies in pTatin3d and StagYY","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present recent results in using graphics processing units (GPUs) for computational hotspots in multigrid methods in the geophysics packages pTatin3d and StagYY. A common approach is to express smoothing, grid transfer and residual evaluations as sparse matrix-vector products.\nHowever, sparse matrix-vector products offer only low arithmetic intensity. As a remedy, we employ matrix-free methods, which allow for increased arithmetic intensity and thus performance, particularly for higher-order discretization methods. We present results obtained for a Q2-P1 discretization used in the simulation of lithospheric dynamics, and for a first-order staggered grid approach for simulating mantle convection. Through a careful choice of per-thread register usage, thread assignments, and tricks like warp shuffles, our performance results match those predicted by our performance models. Since the techniques presented in this talk are not restricted to applications in geophysics, our results and techniques should be of interest to a broad audience.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa110","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Karl","last_name":"Rupp","affiliation":"TU Wien","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa110","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Karl","last_name":"Rupp","affiliation":"TU Wien","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa110","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa110","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Patrick","last_name":"Sanan"