	</script><div class="title">GPU-Accelerated Matrix-Free Methods in Geophysics: Case Studies in pTatin3d and StagYY</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Karl Rupp (TU Wien, Austria)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa110","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Karl","last_name":"Rupp","affiliation":"TU Wien","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present recent results in using graphics processing units (GPUs) for computational hotspots in multigrid methods in the geophysics packages pTatin3d and StagYY. A common approach is to express smoothing, grid transfer and residual evaluations as sparse matrix-vector products.However, sparse matrix-vector products offer only low arithmetic intensity. As a remedy, we employ matrix-free methods, which allow for increased arithmetic intensity and thus performance, particularly for higher-order discretization methods. We present results obtained for a Q2-P1 discretization used in the simulation of lithospheric dynamics, and for a first-order staggered grid approach for simulating mantle convection. Through a careful choice of per-thread register usage, thread assignments, and tricks like warp shuffles, our performance results match those predicted by our performance models. Since the techniques presented in this talk are not restricted to applications in geophysics, our results and techniques should be of interest to a broad audience. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess179-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess179" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS03 From Linear Algebra to High-Performance Code</strong>, Room C1</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px