	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present here a general approach to calculating thermal transport based on density-functional perturbation theory, where harmonic and anharmonic terms are calculated from first-principles and used in the solution of the Boltzmann transport equation. We present results for bulk silicon and germanium, their alloys and superlattices, single-sheet graphene, highlighting the effects of dimensionality, alloying, or nanostructuring in engineering thermal conductance and the figure of merit of thermoelectric devices. Last, we show how the study of the exact solutions of the linearised Boltzmann transport equation forces revisiting some classic concepts of heat propagation, and where phonons cannot be considered the elementary carriers of heat. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa114"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa114","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Ab Initio Calculations of the Lattice Thermal Conductivity and the Discovery of New Thermoelectric Materials","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Within the last few years it has been possible to compute the lattice thermal conductivity of bulk materials using ab initio methods. The interactions between the phonons are obtained from density functional theory and this information is incorporated into the Boltzmann to obtain the thermal conductivity. The high accuracy obtained from those calculations suggests they could be useful for finding new materials. We present several strategies that we used performing such a search. The first method we used is datamining. We screened the entire Material Project library to find materials with ultra low thermal conductivity. The second method is based on polymorphism and was used to study Zn-Sb compounds. Finally, we conclude showing how ab initio calculations can be combined with Monte Carlo simulations to describe thermal conduction at the micron scale.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa114","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Laurent","last_name":"Chaput","affiliation":"University of Lorraine","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa114","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Laurent","last_name":"Chaput","affiliation":"University of Lorraine","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Ab Initio Calculations of the Lattice Thermal Conductivity and the Discovery of New Thermoelectric Materials</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Laurent Chaput (University of Lorraine, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa114","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Laurent","last_name":"Chaput","affiliation":"University of Lorraine","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Within the last few years it has been possible to compute the lattice thermal conductivity of bulk materials using ab initio methods. The interactions between the phonons are obtained from density functional theory and this information is incorporated into the Boltzmann to obtain the thermal conductivity. The high accuracy obtained from those calculations suggests they could be useful for finding new materials. We present several strategies that we used performing such a search. The first method we used is datamining. We screened the entire Material Project library to find materials with ultra low thermal conductivity. The second method is based on polymorphism and was used to study Zn-Sb compounds. Finally, we conclude showing how ab initio calculations can be combined with Monte Carlo simulations to describe thermal conduction at the micron scale. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa240"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa240","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Systematic Data Collection from First-Principles Lattice Thermal Conductivity Calculation and its Analysis","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Recent progress of computers enables us to calculate lattice thermal conductivity from first-principles. We can obtain highly reliable results based on Boltzmann equation with the collision term obtained from first-principles anharmonic phonon calculation. Although currently this calculation requires a lot of computational demand, its computation can be easily distributed among very many computer-nodes with no overhead and each piece is computationally not demanding at all. Using this calculation approach, we can systematically compute lattice thermal conductivities of a variety of compounds and collect a huge amount of fruitful microscopic information on lattice thermal conductivity such as phonon lifetime and group velocity. Our current objective is to develop ways to analyze these detailed data. We have been applying machine learning approaches for it and visualization will play an important role. We introduce a phonon open database (http:\/\/phonondb.mtl.kyoto-u.ac.jp), that we are making and hosting.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa240","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Atsushi","last_name":"Togo","affiliation":"Kyoto University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa240","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Atsushi","last_name":"Togo","affiliation":"Kyoto University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa240","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Isao","last_name":"Tanaka","affiliation":"Kyoto University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Systematic Data Collection from First-Principles Lattice Thermal Conductivity Calculation and its Analysis</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Atsushi Togo (Kyoto University, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa240","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Atsushi","last_name":"Togo","affiliation":"Kyoto University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Recent progress of computers enables us to calculate lattice thermal conductivity from first-principles. We can obtain highly reliable results based on Boltzmann equation with the collision term obtained from first-principles anharmonic phonon calculation. Although currently this calculation requires a lot of computational demand, its computation can be easily distributed among very many computer-nodes with no overhead and each piece is computationally not demanding at all. Using this calculation approach, we can systematically compute lattice thermal conductivities of a variety of compounds and collect a huge amount of fruitful microscopic information on lattice thermal conductivity such as phonon lifetime and group velocity. Our current objective is to develop ways to analyze these detailed data. We have been applying machine learning approaches for it and visualization will play an important role. We introduce a phonon open database (http://phonondb.mtl.kyoto-u.ac.jp), that we are making and hosting. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess167-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess167" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS05 Higher Order Discretizations in Large Eddy Simulation of High Reynolds Number Turbulent Flow in Engineering Applications</strong>, Room E</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess167"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Ramesh Balakrishnan (Argonne National Laboratory, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ramesh","last_name":"Balakrishnan","affiliation":"Argonne National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Engineering</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The simulation of turbulent flows in engineering applications is often characterized by high Reynolds number, physical processes that depend on length scales that are too small to be resolved, and complex geometry. The advances in computing hardware notwithstanding, it is becoming clear that large eddy simulation (LES) of such flows, where the resolved/filtered scales of motion are evolved, and the unresolved scaled are modeled, is still intractable. The large number of grid points required for a well-resolved simulation of the flow physics places a greater need for modeling the unresolved scales and evolving the resolved scales in a manner whereby the dissipative and dispersive errors are minimized. Given that in a LES, the errors in the solution are a combination of filtering errors that are characterized by the filter width (delta), the numerical order of accuracy, which is characterized by the cell width (h), and the sub-grid scale (SGS) modeling error, an assessment of the resulting &ldquo;solution&rdquo; is complicated by the fact that it is difficult to isolate the effects of each of these contributing factors. This area of research offers opportunities to quantify the tradeoffs between the computational advantages offered by higher-order numerical methods and the turbulence resolving capabilities of these numerical methods in the context of LES of high Reynolds number flows. On emerging exascale computing platforms, where the available power is capped at 20MW, the architecture is beginning to be characterized by processors with a large number of cores that run at dynamic clock speeds that decrease as the cores begin to overheat, deep memory hierarchies with less on-chip memory, and multiple pathways to parallelizing algorithms, ranging from coarse-grained parallelism (MPI) to fine-grained parallelism (threads, vectorization). The reduced on-chip memory requires time consuming operations to fetch data from external (off-chip) memory to local cache in order to make computations possible! On such platforms, the traditional measure of assessing the efficiency of parallel codes, via FLOPs alone, is being replaced by the more meaningful arithmetic intensity (AI), which is defined as the ratio of FLOPs to the number of load-store operations. For turbulence simulations, it would appear that higher-order numerical methods that are less memory bandwidth limited may offer an obvious advantage. However, despite a veritable body of literature that documents the advantages of higher-order methods when applied to problems that are ideal &ndash; in the sense that the cases to which they have been applied are those where one has a fairly high degree of control on the inflow and boundary conditions, and the geometry of the computational domain &ndash; it is not quite clear if these methods could serve as the gold standard when one applies higher-order methods to drive the compute engine in a predictive flow simulation tool, with considerable uncertainties in the flow conditions and complexities in the geometry. The focus of this minisymposium, therefore, is a presentation of higher-order numerical discretizations, their impacts on the resolvable turbulent flow physics, and the scaling and parallel performance of higher-order discretizations on emerging computing hardware.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa126"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:00 - 13:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa126","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Numerical Simulations and Robust Predictions of Cloud Cavitation Collapse","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We will present large-scale simulations of free-field cloud collapses with up to O(10k) resolved gas bubbles. This large number of resolved bubbles is necessary in order to collect meaningful statistics. We will provide detailed insight into the collapse process that starts from the outer surface of the cloud and propagates inwards in the form of a pressure, velocity, and bubble deformation wave. Furthermore, we will address comparisons to simplified models, in particular, Rayleigh-Plesset-like equations. Additionally, we will also quantify uncertainties in peak pressures and micro-jet formation of clouds under random initial bubble locations and radii. These degrees of randomness manifest themselves in a wide range of peak pressures. We will show uncertainty quantifications on the aforementioned quantities of interest using the non-intrusive Multi-Level Monte Carlo method coupled with our multicomponent flow solver.","begin_time":"13:00","begin_timestamp":"1522234800","end_time":"13:30","end_timestamp":"1522236600","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa126","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Fabian","last_name":"Wermelinger","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa126","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Fabian","last_name":"Wermelinger","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa126","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Petros","last_name":"Koumoutsakos","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Numerical Simulations and Robust Predictions of Cloud Cavitation Collapse</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Fabian Wermelinger (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa126","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Fabian","last_name":"Wermelinger","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We will present large-scale simulations of free-field cloud collapses with up to O(10k) resolved gas bubbles. This large number of resolved bubbles is necessary in order to collect meaningful statistics. We will provide detailed insight into the collapse process that starts from the outer surface of the cloud and propagates inwards in the form of a pressure, velocity, and bubble deformation wave. Furthermore, we will address comparisons to simplified models, in particular, Rayleigh-Plesset-like equations. Additionally, we will also quantify uncertainties in peak pressures and micro-jet formation of clouds under random initial bubble locations and radii. These degrees of randomness manifest themselves in a wide range of peak pressures. We will show uncertainty quantifications on the aforementioned quantities of interest using the non-intrusive Multi-Level Monte Carlo method coupled with our multicomponent flow solver. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa137"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
