	</script><div class="title">Scalable Implicit Flow Solver for Realistic Wing Simulations with Flow Control</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michel Rasquin (Cenaero, Belgium)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa137","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Rasquin","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The open source code PHASTA is a parallel, hierarchic (2nd to 5th order accurate), adaptive, stabilized (finite-element) transient analysis tool for the solution of compressible or incompressible flows. This code was extended under an ALCF Early Science project to scale well to over 3M IBM BG/Q processes using a 92 billion element fully unstructured, adapted mesh. This talk will chronicle some of the lessons learned in that effort and discuss new challenges that are being faced in similar ALCF Early Science projects to extend this code to the next ALCF machines (Theta, already in service, and Aurora, the exascale pathway machine that will follow it). Both machines are based on Intel Xeon Phi processors. While prevailing wisdom suggests that algorithms will have to radically change between BG/Q and Phi, early simulations with PHASTA on Phi suggest that flexible versions of existing algorithms still scale surprisingly well. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa141"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa141","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Developing Discontinuous Galerkin Methods for Large Eddy Simulation of Multistage Turbomachinery","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The discontinuous Galerkin method (DGM) combines very high accuracy on low-quality unstructured meshes with excellent computational performance. It furthermore offers a flexible framework for adaptivity, and maintains full accuracy near boundaries and sliding interfaces. The precision, geometric flexibility, and efficiency make DGM a prime candidate for enabling the reliable and accurate use of adaptive Large Eddy Simulation (LES) for industrial design. This talk will discuss the essential steps and perspectives in the development of a new DGM solver named Argo and developed at Cenaero for Large Eddy Simulations of multistage turbomachinery flows. This talk will focus in particular on the most recent efforts geared towards (i) the assessment of the Argo solver for transonic flow and (ii) the accurate efficient implementation and scalability of rotor-stator sliding interfaces for large-scale computations on the BG\/Q system at the Argonne National Leadership Facility.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Rasquin","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Rasquin","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jean-S\u00e9bastien","last_name":"Cagnone","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Koen","last_name":"Hillewaert","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"0"}]}