	</script><div class="title">Developing Discontinuous Galerkin Methods for Large Eddy Simulation of Multistage Turbomachinery</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michel Rasquin (Cenaero, Belgium)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Rasquin","affiliation":"Cenaero","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The discontinuous Galerkin method (DGM) combines very high accuracy on low-quality unstructured meshes with excellent computational performance. It furthermore offers a flexible framework for adaptivity, and maintains full accuracy near boundaries and sliding interfaces. The precision, geometric flexibility, and efficiency make DGM a prime candidate for enabling the reliable and accurate use of adaptive Large Eddy Simulation (LES) for industrial design. This talk will discuss the essential steps and perspectives in the development of a new DGM solver named Argo and developed at Cenaero for Large Eddy Simulations of multistage turbomachinery flows. This talk will focus in particular on the most recent efforts geared towards (i) the assessment of the Argo solver for transonic flow and (ii) the accurate efficient implementation and scalability of rotor-stator sliding interfaces for large-scale computations on the BG/Q system at the Argonne National Leadership Facility. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa173"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa173","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Scale-Resolving Simulations with SU2 for Wind Engineering Applications","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The open source suite of C++ codes, SU2, for aerodynamic design consists of an unstructured mesh finite volume (FV) solver and a Discontinuous Galerkin finite element (DG_FE) higher-order solver for compressible flows. The code is designed to exploit the SIMD parallelism on large vector registers, thread level parallelism that is available on the large number of cores per compute node and the hardware threads per core, in addition to MPI, which facilitates the data movement between compute nodes. The SU2 flow solver has been applied to large eddy simulations for problems in wind engineering involving flow over airfoils and the atmospheric boundary layer over canonical terrain geometries. This talk presents the scaling and performance of SU2 on the IBM BG\/Q and Intel Xeon Phi platforms, and the results of the LES that have been carried out with the FV and DG solvers.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa173","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ramesh","last_name":"Balakrishnan","affiliation":"Argonne National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa173","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ramesh","last_name":"Balakrishnan","affiliation":"Argonne National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa173","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Juan","last_name":"Alonso","affiliation":"Stanford University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa173","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Economon","affiliation":"Stanford University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{