	</script><div class="title">Grid: A Data Parallel Structured Cartesian Framework for Lattice QCD Calculations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Peter Boyle (University of Edinburgh, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa206","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Peter","last_name":"Boyle","affiliation":"University of Edinburgh","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We discuss the motivation, implementation details, and performance of a new physics code base called Grid. It is intended to be more performant, more general, but similar in spirit to QDP++. Our approach is to engineer the basic type system to be consistently fast, rather than bolt on a few optimised routines, and we attempt to write all our optimised routines directly in the Grid framework. It is hoped this will deliver best known practice performance across the next generation of supercomputers, which will provide programming challenges to traditional scalar codes. We illustrate the programming patterns used to implement our goals, and advances in productivity that have been enabled by using new features in C++11.Initial results are presented on Broadwell and Knight's Landing with both Intel Omnipath and Cray Aries interconnects. Techniques for maximising delivered communication bandwidth in the Halo Exchange by using MPI3 features are discussed. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa205"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa205","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Modernizing Code for the Intel \u0022Knights Landing\u0022 Processor: Real World Tales from the IXPUG Trenches","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Successful exploitation of new computing devices with high parallelism comes with an increased need to expose more task, data and pipeline parallelism at the algorithmic level, as well as the need to significantly reduce data movement by making more effective use of cache. With these challenges in mind, there is a renewed demand for advances in performance analysis tools to provide a clearer view on where performance bottlenecks lie. An overview will be provided of how one such technique, the cache-aware roofline model (CARM), can facilitate deeper insight into performance challenges on the Knights Landing processor. We propose a deep dive on how the CARM has guided optimizations on Reverse Time Migration (RTM) kernels at ICHEC, as well as a wider perspective on how tools-aided approaches to the roofline methodology are being employed by several members of the Intel Xeon Phi User Group (IXPUG) on real-world applications.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa205","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Lysaght","affiliation":"Intel Inc.","country":"Ireland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa205","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Lysaght","affiliation":"Intel Inc.","country":"Ireland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Modernizing Code for the Intel "Knights Landing" Processor: Real World Tales from the IXPUG Trenches</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michael Lysaght (Intel Inc., Ireland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa205","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Lysaght","affiliation":"Intel Inc.","country":"Ireland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Successful exploitation of new computing devices with high parallelism comes with an increased need to expose more task, data and pipeline parallelism at the algorithmic level, as well as the need to significantly reduce data movement by making more effective use of cache. With these challenges in mind, there is a renewed demand for advances in performance analysis tools to provide a clearer view on where performance bottlenecks lie. An overview will be provided of how one such technique, the cache-aware roofline model (CARM), can facilitate deeper insight into performance challenges on the Knights Landing processor. We propose a deep dive on how the CARM has guided optimizations on Reverse Time Migration (RTM) kernels at ICHEC, as well as a wider perspective on how tools-aided approaches to the roofline methodology are being employed by several members of the Intel Xeon Phi User Group (IXPUG) on real-world applications. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa211"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa211","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"FPGA Acceleration for High-Throughput Data Processing in High-Energy Physics Experiments","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The LHCb experiment at CERN will upgrade its detector by 2018\/2019 to a \u0027triggerless\u0027 readout scheme, where all the readout electronics - able to read out the detector at 40MHz - and several sub-detector parts will be replaced. This increases the data bandwidth from the detector down to the event filter farm to 40TBit\/s. The architecture of such a computing farm is a challenging task and several compute accelerator technologies are being considered for use inside the new event filter farm. In designing the architecture of such a computing farm, the usage of the Intel platform hosting a general Xeon CPU and a high performance Arria 10 FPGA inside a multi-chip package linked via a high speed and low latency link is being tested. A computing intensive algorithm was successfully ported to the Intel(r) Xeon(r)\/FPGA platform and accelerated; Verilog and OpenCL kernels are compared in performance and development time.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa211","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christian","last_name":"Faerber","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa211","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christian","last_name":"Faerber","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">FPGA Acceleration for High-Throughput Data Processing in High-Energy Physics Experiments</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Christian Faerber (CERN, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa211","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christian","last_name":"Faerber","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The LHCb experiment at CERN will upgrade its detector by 2018/2019 to a 'triggerless' readout scheme, where all the readout electronics - able to read out the detector at 40MHz - and several sub-detector parts will be replaced. This increases the data bandwidth from the detector down to the event filter farm to 40TBit/s. The architecture of such a computing farm is a challenging task and several compute accelerator technologies are being considered for use inside the new event filter farm. In designing the architecture of such a computing farm, the usage of the Intel platform hosting a general Xeon CPU and a high performance Arria 10 FPGA inside a multi-chip package linked via a high speed and low latency link is being tested. A computing intensive algorithm was successfully ported to the Intel(r) Xeon(r)/FPGA platform and accelerated; Verilog and OpenCL kernels are compared in performance and development time. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess190-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess190" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS07 Scientific and High Performance Computing for Applied Life Sciences and Precision Medicine</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 005</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new