		{"id":"symp138","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tom","last_name":"Vander Aa","affiliation":"IMEC","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Emerging Domains in HPC, Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The applied life sciences are of huge importance, both economically (the pharmaceutical sector alone supplies something like 30% of the exports of Switzerland), and in terms of tackling societal challenges such as aging populations, the increasing burden of chronic diseases, and spiraling costs of health care. The challenges in the industry are many and varied, and include the need for a much better understanding of why certain promising drugs fail trials, how best to identify and model sub-groups in patient populations to deliver on the promises of precision medicine, and how to integrate information and models ranging from the molecular level up to patient-worn sensors.<br /><br />Due to their importance, the applied life sciences should be supported with the best possible tools to tackle these challenges. Whilst the use of computing is reasonably well established in this sector, the use of High-Performance Computing (HPC) is much less well established when compared to other sectors such as engineering or physics. This is indeed unfortunate given the potential of in silico experiments and analysis of complex data to advance the state of the art in the field and deliver concrete benefits to society.<br /><br />In this minisymposium we will explore various approaches to the use of computing for the applied life sciences, ranging from lower-level systems modeling, through the application of large-scale machine learning to high volume screens in drug discovery, to analysis of genomic information. Each of these has different modeling and scaling challenges and has had varying levels of success in the application of HPC to the problem. We will have speakers from industry, academia and industrial-academic collaborations alike, giving varying perspectives on the state of the art and the potential for the application of HPC. <br /><br />The specific areas covered by the speakers will be the following:<br />- HPC implementation of multi-target compound activity prediction in chemogenomics based on state of the art large scale machine learning techniques<br />- Challenges in data handling and computation for the analysis of DNA for personalized healthcare<br />- Systems biology and HPC</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa170"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:00 - 13:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa170","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Federated Analysis of Genomes for Personalized Healthcare","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In precision medicine, healthcare is tailored for individuals with unique profiles rather than imposed on them based on average responses of large patient cohorts. To develop and choose the right treatments for the right patients, Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) experiments are being performed on the genomes, transcriptomes and epigenomes of hundreds of thousands of individuals. However, the prohibitively large size and worldwide dispersion of NGS data often prevent researchers from performing aggregated analyses and can undermine the reproducibility of results. To solve these challenges, Roche is integrating NGS data sets by developing a modular and lean platform that leverages open standards, virtualizes file systems and processing pipelines, and supports data provenance. This model also lends itself to storage and analysis of medical images. Our system will link HPC platforms on two continents, enable reuse of precious data sets for exploratory research, and foster collaboration within a large in-house scientific community.","begin_time":"13:00","begin_timestamp":"1522234800","end_time":"13:30","end_timestamp":"1522236600","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa170","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Satu","last_name":"Nahkuri","affiliation":"Roche","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa170","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Satu","last_name":"Nahkuri","affiliation":"Roche","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa170","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Marc","last_name":"Litherland","affiliation":"Roche","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Federated Analysis of Genomes for Personalized Healthcare</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Satu Nahkuri (Roche, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa170","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Satu","last_name":"Nahkuri","affiliation":"Roche","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In precision medicine, healthcare is tailored for individuals with unique profiles rather than imposed on them based on average responses of large patient cohorts. To develop and choose the right treatments for the right patients, Next Generation Sequencing (NGS) experiments are being performed on the genomes, transcriptomes and epigenomes of hundreds of thousands of individuals. However, the prohibitively large size and worldwide dispersion of NGS data often prevent researchers from performing aggregated analyses and can undermine the reproducibility of results. To solve these challenges, Roche is integrating NGS data sets by developing a modular and lean platform that leverages open standards, virtualizes file systems and processing pipelines, and supports data provenance. This model also lends itself to storage and analysis of medical images. Our system will link HPC platforms on two continents, enable reuse of precious data sets for exploratory research, and foster collaboration within a large in-house scientific community. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa159"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa159","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"HPC for Inferring Causal Biological Networks","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Inference of mechanistic, causal models for biological systems is challenging both theoretically and computationally because limited knowledge and data often require one to address structural (regarding the governing dynamic equations) and parametric uncertainties simultaneously. The talk discusses these challenges for dynamical systems (models) and associated opportunities for HPC. Specific approaches to be addressed are: (i) numerical methods to characterize uncertainties in high-dimensional parameter spaces based on polynomial approximations; (ii) Bayesian inference of model structures that relies on projections in parameter space instead of a (combinatorially complex) enumeration of all possible models; and (iii) coarse-graining of this approach when only patterns of interactions in a network are of primary interest. Molecular-level examples will link to potential applications in precision medicine.","begin_time":"13:30","begin_timestamp":"1522236600","end_time":"14:00","end_timestamp":"1522238400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa159","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Joerg","last_name":"Stelling","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa159","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Joerg","last_name":"Stelling","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">HPC for Inferring Causal Biological Networks</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Joerg Stelling (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa159","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Joerg","last_name":"Stelling","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Inference of mechanistic, causal models for biological systems is challenging both theoretically and computationally because limited knowledge and data often require one to address structural (regarding the governing dynamic equations) and parametric uncertainties simultaneously. The talk discusses these challenges for dynamical systems (models) and associated opportunities for HPC. Specific approaches to be addressed are: (i) numerical methods to characterize uncertainties in high-dimensional parameter spaces based on polynomial approximations; (ii) Bayesian inference of model structures that relies on projections in parameter space instead of a (combinatorially complex) enumeration of all possible models; and (iii) coarse-graining of this approach when only patterns of interactions in a network are of primary interest. Molecular-level examples will link to potential applications in precision medicine. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa278"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa278","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Practical Experience with Software for Next-Generation Sequence Analyses in HPC Environment","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Recent advances in DNA sequencing technologies significantly changed our understanding of genomic content of living organisms and their evolution. The talk will give a brief overview of current state-of-the-art software tools used for raw DNA sequence processing, genome assembly, single-nucleotide polymorphism detection, filtering and further analyses. The software tools are usually memory-bound and have highly variable resource requirements, are often written in higher-level languages while much less in C or C++. Only a handful use MPI or threads at the best. The talk will show several examples of CPU- or memory-hungry applications. The last part of the talk will give a brief description about the technology for remote execution of the before mentioned bioinformatics tools on a supercomputer infrastructure directly from the user interface of the client application without the necessity to connect directly to the HPC cluster and manage the jobs from the command line interface.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa278","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Mokrej\u0161","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa278","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Mokrej\u0161","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa278","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jan","last_name":"Martinovi\u010d","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Practical Experience with Software for Next-Generation Sequence Analyses in HPC Environment</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Martin Mokrejš (TU Ostrava, Czech Republic)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
