	</script><div class="title">Waveform Tomography for Breast Cancer Detection with Ultrasound</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Christian Boehm (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa250","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christian","last_name":"Boehm","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Ultrasound waveform tomography is a promising method for imaging and characterizing breast tissue, but it remains computationally challenging especially when considering 3D scanning systems and high frequencies. Despite the vastly different scale, ultrasound tomography shares a remarkable amount of similarities with seismic imaging. In this presentation we show how tools from computational seismology can be transferred successfully to medical imaging. In particular, we discuss models and algorithmic strategies for the following steps towards creating a tomographic image of the human breast. First, a cost-effective acquisition geometry of sending and receiving ultrasound transducers is determined using experimental design. Second, we image sound speed using a ray-based method to create an initial reconstruction. In a third step, we improve the resolution of the image using waveform inversion governed by the acoustic wave equation. Here, we apply stochastic descent methods to efficiently solve the inverse problem and present numerical examples using Salvus. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa273"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa273","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Scalable Wave Propagation in Multiscale Media Based on a Pseudospectral\/Spectral-Element Method with Particle Relabeling","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present a new numerical method to simulate seismic wave propagation in 3-D Earth models and finite boundary perturbations. Our method is a hybrid of pseudo-spectral and spectral element methods. We characterize the azimuthal wavefield dependence in terms of Fourier series, such that 3-D equations of motion reduce to an algebraic system of coupled 2-D meridional equations solved by a 2-D spectral element method. Computational efficiency of our method stems from lateral smoothness of Earth models which confine Fourier modes to few lower orders. Non-spherical boundary perturbations are considered by a Particle Relabeling Transformation. The MPI-based C++ code AxiSEM3D is available for 3-D models with fluid core, ellipticity, and both mantle and crustal structures. We show benchmarks for wave solutions in 3-D structures between AxiSEM3D and SPECFEM3D with remarkable agreement. Parallelization requires sophisticated load balancing due to locally varying Fourier expansion. The code scales excellently up to 13,000 cores (ARCHER).","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa273","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tarje","last_name":"Nissen-Meyer","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa273","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tarje","last_name":"Nissen-Meyer","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa273","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Kuangdai","last_name":"Leng","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},{"