	</script><div class="title">Scalable Wave Propagation in Multiscale Media Based on a Pseudospectral/Spectral-Element Method with Particle Relabeling</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Tarje Nissen-Meyer (University of Oxford, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa273","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tarje","last_name":"Nissen-Meyer","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present a new numerical method to simulate seismic wave propagation in 3-D Earth models and finite boundary perturbations. Our method is a hybrid of pseudo-spectral and spectral element methods. We characterize the azimuthal wavefield dependence in terms of Fourier series, such that 3-D equations of motion reduce to an algebraic system of coupled 2-D meridional equations solved by a 2-D spectral element method. Computational efficiency of our method stems from lateral smoothness of Earth models which confine Fourier modes to few lower orders. Non-spherical boundary perturbations are considered by a Particle Relabeling Transformation. The MPI-based C++ code AxiSEM3D is available for 3-D models with fluid core, ellipticity, and both mantle and crustal structures. We show benchmarks for wave solutions in 3-D structures between AxiSEM3D and SPECFEM3D with remarkable agreement. Parallelization requires sophisticated load balancing due to locally varying Fourier expansion. The code scales excellently up to 13,000 cores (ARCHER). </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa257"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa257","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"A Spectral Finite Element Discretisation for Elastodynamics on Unstructured Triangle and Tetrahedral Meshes","scientific_track":"","abstract":"I will describe a continuous Galerkin spectral-element discretisation defined over triangles, or tetrahedra. The method uses a stable nodal basis and retains the accuracy and low dispersive properties of the classical SEM. However, the discretisation results in a non-diagonal mass matrix. I will describe an efficient preconditioned Krylov solver for the mass matrix operators which is robust with respect to the polynomial order, and possesses high arithmetic intensity. I will also describe a p-multigrid preconditioner which is effective for operators arising from implicit time-integrators. Implicit methods become relevant when using geometries defined by poor quality meshes, or if they contain elements with a wide range of length scales. The applicability of the new method will be demonstrated via several two- and three-dimensional wave-propagation scenarios. These scenarios will characterise the accuracy and cost of the method. Lastly, I will assess the potential benefits of using implicit time-integrators for regional-scale wave-propagation simulations.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa257","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa257","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa257","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alice-Agnes","last_name":"Gabriel","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">A Spectral Finite Element Discretisation for Elastodynamics on Unstructured Triangle and Tetrahedral Meshes</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dave A. May (University of Oxford, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa257","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> I will describe a continuous Galerkin spectral-element discretisation defined over triangles, or tetrahedra. The method uses a stable nodal basis and retains the accuracy and low dispersive properties of the classical SEM. However, the discretisation results in a non-diagonal mass matrix. I will describe an efficient preconditioned Krylov solver for the mass matrix operators which is robust with respect to the polynomial order, and possesses high arithmetic intensity. I will also describe a p-multigrid preconditioner which is effective for operators arising from implicit time-integrators. Implicit methods become relevant when using geometries defined by poor quality meshes, or if they contain elements with a wide range of length scales. The applicability of the new method will be demonstrated via several two- and three-dimensional wave-propagation scenarios. These scenarios will characterise the accuracy and cost of the method. Lastly, I will assess the potential benefits of using implicit time-integrators for regional-scale wave-propagation simulations. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa287"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa287","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"GeoPC: Composable Solvers for Geophysics on Modern Architectures","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We describe recent work within the GeoPC PASC project, synthesizing software components into a geophysical application. This work demonstrates the incorporation of several modern computational components into the application code pTatin3D for lithospheric dynamics. Our focus is to run realistic simulations at high efficiency on the Piz Daint supercomputer, leveraging its hybrid compute nodes to solve the nonlinear Stokes equations with complex rheologies. Components discussed include pipelined (communication-hiding) Krylov methods, processor agglomeration via a reusable component, GPU-enabled subsolves, and GPU-accelerated multigrid smoothing. We share our lessons learned as a result of undertaking an ambitious co-design project, and current practical results within a high-resolution rifting simulation will be discussed.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa287","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Patrick","last_name":"Sanan","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa287","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Patrick","last_name":"Sanan","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa287","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa287","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Karl","last_name":"Rupp","affiliation":"TU Wien","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa287","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Olaf","last_name":"Schenk","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0