	</script><div class="title">Phase-Field Based Simulations of Embryonic Branching Morphogenesis</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Lucas D. Wittwer (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa277","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Lucas D.","last_name":"Wittwer","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The mechanism that controls embryonic branching is not fully understood. Of all proposed mechanisms, only a Turing pattern-based model succeeds in predicting the location of newly emerging branches during lung and kidney branching morphogenesis. Turing models are based on at least two coupled non-linear reaction-diffusion equations. In case of the lung model, the two components (ligands and receptors) are produced in two different tissue layers. Thus the ligand is produced in the outer mesenchymal layer and the receptor is produced in the inner, branching epithelial layer; the diffusion of receptors is restricted to this epithelial layer. So far, numerical instabilities due to highly complex mesh deformations limit the maximal rounds of branching that can be simulated in an ALE-based framework. I will present our new Phase-Field-based framework for simulating embryonic lung morphogenesis and how we coupled the reaction-diffusion equations to the implicit domain. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa209"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa209","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Virtual Erythrocyte: Constitutive Relations and Fluid\u00adcell Interactions","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Erythrocyte is a membrane separating two liquids. We focus on low Reynolds number flows which are relatively easy to model. The erythrocyte behavior is complex because of the membrane mechanics and its interactions with liquids. For a thin membrane, the motion is controlled by no slip with the external and the internal liquids, and Newton\u2019s law \u2013 zero sum of liquid stresses, membrane stresses and acceleration. For Newtonian or Bingham solid membranes, if the membrane is kept spherical, the analytical solutions are known. In reality, the erythrocytes stress is a function of local strain and strain rate. We use particle methods to model erythrocyte. The advantage is the easy introduction of constitutive relationship, by prescribing interactions on a particle level. However there is no a-priori connection to macroscopic laws. We assess constitutive relations and fluid-membrane interactions, by comparing results with analytical solutions and experiments, using sensitivity analysis and uncertainty quantification.","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa209","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey","last_name":"Litvinov","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa209","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey","last_name":"Litvinov","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Virtual Erythrocyte: Constitutive Relations and Fluid­cell Interactions</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sergey Litvinov (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa209","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey","last_name":"Litvinov","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Erythrocyte is a membrane separating two liquids. We focus on low Reynolds number flows which are relatively easy to model. The erythrocyte behavior is complex because of the membrane mechanics and its interactions with liquids. For a thin membrane, the motion is controlled by no slip with the external and the internal liquids, and Newton’s law – zero sum of liquid stresses, membrane stresses and acceleration. For Newtonian or Bingham solid membranes, if the membrane is kept spherical, the analytical solutions are known. In reality, the erythrocytes stress is a function of local strain and strain rate. We use particle methods to model erythrocyte. The advantage is the easy introduction of constitutive relationship, by prescribing interactions on a particle level. However there is no a-priori connection to macroscopic laws. We assess constitutive relations and fluid-membrane interactions, by comparing results with analytical solutions and experiments, using sensitivity analysis and uncertainty quantification. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa280"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa280","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Cell Monolayer Mechanics and Acomys Spine Morphogenesis","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this presentation, we introduce a 2D vertex model that we developed (based on Farhadifar et al., Curr. Biol., 2007)  to simulate cell monolayers. The model includes cells\u2019 mechanical properties, proliferation and signalling. It was used to study how cell biophysics affect the mechanical response of tissues to stretching, and inversely how tissue stretching may affect the mechanical properties of cells (Merzouki et al., Soft Matter, 2016). We simulated tissue stretching and calibrated our model parameters using the experimental stress-strain results of Harris et al., PNAS, 2012. We found that the parameters must vary with the tissue strain to be in agreement with the experiments. Finally, we also use the model to study the morphogenesis of Acomys Dimidiatus spines (Montandon et al., EvoDevo, 2014). We investigate how the signal that is produced by the Dermal Papilla cells and drives Matrix cell proliferation, may determine the final morphology of the follicles.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa280","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Aziza","last_name":"Merzouki","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa280","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Aziza","last_name":"Merzouki","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Cell Monolayer Mechanics and Acomys Spine Morphogenesis</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Aziza Merzouki (University of Geneva, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa280","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Aziza","last_name":"Merzouki","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this presentation, we introduce a 2D vertex model that we developed (based on Farhadifar et al., Curr. Biol., 2007) to simulate cell monolayers. The model includes cells’ mechanical properties, proliferation and signalling. It was used to study how cell biophysics affect the mechanical response of tissues to stretching, and inversely how tissue stretching may affect the mechanical properties of cells (Merzouki et al., Soft Matter, 2016). We simulated tissue stretching and calibrated our model parameters using the experimental stress-strain results of Harris et al., PNAS, 2012. We found that the parameters must vary with the tissue strain to be in agreement with the experiments. Finally, we also use the model to study the morphogenesis of Acomys Dimidiatus spines (Montandon et al., EvoDevo, 2014). We investigate how the signal that is produced by the Dermal Papilla cells and drives Matrix cell proliferation, may determine the final morphology of the follicles. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa289"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa289","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"LBIBCell: A Cell-Based Simulation Framework to Explore the Impact of Cell Mechanics on Tissue Organisation and Growth","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Our group has recently developed the 2D software framework, LBIBCell, to enable data-based simulations of tissue dynamics at cellular resolution. LBIBCell provides a very detailed simulation framework that represents the fluid-structure interaction between the elastic cell boundaries of the highly resolved polygonal cell geometries and the fluid inside and outside the cells. In the talk, I will introduce the software and present two examples of simulating epithelial tissue dynamics. Epithelia constitute the building blocks of organs throughout animals. Epithelial cells tightly adhere to their neighbours such that their apical surfaces form a polygonal lattice. The at-first-sight random arrangement of polygons exhibits some intriguing structure, and I will show how LBIBCell can be used to determine the underlying mechanism that gives rise to the observed order. Moreover, I will show how the software can be used to explore the impact of cell mechanics on growth pattern in epithelial tubes.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa289","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dagmar","last_name":"Iber","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa289","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dagmar","last_name":"Iber","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">LBIBCell: A Cell-Based Simulation Framework to Explore the Impact of Cell Mechanics on Tissue Organisation and Growth</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dagmar Iber (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa289","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dagmar","last_name":"Iber","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Our group has recently developed the 2D software framework, LBIBCell, to enable data-based simulations of tissue dynamics at cellular resolution. LBIBCell provides a very detailed simulation framework that represents the fluid-structure interaction between the elastic cell boundaries of the highly resolved polygonal cell geometries and the fluid inside and outside the cells. In the talk, I will introduce the software and present two examples of simulating epithelial tissue dynamics. Epithelia constitute the building blocks of organs throughout animals. Epithelial cells tightly adhere to their neighbours such that their apical surfaces form a polygonal lattice. The at-first-sight random arrangement of polygons exhibits some intriguing structure, and I will show how LBIBCell can be used to determine the underlying mechanism that gives rise to the observed order. Moreover, I will show how the software can be used to explore the impact of cell mechanics on growth pattern in epithelial tubes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess178-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess178" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS10 Enabling Exascale Fluid Dynamics Simulations</strong>, Room B2</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="ena