	</script><div class="title">Towards Adaptive Meshes for the Spectral Element Code Nek5000</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Philipp Schlatter (Royal Institute of Technology, Sweden)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa217","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Philipp","last_name":"Schlatter","affiliation":"Royal Institute of Technology","country":"Sweden","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> When performing computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations, the expected flow physics is often unknown. For this reason, the generation of a high-quality mesh is a complextask and is usually considered as a bottle-neck for any user of a CFD code. Ideally, the mesh should avoid unnecessary over-resolution in unimportant regions and require as few computational resources as possible. Adaptive mesh refinement (AMR) techniques have been developed to tackle this issue by, first, identifying poorly resolved regions with effective error estimators and then, applying a mesh refinement strategy. In the present work, we propose to implement non-conforming mesh refinement within the code Nek5000: an open-source, highly scalable and portable code based on the spectral element method (SEM). We apply our techniques first to 2D flow configurations together with spectral and adjoint error estimators. In addition, we present an effective preconditioning using the Hypre library. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa260"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa260","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Delivering Performance Through HPC","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Engineers commonly use computational fluid dynamics to understand the flow around prototype ideas and refine their designs. In an industry such as Formula One, where 2% of aerodynamics performance is the difference between being 1st and 10th, every design concept is firstly optimised in CFD. There is also an increasing appetite for more advanced CFD models being developed in academia, in particular time-resolved simulations because of the highly transient flow regimes we are dealing with. From our industry perspective, the development time scales also have to be taken into consideration: the full life of one of our race cars is a year, during which four to five major upgrades and their associated changes of aerodynamics concept will be considered. Thus, for time resolved CFD simulations to be accepted within our production process where the time scales are weeks, there is a strong need to be able to scale up simulations.","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa260","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Julien","last_name":"Hoessler","affiliation":"McLaren Racing Ltd","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa260","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Julien","last_name":"Hoessler","affiliation":"McLaren Racing Ltd","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Delivering Performance Through HPC</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Julien Hoessler (McLaren Racing Ltd, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
