	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Engineers commonly use computational fluid dynamics to understand the flow around prototype ideas and refine their designs. In an industry such as Formula One, where 2% of aerodynamics performance is the difference between being 1st and 10th, every design concept is firstly optimised in CFD. There is also an increasing appetite for more advanced CFD models being developed in academia, in particular time-resolved simulations because of the highly transient flow regimes we are dealing with. From our industry perspective, the development time scales also have to be taken into consideration: the full life of one of our race cars is a year, during which four to five major upgrades and their associated changes of aerodynamics concept will be considered. Thus, for time resolved CFD simulations to be accepted within our production process where the time scales are weeks, there is a strong need to be able to scale up simulations. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa227"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa227","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Multilevel Diskless Checksum Checkpoints for Automated Application Recovery","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Multilevel diskless checksum check-pointing is a novel approach for scalable resilience towards hard errors. Multilevel check-pointing has been shown to increase the overall efficiency of scientific codes in comparison with conventional single-stage check-pointing. It decreases the cost of check-pointing and recovery upon failure whilst also reducing the load on the parallel file-system. In this talk, we give a short introduction to the concept of multilevel check-pointing and present our experience implementing multilevel diskless checksum check-pointing in the Nektar++ spectral\/hp element framework code using ULFM MPI. Furthermore, we will show preliminary findings on a novel algorithm for partial information recovery in incomplete checksums.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa227","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Allan","last_name":"Nielsen","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa227","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Allan","last_name":"Nielsen","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa227","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Jan","last_name":"Hesthaven","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Multilevel Diskless Checksum Checkpoints for Automated Application Recovery</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Allan Nielsen (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa227","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Allan","last_name":"Nielsen","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Multilevel diskless checksum check-pointing is a novel approach for scalable resilience towards hard errors. Multilevel check-pointing has been shown to increase the overall efficiency of scientific codes in comparison with conventional single-stage check-pointing. It decreases the cost of check-pointing and recovery upon failure whilst also reducing the load on the parallel file-system. In this talk, we give a short introduction to the concept of multilevel check-pointing and present our experience implementing multilevel diskless checksum check-pointing in the Nektar++ spectral/hp element framework code using ULFM MPI. Furthermore, we will show preliminary findings on a novel algorithm for partial information recovery in incomplete checksums. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa143"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa143","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Targeting the Spectral\/hp Element Method for Exascale Platforms","scientific_track":"","abstract":"As the HPC community looks towards the use of many-core technology to enable the next generation of supercomputers and bring an exascale facility towards becoming reality, there is a need to understand how this new paradigm maps to existing codes and algorithms that can already effectively utilize current generation HPC facilities. In this presentation, we present the approaches currently being undertaken inside the Nektar++ spectral\/hp element framework to tackle this challenging issue. In particular, we will examine some of the key mathematical operations in the spectral\/hp formulation, which form the basis of many scientific and engineering problems, and examine how these can be grouped collectively to make more efficient use of modern hardware. We will show how this collective nature provides a route through which we can tackle the challenge of many-core hardware in our existing codebase.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa143","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"David","last_name":"Moxey","affiliation":"Imperial College London","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa143","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"David","last_name":"Moxey","affiliation":"Imperial College London","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa143","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Chris","last_name":"Cantwell","affiliation":"Imperial College London","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa143","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Mike","last_name":"Kirby","affiliation":"University of Utah","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa143","title":"Prof.",