	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The MPDATA advection dwarf for structured grids is one of the two numerical machineries constituting the EULAG dynamical core of the high-resolution regional COSMO model aimed at Alpine weather prediction. To facilitate development and dissemination, the legacy MPDATA formulation was cast in the form of the independent dwarf with minimal set of the auxiliary subroutines leading to lightweight and flexible structure. The dwarf was equipped with a set of Cartesian and spherical idealized tests for verification against published results to ensure quality. Furthermore, the two versions of the MPDATA scheme were reformulated to expose stencil computations and improve computational intensity. Performance improvement is observed up to 250% and further developments are underway to compare the optimized Fortran with custom-made GPU/Phi implementations, as well as a DSEL GridTools port. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa212"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa212","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Multigrid Preconditioning of Elliptic Operators in High-Performance All-Scale Atmospheric Models","scientific_track":"","abstract":"This paper discusses aspects of bespoke operator preconditioning for an elliptic solver, which forms part of the finite volume module (FVM). FVM is a dynamical core module being developed to be compatible with ECMWF\u2019s Integrated Forecasting System. It is based on a non-hydrostatic solver for compressible Euler equations under gravity on a rotating sphere. FVM employs a non-oscillatory forward in time integrator that relies on MPDATA and a robust non-symmetric Krylov solver, formulated on arbitrary hybrid computational meshes discretising the generalised curvilinear framework of the computational space. In the presented work, FVM utilises hybrid unstructured meshes derived from the octahedral reduced Gaussian grid. In the Krylov solver, the preconditioner encompasses two aspects to address: stiffness due to the anisotropy of the atmosphere using a deflation approach, and stiffness due to the high-resolution horizontal discretisation scheme using multigrid. Theoretical considerations are illustrated with simulations of stratified turbulent flows and baroclinic instability.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa212","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mike","last_name":"Gillard","affiliation":"Loughborough University","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa212","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mike","last_name":"Gillard","affiliation":"Loughborough University","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa212","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Willem","last_name":"Deconinck","affiliation":"ECMWF","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},