	</script><div class="title">Multigrid Preconditioning of Elliptic Operators in High-Performance All-Scale Atmospheric Models</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Mike Gillard (Loughborough University, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa212","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mike","last_name":"Gillard","affiliation":"Loughborough University","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> This paper discusses aspects of bespoke operator preconditioning for an elliptic solver, which forms part of the finite volume module (FVM). FVM is a dynamical core module being developed to be compatible with ECMWF’s Integrated Forecasting System. It is based on a non-hydrostatic solver for compressible Euler equations under gravity on a rotating sphere. FVM employs a non-oscillatory forward in time integrator that relies on MPDATA and a robust non-symmetric Krylov solver, formulated on arbitrary hybrid computational meshes discretising the generalised curvilinear framework of the computational space. In the presented work, FVM utilises hybrid unstructured meshes derived from the octahedral reduced Gaussian grid. In the Krylov solver, the preconditioner encompasses two aspects to address: stiffness due to the anisotropy of the atmosphere using a deflation approach, and stiffness due to the high-resolution horizontal discretisation scheme using multigrid. Theoretical considerations are illustrated with simulations of stratified turbulent flows and baroclinic instability. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa181"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa181","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Parallel-In-Time Integration with PFASST: The Hyperbolic Case","scientific_track":"","abstract":"New parallel algorithms are required to unlock the computing power provided by massively parallel supercomputers for applications in science and engineering. For time-dependent PDEs, the \u0022parallel full approximation scheme in space and time\u0022 (PFASST) can integrate multiple time-steps simultaneously, making use of different space-time coarsening strategies to improve parallel performance. Yet, as it is the case for many other parallel-in-time integration methods, PFASST works best for problems of diffusive type but shows poor performance for hyperbolic equations. In this talk, we briefly discuss previous results and benefits of PFASST and then formulate this algorithm as a multigrid method to provide an easy access to the mathematical analysis. In particular, using a customized local Fourier analysis, this approach allows us to analyze the convergence of PFASST in a semi-analytical manner for linear diffusion and advection, highlighting the difference between those two problems.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa181","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa181","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa181","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniel","last_name":"Ruprecht","affiliation":"University of Leeds","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Parallel-In-Time Integration with PFASST: The Hyperbolic Case</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Robert Speck (Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa181","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> New parallel algorithms are required to unlock the computing power provided by massively parallel supercomputers for applications in science and engineering. For time-dependent PDEs, the "parallel full approximation scheme in space and time" (PFASST) can integrate multiple time-steps simultaneously, making use of different space-time coarsening strategies to improve parallel performance. Yet, as it is the case for many other parallel-in-time integration methods, PFASST works best for problems of diffusive type but shows poor performance for hyperbolic equations. In this talk, we briefly discuss previous results and benefits of PFASST and then formulate this algorithm as a multigrid method to provide an easy access to the mathematical analysis. In particular, using a customized local Fourier analysis, this approach allows us to analyze the convergence of PFASST in a semi-analytical manner for linear diffusion and advection, highlighting the difference between those two problems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess172-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess172" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS12 Fast Numerical Linear Algebra Methods in Isogeometric Analysis</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 205</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox=