		{"id":"symp119","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Stefano","last_name":"Serra Capizzano","affiliation":"Insubria University","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Isogeometric Analysis (IgA) is a recent but well established method for the analysis of problems governed by differential equations. Its goal is to reduce the gap between the worlds of Finite Element Analysis (FEA) and Computer Aided Design (CAD). One of the key ideas in IgA is to use a common spline representation model for the design as well as for the analysis, providing a true design-through-analysis methodology.<br /><br />The IgA approach has been proved to be superior with respect to conventional FEA in various engineering application areas, including structural mechanics, electromagnetism, fluid-structure interaction. The keystones of this success are the many outstanding properties of the considered spline spaces and the associated B-spline basis. Spline representations allow for an efficient (geometric) manipulation, a high approximation power with respect to their degrees of freedom, appealing spectral properties, fast numerical linear algebra methods depending on spectral properties and/or tensor techniques.<br /><br />The minisymposium will address the most recent research directions and results related to <br />1) analysis of spectral properties in concrete applications<br />2) fast numerical linear algebra methods in connection with Bsplines, NURBS, extended spaces, etc.<em> </em></p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa101"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa101","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Symbol Approach in IgA Matrix Analysis: from the Spectral Analysis to the Design of Fast Solvers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Isogeometric Analysis (IgA) is a paradigm for solving PDEs. Any discretization of a PDE for some sequence of stepsizes h tending to zero leads to a sequence of linear systems A_h * x_h = b_h, where dim(A_h) tends to 0 with h. For the solution of such linear systems, it is important to understand the spectral properties of the matrices A_h. In particular, the spectral distribution is a relevant concept. Roughly speaking, saying that the sequence {A_h}_h is distributed like the function f (called the symbol of {A_h}_h) means that the eigenvalues of A_h behave as a uniform sampling of f over its domain. In this talk we discuss the case of stiffness matrices arising from IgA: we compute and analyze their symbol and we use the information contained in the symbol to design a fast multi-iterative solver involving the PCG as a smoother in the multigrid procedure.","begin_time":"15:30","begin_timestamp":"1522243800","end_time":"16:00","end_timestamp":"1522245600","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa101","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Carlo","last_name":"Garoni","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa101","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Carlo","last_name":"Garoni","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Symbol Approach in IgA Matrix Analysis: from the Spectral Analysis to the Design of Fast Solvers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Carlo Garoni (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa101","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Carlo","last_name":"Garoni","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Isogeometric Analysis (IgA) is a paradigm for solving PDEs. Any discretization of a PDE for some sequence of stepsizes h tending to zero leads to a sequence of linear systems A_h * x_h = b_h, where dim(A_h) tends to 0 with h. For the solution of such linear systems, it is important to understand the spectral properties of the matrices A_h. In particular, the spectral distribution is a relevant concept. Roughly speaking, saying that the sequence {A_h}_h is distributed like the function f (called the symbol of {A_h}_h) means that the eigenvalues of A_h behave as a uniform sampling of f over its domain. In this talk we discuss the case of stiffness matrices arising from IgA: we compute and analyze their symbol and we use the information contained in the symbol to design a fast multi-iterative solver involving the PCG as a smoother in the multigrid procedure. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa158"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa158","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"IGA for MagnetoHydroDynamics (MHD) Problems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Many aspects of the large-scale instabilities that appear in a magnetic confined plasma can be well described in the magneto-hydrodynamic (MHD) framework (with additional physics extensions). Solving these equations globally in the complicated geometry of a divertor tokamak or a stellerator is a highly demanding task due to the strong temporal and spatial multi-scale nature of the problem and the anisotropies reaching up to ten orders of magnitude which are introduced by the magnetic field. In general, explicit time integrators are not suitable while the use of implicit methods leads to very ill-conditioned matrices. In this talk we will cover some reduced MHD problems (in 2d and 3d), show different time integrations schemes and study the corresponding linear systems.","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa158","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ahmed","last_name":"Ratnani","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa158","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ahmed","last_name":"Ratnani","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">IGA for MagnetoHydroDynamics (MHD) Problems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Ahmed Ratnani (Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa158","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ahmed","last_name":"Ratnani","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Many aspects of the large-scale instabilities that appear in a magnetic confined plasma can be well described in the magneto-hydrodynamic (MHD) framework (with additional physics extensions). Solving these equations globally in the complicated geometry of a divertor tokamak or a stellerator is a highly demanding task due to the strong temporal and spatial multi-scale nature of the problem and the anisotropies reaching up to ten orders of magnitude which are introduced by the magnetic field. In general, explicit time integrators are not suitable while the use of implicit methods leads to very ill-conditioned matrices. In this talk we will cover some reduced MHD problems (in 2d and 3d), show different time integrations schemes and study the corresponding linear systems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa225"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa225","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Optimal and Robust Multigrid for Isogeometric Analysis","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this talk we focus on the numerical solution of elliptic problems by means of isogeometric analysis. By exploiting specific spectral properties compactly described by a symbol, we are able to design efficient multigrid methods for the fast solution of the related linear systems. Despite the theoretical optimality, the convergence rate of two-grid methods with classical stationary smoothers worsens exponentially as the involved spline degrees increase. With the aid of the symbol, we can give a theoretical interpretation of this exponential worsening. Moreover, a proper factorization of the symbol allows us to develop a preconditioned conjugate gradient smoother, in the spirit of the multi-iterative strategy, that results in a good multigrid convergence rate, independent of both matrix size and spline degree. Numerical experiments confirm the effectiveness of our proposal and the numerical optimality. This is joint work with Marco Donatelli, Carlo Garoni, Carla Manni and Stefano Serra-Capizzano.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa225","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hendrik","last_name":"Speleers","affiliation":"University of Rome Tor Vergata","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa225","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hendrik","last_name":"Speleers","affiliation":"University of Rome Tor Vergata","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Optimal and Robust Multigrid for Isogeometric Analysis</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Hendrik Speleers (University of Rome Tor Vergata, Italy)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa225","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hendrik","last_name":"Speleers","affiliation":"University of Rome Tor Vergata","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this talk we focus on the numerical solution of elliptic problems by means of isogeometric analysis. By exploiting specific spectral properties compactly described by a symbol, we are able to design efficient multigrid methods for the fast solution of the related linear systems. Despite the theoretical optimality, the convergence rate of two-grid methods with classical stationary smoothers worsens exponentially as the involved spline degrees increase. With the aid of the symbol, we can give a theoretical interpretation of this exponential worsening. Moreover, a proper factorization of the symbol allows us to develop a preconditioned conjugate gradient smoother, in the spirit of the multi-iterative strategy, that results in a good multigrid convergence rate, independent of both matrix size and spline degree. Numerical experiments confirm the effectiveness of our proposal and the numerical optimality. This is joint work with Marco Donatelli, Carlo Garoni, Carla Manni and Stefano Serra-Capizzano. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa134"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa134","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Spectral Analysis of the 2D Curl-Curl (Stabilized) Operator with Applications to the Related Iterative Solutions","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this work, we focus on the linear systems of equations arising from a compatible B-Splines discretization based on a discrete De Rham sequence of the 2D (stabilized) curl-curl operator. Such operator arises, e.g., in Time Harmonic Maxwell as well as in the MagnetoHydroDynamics. Our aim is to spectrally analyze the sequence of the coefficient matrices obtained when we refine the discretization mesh. In this view, we first recognize in the structure of the coefficient matrices a two-by-two pattern where each block is a two-level banded almost Toeplitz matrix whose bandwidths grow linearly with the degree of the B-splines. Then, we use the generalized locally Toeplitz theory to identify the so-called symbol of the coefficient matrix-sequence, a function which compactly describes its asymptotic spectral behavior. Finally, we employ the spectral information provided by the symbol to suggest proper iterative strategies for the numerical solution of the involved linear systems.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa134","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mariarosa","last_name":"Mazza","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa134","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mariarosa","last_name":"Mazza","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa134","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ahmed","last_name":"Ratnani","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa134","title":"Pr