	</script><div class="title">Spectral Analysis of the 2D Curl-Curl (Stabilized) Operator with Applications to the Related Iterative Solutions</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Mariarosa Mazza (Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa134","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mariarosa","last_name":"Mazza","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this work, we focus on the linear systems of equations arising from a compatible B-Splines discretization based on a discrete De Rham sequence of the 2D (stabilized) curl-curl operator. Such operator arises, e.g., in Time Harmonic Maxwell as well as in the MagnetoHydroDynamics. Our aim is to spectrally analyze the sequence of the coefficient matrices obtained when we refine the discretization mesh. In this view, we first recognize in the structure of the coefficient matrices a two-by-two pattern where each block is a two-level banded almost Toeplitz matrix whose bandwidths grow linearly with the degree of the B-splines. Then, we use the generalized locally Toeplitz theory to identify the so-called symbol of the coefficient matrix-sequence, a function which compactly describes its asymptotic spectral behavior. Finally, we employ the spectral information provided by the symbol to suggest proper iterative strategies for the numerical solution of the involved linear systems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess169-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess169" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS13 Kinetic Simulations on HPC Platforms for Plasma Physics Applications (1/3): Algorithms</strong>, Room E</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" vie