	</script><div class="title">A Conservative Exponential Integrator for the Drift-Kinetic Model</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Lukas Einkemmer (University of Innsbruck, Austria)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa109","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Lukas","last_name":"Einkemmer","affiliation":"University of Innsbruck","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Splitting methods have been extensively used to solve kinetic equations such as the four-dimensional drift-kinetic model. These methods are attractive as they decompose the full problem into a sequence of lower dimensional advections which are then treated, for example, using a suitable semi-Lagrangian scheme. In this talk we propose a new exponential integrator based numerical approach that removes the most stringent CFL condition from the drift-kinetic equation. This method is computationally cheaper than the traditional splitting approach and is able to conserve mass up to machine precision (owing to an Arakawa type space discretization). Furthermore, we observe superior behavior with respect to the conservation of both the L^2 norm and energy. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa168"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa168","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Time Discretization of a Geometric Electromagnetic Particle-In-Cell Method","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Numerical schemes that preserve the structure of the underlying kinetic equations can provide new insights into the long time behavior of fusion plasmas. In this talk we will present an electromagnetic particle-in-cell solver for the Vlasov-Maxwell equations that preserves at the discrete level the non-canonical Hamiltonian structure of the Vlasov-Maxwell equations. The Maxwell\u0027s equations are discretized by compatible spline finite elements that yield discrete differential operators that retain properties like div curl = 0. Along with a classical particle discretization of the Vlasov equation, this yields a system of differential equations that has a Poisson structure, that is the non-canonical analog of a symplectic structure. We will discuss two time discretization schemes: an explicit Hamiltonian splitting that retains the Poisson structure and an energy-conserving semi-implicit scheme. Both schemes are compared in terms of their computational complexity and their time step restriction.","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa168","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Katharina","last_name":"Kormann","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa168","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Katharina","last_name":"Kormann","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa168","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Kraus","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa168","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":