	</script><div class="title">Time Discretization of a Geometric Electromagnetic Particle-In-Cell Method</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Katharina Kormann (Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa168","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Katharina","last_name":"Kormann","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Numerical schemes that preserve the structure of the underlying kinetic equations can provide new insights into the long time behavior of fusion plasmas. In this talk we will present an electromagnetic particle-in-cell solver for the Vlasov-Maxwell equations that preserves at the discrete level the non-canonical Hamiltonian structure of the Vlasov-Maxwell equations. The Maxwell's equations are discretized by compatible spline finite elements that yield discrete differential operators that retain properties like div curl = 0. Along with a classical particle discretization of the Vlasov equation, this yields a system of differential equations that has a Poisson structure, that is the non-canonical analog of a symplectic structure. We will discuss two time discretization schemes: an explicit Hamiltonian splitting that retains the Poisson structure and an energy-conserving semi-implicit scheme. Both schemes are compared in terms of their computational complexity and their time step restriction. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa167"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa167","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"The Particle-In-Fourier (PIF) Approach Applied to Gyrokinetic Simulations and its Implementation on GPUs","scientific_track":"","abstract":"A widespread method for gyrokinetic simulations relies on the discretization of distribution functions with numerical markers. The electromagnetic field is represented by finite differences or finite elements (Particle-In-Cell, PIC). When simulating large-sized systems, this method encounters performance losses, both locally (intra-CPU) and globally (inter-CPU) because the amount of communicated data increases. Another approach, Particle-In-Fourier (PIF), takes advantage of the anisotropy of the field by representing it in Fourier space, where data is much smaller. One can scale up the system size keeping the number of particles per mode constant, and removing the subdomain decomposition, resulting in a better parallel scalability. The price to pay is the computation of sines and cosines at marker positions instead of low-order polynomials. GPUs are well suited to such high arithmetic intensity. We will show that PIF is advantageous over PIC for cases that do not require too large a number of modes.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa167","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"No\u00e9","last_name":"Ohana","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa167","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"No\u00e9","last_name":"Ohana","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stephan","last_name":"Brunner","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Claudio","last_name":"Gheller","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Jocksch","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Emmanuel","last_name":"Lanti","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Aaron","last_name":"Scheinberg","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa167","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Laurent","last_name":"Villard","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]},"presentation_file":"MS13.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">The Particle-In-Fourier (PIF) Approach Applied to Gyrokinetic Simulations and its Implementation on GPUs</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Noé Ohana (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa167","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"No\u00e9","last_name":"Ohana","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS13.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> A widespread method for gyrokinetic simulations relies on the discretization of distribution functions with numerical markers. The electromagnetic field is represented by finite differences or finite elements (Particle-In-Cell, PIC). When simulating large-sized systems, this method encounters performance losses, both locally (intra-CPU) and globally (inter-CPU) because the amount of communicated data increases. Another approach, Particle-In-Fourier (PIF), takes advantage of the anisotropy of the field by representing it in Fourier space, where data is much smaller. One can scale up the system size keeping the number of particles per mode constant, and removing the subdomain decomposition, resulting in a better parallel scalability. The price to pay is the computation of sines and cosines at marker positions instead of low-order polynomials. GPUs are well suited to such high arithmetic intensity. We will show that PIF is advantageous over PIC for cases that do not require too large a number of modes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa195"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa195","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"InKS, a Programming Model to Decouple Semantics from Optimizations in HPC and its Application to the 6D Semi-Lagrangian Advection Use-Case","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Supercomputer architectures are becoming increasingly complex, and developing high-performance simulations not only requires a deep understanding of the simulated domain but also of complex optimizations. This is made even more difficult due to the coexistence of multiple distinct architectures that evolve quickly. The mix of domain concerns and optimizations in codes leads to complexity and maintenance difficulties. In this talk, we present InKS (independent kernels scheduling), a programming model we design to decouple semantic from optimization choices. It supports the description of the semantics as a set of functions that operate on logically infinite arrays with pragma annotations to specify dependencies. The choices regarding mapping to memory and scheduling can be made independently. We implement a compiler for automatic execution and provide tools to enable optimization specialists to make the best possible choices. We evaluate our approach on a 6D vlasov-poisson solver for which optimizations are critical.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa195","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ksander","last_name":"Ejjaaouani","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa195","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ksander","last_name":"Ejjaaouani","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa195","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Julien","last_name":"Bigot","affiliation":"CEA","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">InKS, a Programming Model to Decouple Semantics from Optimizations in HPC and its Application to the 6D Semi-Lagrangian Advection Use-Case</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Ksander Ejjaaouani (INRIA, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa195","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ksander","last_name":"Ejjaaouani","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Supercomputer architectures are becoming increasingly complex, and developing high-performance simulations not only requires a deep understanding of the simulated domain but also of complex optimizations. This is made even more difficult due to the coexistence of multiple distinct architectures that evolve quickly. The mix of domain concerns and optimizations in codes leads to complexity and maintenance difficulties. In this talk, we present InKS (independent kernels scheduling), a programming model we design to decouple semantic from optimization choices. It supports the description of the semantics as a set of functions that operate on logically infinite arrays with pragma annotations to specify dependencies. The choices regarding mapping to memory and scheduling can be made independently. We implement a compiler for automatic execution and provide tools to enable optimization specialists to make the best possible choices. We evaluate our approach on a 6D vlasov-poisson solver for which optimizations are critical. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess187-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess187" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS14 Machine Learning</strong>, Room B3</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess187"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Michele Ceriotti (EPFL, Switzerland)</span>, <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
