	</script><div class="title">Discerning Causalities in Protein Function using “Inverse” Machine Learning</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sameer Varma (University of South Florida, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa231","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Sameer","last_name":"Varma","affiliation":"University of South Florida","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Machine learning is traditionally used for classifying data. Here we present new developments where we use support vector machines, not for classification, but for repartitioning pre-classified data and for determining causalities in data. These developments provide us with a unique set of solutions to address challenges facing the study of many major protein families, including GPCRs, NTFs, HSPs and Igs. The thermodynamic states of these proteins cannot be differentiated solely on the basis of their representative 3D structures, as inter-state structural differences are small and differences in structural fluctuations also matter. Consequently, their mechanisms cannot be understood in terms of how their 3D structures differ between states, and new methods are required to statistically analyze differences between high-dimensional structural ensembles and also relate differences to function. Our new “inverse” machine learning based solutions accomplish just this, and have begun to provide molecular insights into their underlying mechanisms. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa237"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
