		{"id":"symp132","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Huckle","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>In the minisymposium "Parallel Numerical Linear Algebra" we will present two major problems. The first part concentrates on dense eigenvalue solvers and is based on the work of the ELPA-AEO project. The underlying problems are Hermitian generalized eigenvalue problems and the parallel computation of a large part of the spectrum. The talks will present theoretical results and practical implementations. The second topic is the parallel solution of systems of linear equations. Here, the first talk will consider the parallelization of smoothers in Multigrid methods. The second talk will present parallel preconditioners based on ILU; here, the resulting sparse triangular systems are preconditioned and can be solved iteratively to achieve efficient parallel methods.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa255"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa255","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Improving Scalability and Efficiency of Multigrid Methods by Block-Smoothers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"While multigrid methods show an excellent scaling behavior depending on the number of cores only logarithmically, on large-scale supercomputers this logarithmic dependency is visible. To reduce influence of this dependence, the amount of work being carried out on the coarse levels has to be reduced. This can be achieved by applying aggressive coarsening, effectively reducing the number of coarse levels. While this is easily possible in a geometric multigrid setting, the overall performance of the method will deteriorate, as the size of the coarse space is reduced. To retain a good convergence rate, the smoothing procedure has to be improved. We propose to use block smoothers to accomplish this; at the same time this results in a higher locality of the operations performed and thus in a better exploitation of modern computer architectures.","begin_time":"15:30","begin_timestamp":"1522243800","end_time":"16:00","end_timestamp":"1522245600","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa255","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Bolten","affiliation":"University of Kassel","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa255","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Bolten","affiliation":"University of Kassel","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Improving Scalability and Efficiency of Multigrid Methods by Block-Smoothers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Matthias Bolten (University of Kassel, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa255","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Bolten","affiliation":"University of Kassel","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> While multigrid methods show an excellent scaling behavior depending on the number of cores only logarithmically, on large-scale supercomputers this logarithmic dependency is visible. To reduce influence of this dependence, the amount of work being carried out on the coarse levels has to be reduced. This can be achieved by applying aggressive coarsening, effectively reducing the number of coarse levels. While this is easily possible in a geometric multigrid setting, the overall performance of the method will deteriorate, as the size of the coarse space is reduced. To retain a good convergence rate, the smoothing procedure has to be improved. We propose to use block smoothers to accomplish this; at the same time this results in a higher locality of the operations performed and thus in a better exploitation of modern computer architectures. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa224"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:00 - 16:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa224","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Iterative Parallel Methods for Deriving ILU-type Preconditioners","scientific_track":"","abstract":"ILU-type preconditioners are efficient preconditioners for solving systems of linear equations iteratively. In recent work by E. Chow it had been shown that they can be generated effectively in parallel based on a fixed point equation for (A \u0026#8722; LU )_S = 0 as function f of L and U on pattern S. Here, we generalize this approach to modified ILU and by using Newton\u0027s method for finding the zero of f. Furthermore, ILU preconditioners lead to triangular systems that have to be solved in parallel. Here, we discuss different iterative schemes for solving triangular systems.","begin_time":"16:00","begin_timestamp":"1522245600","end_time":"16:30","end_timestamp":"1522247400","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa224","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Huckle","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa224","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Huckle","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Iterative Parallel Methods for Deriving ILU-type Preconditioners</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Thomas Huckle (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa224","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Huckle","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> ILU-type preconditioners are efficient preconditioners for solving systems of linear equations iteratively. In recent work by E. Chow it had been shown that they can be generated effectively in parallel based on a fixed point equation for (A &#8722; LU )_S = 0 as function f of L and U on pattern S. Here, we generalize this approach to modified ILU and by using Newton's method for finding the zero of f. Furthermore, ILU preconditioners lead to triangular systems that have to be solved in parallel. Here, we discuss different iterative schemes for solving triangular systems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa256"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">16:30 - 17:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa256","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Efficient Reduction of Generalized hpd Eigenproblems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The standard approach for solving dense generalized eigenvalue problems Ax = eBx with hermitian A and hermitian positive definite B first reduces the problem to a standard eigenproblem Cz = ez, where, e.g., C = inv(L) A inv(L*), z = L* x, and L is obtained from a Cholesky decomposition B = L L* with L* being its hermitian transpose. There are several ways to compute C, and parallelized routines for this task are available in the ScaLAPACK, Elemental, and ELPA libraries. We combine ideas from these methods for optimizing data accesses and communication and present additional approaches for increasing the performance.","begin_time":"16:30","begin_timestamp":"1522247400","end_time":"17:00","end_timestamp":"1522249200","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa256","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valeriy","last_name":"Manin","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa256","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valeriy","last_name":"Manin","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa256","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Galgon","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa256","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Sarah","last_name":"Huber","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa256","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Bruno","last_name":"Lang","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Efficient Reduction of Generalized hpd Eigenproblems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Valeriy Manin (University of Wuppertal, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa256","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valeriy","last_name":"Manin","affiliation":"University of Wuppertal","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The standard approach for solving dense generalized eigenvalue problems Ax = eBx with hermitian A and hermitian positive definite B first reduces the problem to a standard eigenproblem Cz = ez, where, e.g., C = inv(L) A inv(L*), z = L* x, and L is obtained from a Cholesky decomposition B = L L* with L* being its hermitian transpose. There are several ways to compute C, and parallelized routines for this task are available in the ScaLAPACK, Elemental, and ELPA libraries. We combine ideas from these methods for optimizing data accesses and communication and present additional approaches for increasing the performance. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa235"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">17:00 - 17:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa235","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Efficient Transformation of the General Eigenproblem with Symmetric Banded Matrices to a Banded Standard Eigenproblem","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The solution of symmetric eigenproblems plays a key role in many computational simulations. Generalized eigenproblems are transformed to a standard problem. This transformation has the drawback that for banded matrices in the generalized eigenproblem the banded structure is not preserved. The matrix of the standard eigenproblem will generally be a full matrix. We followed the ideas of the group of Lang (University of Wuppertal) who modified Crawford\u0027s algorithm and implemented this procedure in the ELPA project. By keeping the banded structure we save one reduction step on the matrix and one backtransformation step for the eigenvectors. This provides a good speedup compared to the standard tranformation procedure with Cholesky factorization.","begin_time":"17:00","begin_timestamp":"1522249200","end_time":"17:30","end_timestamp":"1522251000","session_date":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa235","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Rippl","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa235","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Rippl","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Monday, June 26, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Efficient Transformation of the General Eigenproblem with Symmetric Banded Matrices to a Banded Standard Eigenproblem</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michael Rippl (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa235","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Rippl","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The solution of symmetric eigenproblems plays a key role in many computational simulations. Generalized eigenproblems are transformed to a standard problem. This transformation has the drawback that for banded matrices in the generalized eigenproblem the banded structure is not preserved. The matrix of the standard eigenproblem will generally be a full matrix. We followed the ideas of the group of Lang (University of Wuppertal) who modified Crawford's algorithm and implemented this procedure in the ELPA project. By keeping the banded structure we save one reduction step on the matrix and one backtransformation step for the eigenvectors. This provides a good speedup compared to the standard tranformation procedure with Cholesky factorization. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head simple"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>17:30 - 18:00</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>Coffee Break</strong>, Foyer</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess209-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess209" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>18:00 - 19:00</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>Panel Discussion - Beyond Moore's Law</strong>, Room A</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess209"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="title"><h4>PNL01 Beyond Moore's Law</h4></div> <div class="session-introduction"> <div class="table session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Chair:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="chairs inline"> <div class="author"> John Shalf (Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"1418","bio":"","first_name":"John","last_name":"Shalf","affiliation":"Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","type":"Session Chair"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>By most accounts, we are nearing the limits of conventional photolithography processes. It will be challenging to continue to shrink feature sizes smaller than 5nm and still realize any performance improvement for digital electronics in silicon. At the current rate of development, the purported “End of Moore’s Law” will be reached in the middle to end of next decade.<br /><br />Shrinking the feature sizes of wires and transistors has been the driver for Moore’s Law for the past 5 decades, but what might lie beyond the end of current lithographic roadmaps and how will it affect computing as we know it? Moore’s Law is an economic theory after all, and any option that can make future computing more capable each new generation (by some measure) could continue Moore’s economic theory well into the future.<br /><br />The goal of this panel session is to communicate the options for extending computing beyond the end of our current silicon lithography roadmaps. The correct answers may be found in new ways to extend digital electronics efficiency or capability, or even new models of computation such as neuromorphic and quantum.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="panditem104"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">18:15 - 18:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
