	</script><div class="title">Interior Eigenvalue and Eigenvalue Density Computations in Quantum Physics Applications</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Andreas Alvermann (University of Greifswald, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa153","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Alvermann","affiliation":"University of Greifswald","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Computation of the eigenvalues or spectrum of a Hermitian matrix is a fundamental task in numerical quantum physics. With the advent of topological materials such as graphene, extraction of the interior part of the spectrum has moved into focus. In my talk I will discuss two techniques that address this challenge. The first technique, known as the Kernel Polynomial Method (KPM), allows for the computation of spectral functions, for example, the eigenvalue density, without having to determine individual eigenvalues. The second technique, which we call Chebyshev filter diagonalization (ChebFD), is dedicated to the computation of a large number of interior eigenvalues. Both techniques draw their strength from Chebyshev polynomials and require the respective matrix only through matrix-vector multiplication. After discussion of the algorithmic background of these techniques, including the optimal choice of polynomials, I will address some specific application-related aspects, e.g., how the ChebFD convergence depends on the eigenvalue density. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa186"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa186","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Nonlinear Sakurai-Sugiura Method for Electronic Transport Calculation on KNL Cluster","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Electronic transport calculations require the computation of eigenvalues located in a ring region and their corresponding eigenvectors of a quadratic eigenvalue problem with T-palindromic structure. In this talk, we propose a technique for solving such quadratic problems by using the nonlinear Sakurai-Sugiura method. The proposed method reduces computational costs using a T-palindromic structure and achieves high parallel efficiency by using a contour integral. The performance of the proposed method is evaluated on Knights Landing cluster, Oakforest-PACS, in Japan.","begin_time":"11:30","begin_timestamp":"1522229400","end_time":"12:00","end_timestamp":"1522231200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa186","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tetsuya","last_name":"Sakurai","affiliation":"University of Tsukuba","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa186","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tetsuya","last_name":"Sakurai","affiliation":"University of Tsukuba","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa186","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yasunori","last_name":"Futamura","affiliation":"University of Tsukuba","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa186","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Akira","last_name":"Imakura","affiliation":"University of Tsukuba","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Nonlinear Sakurai-Sugiura Method for Electronic Transport Calculation on KNL Cluster</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Tetsuya Sakurai (University of Tsukuba, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa186","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Tetsuya","last_name":"Sakurai","affiliation":"University of Tsukuba","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Electronic transport calculations require the computation of eigenvalues located in a ring region and their corresponding eigenvectors of a quadratic eigenvalue problem with T-palindromic structure. In this talk, we propose a technique for solving such quadratic problems by using the nonlinear Sakurai-Sugiura method. The proposed method reduces computational costs using a T-palindromic structure and achieves high parallel efficiency by using a contour integral. The performance of the proposed method is evaluated on Knights Landing cluster, Oakforest-PACS, in Japan. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa128"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa128","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Extremely Large Quantum Material Simulations with Novel Linear Algebraic Algorithms and Massively Parallel Supercomputers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"A novel linear-algebraic algorithm realizes extremely large quantum material simulations (electronic state calculations) with 10^8 atoms or 100-nm-scale materials. The mathematical foundation is generalized shifted linear equations ( ( z B \u2013 A ) x = b ), instead of conventional generalized eigenvalue equations ( A y = e B y ) . The method has a highly parallelizable mathematical structure. The fundamental theory is general and is applicable also to other scientific fields.  The benchmark shows an extreme strong scaling and a qualified time-to-solution on the full system of the K computer. The method was demonstrated in a real material research for ultra-flexible (organic) devices that play a crucial role in next-generation Internet-of-Things (IoT) products like display, sensor, and battery. Related methods are also presented. The present contribution shows that an innovative scalable algorithm for a real research problem can appear by the co-design among application, algorithm, and architecture.","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa128","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Takeo","last_name":"Hoshi","affiliation":"Tottori University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa128","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Takeo","last_name":"Hoshi","affiliation":"Tottori University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa128","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yukiya","last_name":"Abe","affiliation":"Tottori University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa128","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tomoya","last_name":"Fukumo