	</script><div class="title">Extremely Large Quantum Material Simulations with Novel Linear Algebraic Algorithms and Massively Parallel Supercomputers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Takeo Hoshi (Tottori University, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa128","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Takeo","last_name":"Hoshi","affiliation":"Tottori University","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> A novel linear-algebraic algorithm realizes extremely large quantum material simulations (electronic state calculations) with 10^8 atoms or 100-nm-scale materials. The mathematical foundation is generalized shifted linear equations ( ( z B – A ) x = b ), instead of conventional generalized eigenvalue equations ( A y = e B y ) . The method has a highly parallelizable mathematical structure. The fundamental theory is general and is applicable also to other scientific fields. The benchmark shows an extreme strong scaling and a qualified time-to-solution on the full system of the K computer. The method was demonstrated in a real material research for ultra-flexible (organic) devices that play a crucial role in next-generation Internet-of-Things (IoT) products like display, sensor, and battery. Related methods are also presented. The present contribution shows that an innovative scalable algorithm for a real research problem can appear by the co-design among application, algorithm, and architecture. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa119"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa119","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Rational and Polynomial Filtering for Eigenvalue Problems and the EVSL Project","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The presentation will begin with an overview of polynomial filtering\ntechniques in the context of spectrum slicing for eigenvalue problem, i.e., the technique of computing slices of the spectrum independently. This general approach can be quite efficient in the situation where the matrix-vector product operation is inexpensive and when a large number of eigenvalues is  sought.  We present an  algorithm  (and package)   that combines the  Lanczos algorithm   with partial reorthogonalization and  polynomial filtering.   An alternative to polynomial filtering that is generating a growing interest is a class of methods that exploit filtering by rational functions.  Here we will argue that the standard way of selecting these rational filters, which is based on using the Cauchy integral, can be substantially improved \u2013 especially when iterative solvers are involved.","begin_time":"12:30","begin_timestamp":"1522233000","end_time":"13:00","end_timestamp":"1522234800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa119","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yousef","last_name":"Saad","affiliation":"University of Minnesota","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa119","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yousef","last_name":"Saad","affiliation":"University of Minnesota","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Rational and Polynomial Filtering for Eigenvalue Problems and the EVSL Project</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Yousef Saad (University of Minnesota, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa119","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yousef","last_name":"Saad","affiliation":"University of Minnesota","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The presentation will begin with an overview of polynomial filteringtechniques in the context of spectrum slicing for eigenvalue problem, i.e., the technique of computing slices of the spectrum independently. This general approach can be quite efficient in the situation where the matrix-vector product operation is inexpensive and when a large number of eigenvalues is sought. We present an algorithm (and package) that combines the Lanczos algorithm with partial reorthogonalization and polynomial filtering. An alternative to polynomial filtering that is generating a growing interest is a class of methods that exploit filtering by rational functions. Here we will argue that the standard way of selecting these rational filters, which is based on using the Cauchy integral, can be substantially improved – especially when iterative solvers are involved. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess196-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess196" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS17 Exascale Solver for Application-Driven Science (2/2): Multigrid</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 205</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess196"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Markus Huber (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp144","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Markus","last_name":"Huber","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>In this series of two minisymposia, a special focus lies on providing a platform for exchanging ideas about scalable, memory-efficient, fast and resilient solving techniques. These characteristics are crucial for science and engineering-driven applications making use of exascale computing like geophysics, astrophysics, aerodynamics, etc. Algorithms in high-performance computing require a rethinking of the standard approaches to ensure on the one hand the full usage of the future computing power, and on the other hand energy-efficiency. A careful implementation of all performance-relevant parts and an intelligent combination with external libraries is fundamental for exascale computation. Multigrid and domain decomposition play an important role in many scientific applications and have often developed ideas separately using the immense compute power of supercomputers. The minisymposia address both communities and focus on exchanging current research progress related to exascale enabled solving techniques.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa132"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:00 - 11:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa132","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Novel Applications of Multigrid Type Methods in Uintah Approaches to Exascale","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The Uintah software at the University of Utah is presently being used to solve a very large simulation problem relating to a clean-coal boiler with a combustion chamber of about 20000 cubic metres. A primary mechanism for heat transfer in such a boiler is thermal radiation. In order to make thermal radiation scale on present and future parallel machines, we adopt a ray-tracing approach coupled to multiple grid levels to reduce the communications costs. We will present an analysis of this approach and demonstrate scaling results on DOE\u0027s Titan computer. We will also explain the challenges that occur when using this method for real live industrial scale problems and how these are overcome on both GPUs and Xeon Phi KNL.","begin_time":"11:00","begin_timestamp":"1522227600","end_time":"11:30","end_timestamp":"1522229400","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa132","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Berzins","affiliation":"University of Utah","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa132","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Berzins","affiliation":"University of Utah","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa132","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alan","last_name":"Humphrey","affiliation":"University of Utah","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"}]},"presentation_file":"MS17.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Novel Applications of Multigrid Type Methods in Uintah Approaches to Exascale</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Martin Berzins (University of Utah, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa132","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Berzins","affiliation":"University of Utah","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS17.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The Uintah software at the University of Utah is presently being used to solve a very large simulation problem relating to a clean-coal boiler with a combustion chamber of about 20000 cubic metres. A primary mechanism for heat transfer in such a boiler is thermal radiation. In order to make thermal radiation scale on present and future parallel machines, we adopt a ray-tracing approach coupled to multiple grid levels to reduce the communications costs. We will present an analysis of this approach and demonstrate scaling results on DOE's Titan computer. We will also explain the challenges that occur when using this method for real live industrial scale problems and how these are overcome on both GPUs and Xeon Phi KNL. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa122"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa122","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Linear Solvers at Scale: Numerical Scalability and Resiliency Inside!","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this talk we will present an algebraic Domain Decomposition solver for general matrices that can be fully algebraically equipped with a coarse space mechanism to be numerically scalable on general SPD systems. While many of these solvers DDM fall in Abstract Schwarz framework, their robustness has often been demonstrated on a case-by-case basis. Extending the GenEO method, we propose a bound for the condition number of all deflated AS methods provided that the coarse grid consists of the assembly of local components that contain low-energy modes of some local operators. We furthermore discuss and illustrate the resiliency capability that can be embedded to address hard faults, exploiting the natural redundancy or the preconditioner to implement recovery; or numerical criteria to detect soft-errors, exploiting spectral bound naturally provided by the coarse space correction. Parallel numerical experiments will be given to illustrate the robustness of the resulting algorithms.","begin_time":"11:30","begin_timestamp":"1522229400","end_time":"12:00","end_timestamp":"1522231200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthieu","last_name":"Kuhn","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthieu","last_name":"Kuhn","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Emmanuel","last_name":"Agullo","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Luc","last_name":"Giraud","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bi