	</script><div class="title">Linear Solvers at Scale: Numerical Scalability and Resiliency Inside!</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Matthieu Kuhn (INRIA, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthieu","last_name":"Kuhn","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this talk we will present an algebraic Domain Decomposition solver for general matrices that can be fully algebraically equipped with a coarse space mechanism to be numerically scalable on general SPD systems. While many of these solvers DDM fall in Abstract Schwarz framework, their robustness has often been demonstrated on a case-by-case basis. Extending the GenEO method, we propose a bound for the condition number of all deflated AS methods provided that the coarse grid consists of the assembly of local components that contain low-energy modes of some local operators. We furthermore discuss and illustrate the resiliency capability that can be embedded to address hard faults, exploiting the natural redundancy or the preconditioner to implement recovery; or numerical criteria to detect soft-errors, exploiting spectral bound naturally provided by the coarse space correction. Parallel numerical experiments will be given to illustrate the robustness of the resulting algorithms. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa156"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa156","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fast and Scalable Multigrid Solver Employing Agglomeration Techniques","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Reaching the exascale computing era, algorithms with optimal complexity such as multigrid methods are essential for exploiting the available parallel compute power. Over the last decade we developed a parallel high-performance multigrid framework called hierarchical hybrid grids (HHG). We focused especially on sophisticated data structures, efficient communication routines, the elimination of serial performance bottlenecks and low-level optimization. Using this well-designed framework, we investigated in the area of curved boundaries, large viscosity contrast problems and complex modeling questions arising from geophysical applications. In this talk, we present our new achievements in reducing communication bottlenecks in coarse level solves, using special agglomeration techniques in combination with robust coarse level solvers of well-elaborated scientific high-performance computing libraries (PETSc and MUMPS). We show scalability results with special focus on time-to-solution on two state-of-the-art petascale supercomputers. In addition, we apply these strategies to a stationary Stokes problem as a typical geophysical test scenario.","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa156","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Markus","last_name":"Huber","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa156","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Markus","last_name":"Huber","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa156","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Simon","last_name":"Bauer","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Ge