	</script><div class="title">Fast and Scalable Multigrid Solver Employing Agglomeration Techniques</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Markus Huber (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa156","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Markus","last_name":"Huber","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Reaching the exascale computing era, algorithms with optimal complexity such as multigrid methods are essential for exploiting the available parallel compute power. Over the last decade we developed a parallel high-performance multigrid framework called hierarchical hybrid grids (HHG). We focused especially on sophisticated data structures, efficient communication routines, the elimination of serial performance bottlenecks and low-level optimization. Using this well-designed framework, we investigated in the area of curved boundaries, large viscosity contrast problems and complex modeling questions arising from geophysical applications. In this talk, we present our new achievements in reducing communication bottlenecks in coarse level solves, using special agglomeration techniques in combination with robust coarse level solvers of well-elaborated scientific high-performance computing libraries (PETSc and MUMPS). We show scalability results with special focus on time-to-solution on two state-of-the-art petascale supercomputers. In addition, we apply these strategies to a stationary Stokes problem as a typical geophysical test scenario. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa129"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa129","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Multigrid Preconditioners for High Order Finite Element Discretisations","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this talk I will describe and examine the performance of a particular type of geometric multigrid preconditioner designed for high-order continuous Galerkin finite element discretisations on meshes of unstructured triangle \/ tetrahedra, and or quadrilateral \/ hexahedral. The construction of the Galerkin coarse grid operators, application of the restriction and prolongation operators and application of the smoother almost entirely rely on purely local operations (element-wise, or over a patch of elements). Such characteristics make the method amenable to hardware accelerators.  Interestingly, the methodology is particularly simple to implement and can be introduced into existing high order finite element software in a non-invasive manner. Through a number of numerical experiments, the versatility and robustness of the preconditioner will be demonstrated.","begin_time":"12:30","begin_timestamp":"1522233000","end_time":"13:00","end_timestamp":"1522234800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa129","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa129","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Multigrid Preconditioners for High Order Finite Element Discretisations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dave A. May (University of Oxford, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa129","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dave A.","last_name":"May","affiliation":"University of Oxford","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this talk I will describe and examine the performance of a particular type of geometric multigrid preconditioner designed for high-order continuous Galerkin finite element discretisations on meshes of unstructured triangle / tetrahedra, and or quadrilateral / hexahedral. The construction of the Galerkin coarse grid operators, application of the restriction and prolongation operators and application of the smoother almost entirely rely on purely local operations (element-wise, or over a patch of elements). Such characteristics make the method amenable to hardware accelerators. Interestingly, the methodology is particularly simple to implement and can be introduced into existing high order finite element software in a non-invasive manner. Through a number of numerical experiments, the versatility and robustness of the preconditioner will be demonstrated. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess174-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess174" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS18 Kinetic Simulations on HPC Platforms for Plasma Physics Applications (2/3): Physics Production Codes</strong>, Room E</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess174"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Stephan Brunner (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp121","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stephan","last_name":"Brunner","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Physics, Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Kinetic simulations play an essential role towards understanding the dynamics of plasmas in the fields of nuclear fusion, laser plasma interaction, and astrophysics. The complexity of kinetic computations, in particular, their high dimensionality and multi-scale nature, lead to exciting challenges in physics, applied mathematics, and computer science. For example, modeling the plasma dynamics close to the edge of magnetic fusion devices requires codes which can flexibly handle complex geometries and implement enhanced gyrokinetic models or fully kinetic descriptions. Modern numerical tools such as multi-scale methods, structure-preserving schemes and isogeometric meshes, therefore, need to be adapted to plasma physics models in order to enhance state-of-the-art kinetic codes. At the same time, new programming models are necessary to prepare codes for the use on emerging heterogeneous HPC systems. This includes vectorization, cache efficient memory organization, task-based parallelism as well as new algorithms that are adapted to modern hardware. This minisymposium shall bring together scientists from physics, applied mathematics, and computer science to discuss current trends in the development of (gyro)kinetic codes.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa151"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:00 - 11:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa151","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Computational Challenges Towards Strong Scaling Gyrokinetic Eulerian Codes at Exa-scale","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Turbulent transport is one of the key issues in fusion science. To address this issue via a five-dimensional gyrokinetic model, the Gyrokinetic Toroidal 5D full-f Eulerian code GT5D has been developed. On the K-computer, inter-node parallelization techniques such as multi-dimensional\/-layer domain decomposition and communication-computation overlap were developed, and strong scaling of GT5D was improved up to 73,728 nodes. This computing power enabled us to study ITER relevant issues such as the plasma size scaling of turbulent transport. However, extensions of GT5D towards burning plasmas including kinetic electrons and multi-species ions require greater computing power. Under the post-K project (Japanese Exa-scale computing project), we have developed computing techniques for next generation platforms such as GPUs and many core processors. In this talk, we discuss computational challenges related to complicated intra-node memory hierarchy and relatively limited inter-node communication performance compared with accelerated computation.","begin_time":"11:00","begin_timestamp":"1522227600","end_time":"11:30","end_timestamp":"1522229400","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa151","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yasuhiro","last_name":"Idomura","affiliation":"Japan Atomic Energy Agency","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa151","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yasuhiro","last_name":"Idomura","affiliation":"Japan Atomic Energy Agency","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Computational Challenges Towards Strong Scaling Gyrokinetic Eulerian Codes at Exa-scale</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Yasuhiro Idomura (Japan Atomic Energy Agency, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa151","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yasuhiro","last_name":"Idomura","affiliation":"Japan Atomic Energy Agency","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Turbulent transport is one of the key issues in fusion science. To address this issue via a five-dimensional gyrokinetic model, the Gyrokinetic Toroidal 5D full-f Eulerian code GT5D has been developed. On the K-computer, inter-node parallelization techniques such as multi-dimensional/-layer domain decomposition and communication-computation overlap were developed, and strong scaling of GT5D was improved up to 73,728 nodes. This computing power enabled us to study ITER relevant issues such as the plasma size scaling of turbulent transport. However, extensions of GT5D towards burning plasmas including kinetic electrons and multi-species ions require greater computing power. Under the post-K project (Japanese Exa-scale computing project), we have developed computing techniques for next generation platforms such as GPUs and many core processors. In this talk, we discuss computational challenges related to complicated intra-node memory hierarchy and relatively limited inter-node communication performance compared with accelerated computation. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa210"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
