	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> 2016 has seen the start of an ambitious new initiative at the US Department of Energy: The Exascale Computing Project (https://exascaleproject.org). ECP brings together domain scientists, applied mathematicians, computer scientists, and engineers to work in collaboration to accelerate the development of exascale hardware and software. On the software side, 15 applications were fully funded (+7 seed efforts), as well as 4 “co-design” centers and 35 software development projects. This presentation will give an insider’s view of the exascale project and, in particular, of the funded application on “High-Fidelity Whole Device Modeling of Magnetically Confined Fusion Plasma”. This project aims at developing an exascale-ready framework for the whole-device simulation of tokamak fusion devices. One of the main tasks in this effort is the coupling of the core turbulence delta-f code GENE with the edge turbulence total-f code XGC1. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa133"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa133","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Gyrokinetic Global Electromagnetic Simulations with ORB5 and GENE.","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Access to HPC facilities has allowed gyrokinetic (GK) codes to be taken to significantly more advanced levels of realism. We present a new two-fold (theoretical and numerical) generic framework for GK code verification; the multi-species electromagnetic ORB5 (PIC) and the global version of GENE (Eulerian) are considered as examples. The first part of this work contains a common theoretical framework for the systematic derivation of the ORB5 and GENE code models, while the second part is dedicated to the inter-code benchmark. A detailed analysis of micro-instabilities identified the main numerical difficulties such as requirement of a large radial resolution. Detailed verifications of global electromagnetic test cases developed from the CYCLONE Base Case are considered, including a parametric \u0026#946;-scan covering the transition from ITG to KBM and the spectral properties at the nominal \u0026#946; value. First results of transition towards turbulence regime within the same setup are presented","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Natalia","last_name":"Tronko","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Natalia","last_name":"Tronko","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alberto","last_name":"Bottino","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tobias","la