	</script><div class="title">Gyrokinetic Global Electromagnetic Simulations with ORB5 and GENE.</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Natalia Tronko (Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Natalia","last_name":"Tronko","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Plasma Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Access to HPC facilities has allowed gyrokinetic (GK) codes to be taken to significantly more advanced levels of realism. We present a new two-fold (theoretical and numerical) generic framework for GK code verification; the multi-species electromagnetic ORB5 (PIC) and the global version of GENE (Eulerian) are considered as examples. The first part of this work contains a common theoretical framework for the systematic derivation of the ORB5 and GENE code models, while the second part is dedicated to the inter-code benchmark. A detailed analysis of micro-instabilities identified the main numerical difficulties such as requirement of a large radial resolution. Detailed verifications of global electromagnetic test cases developed from the CYCLONE Base Case are considered, including a parametric &#946;-scan covering the transition from ITG to KBM and the spectral properties at the nominal &#946; value. First results of transition towards turbulence regime within the same setup are presented </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa190"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
