		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa105","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Nature-Inspired Water Splitting for Sustainable Hydrogen Production","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Solar energy is an inexhaustible energy source for a sustainable solution to the global energy consumption. Artificial photosynthesis permits the splitting of water into molecular hydrogen and oxygen and is, therefore, a very promising strategy to meet the increasing worldwide need for clean energy. This requires the development of efficient water-reduction and water-oxidation catalysts (WOCs) where the latter is currently the main bottleneck for efficient photocatalytic water splitting. Very recently, the first Co(II)-based cubane WOCs have been presented, which excel through unprecedented structural analogies to the oxygen-evolving complex of nature\u2019s photosystem II. We study their properties and catalytic behavior by means of high-level density functional theory (DFT) and DFT-based molecular dynamics. Moreover, structurally simpler Co-based WOCs are investigated in detail. The insight gained from the calculations paves the way for the derivation of important structure-activity relationships essential for informed design of novel high-performance WOCs.","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa105","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sandra","last_name":"Luber","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa105","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sandra","last_name":"Luber","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Nature-Inspired Water Splitting for Sustainable Hydrogen Production</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sandra Luber (University of Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa105","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sandra","last_name":"Luber","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Solar energy is an inexhaustible energy source for a sustainable solution to the global energy consumption. Artificial photosynthesis permits the splitting of water into molecular hydrogen and oxygen and is, therefore, a very promising strategy to meet the increasing worldwide need for clean energy. This requires the development of efficient water-reduction and water-oxidation catalysts (WOCs) where the latter is currently the main bottleneck for efficient photocatalytic water splitting. Very recently, the first Co(II)-based cubane WOCs have been presented, which excel through unprecedented structural analogies to the oxygen-evolving complex of nature’s photosystem II. We study their properties and catalytic behavior by means of high-level density functional theory (DFT) and DFT-based molecular dynamics. Moreover, structurally simpler Co-based WOCs are investigated in detail. The insight gained from the calculations paves the way for the derivation of important structure-activity relationships essential for informed design of novel high-performance WOCs. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa219"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa219","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Ab Initio Molecular Dynamics of Liquids: From CO2 Conversion to Osmotic Energy Conversion","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Many chemical processes involved in energy production occur in the liquid state or at liquid interfaces. Here we will discuss how ab initio Molecular Dynamics allows to describe these processes at ambient and at elevated temperatures. We will show how it can gives mechanistic insights as well as recent progress towards multi-scale simulations and the calculation of thermodynamical quantities. We will mainly consider two examples: first, molten carbonates that are used as electrolyte for molten salt fuel cells and have been proposed for elctrochemical conversion of CO2, and second, osmotic energy conversion by chemisorption of hydroxide on boron nitride membranes.","begin_time":"12:30","begin_timestamp":"1522233000","end_time":"13:00","end_timestamp":"1522234800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa219","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Rodolphe","last_name":"Vuilleumier","affiliation":"Pierre and Marie Curie University","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa219","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Rodolphe","last_name":"Vuilleumier","affiliation":"Pierre and Marie Curie University","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Ab Initio Molecular Dynamics of Liquids: From CO2 Conversion to Osmotic Energy Conversion</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Rodolphe Vuilleumier (Pierre and Marie Curie University, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa219","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Rodolphe","last_name":"Vuilleumier","affiliation":"Pierre and Marie Curie University","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Many chemical processes involved in energy production occur in the liquid state or at liquid interfaces. Here we will discuss how ab initio Molecular Dynamics allows to describe these processes at ambient and at elevated temperatures. We will show how it can gives mechanistic insights as well as recent progress towards multi-scale simulations and the calculation of thermodynamical quantities. We will mainly consider two examples: first, molten carbonates that are used as electrolyte for molten salt fuel cells and have been proposed for elctrochemical conversion of CO2, and second, osmotic energy conversion by chemisorption of hydroxide on boron nitride membranes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess188-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess188" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS20 Particle-Based Methods for Simulations in Life Sciences, Fluids and Materials (1/2)</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 005</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess188"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Igor Pivkin (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp136","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Igor","last_name":"Pivkin","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences, Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The main objective of this symposium is to bring international scientists together working in the area of particle-based modeling with applications in Life Sciences, Fluids, and Materials. Numerical methods include but are not restricted to Coarse-Graining Molecular Dynamics (CG-MD), Dissipative Particle Dynamics (DPD), Smoothed Dissipative Particle Dynamics (SDPD), Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH), Lattice-Boltzmann Method (LBM), Moving Particle Semi-Implicit Method (MPS), Brownian Dynamics (BD) and Stokesian Dynamics (SD). The goal of minisymposium is, on one hand, to share state-of-the-art results in various applications of particle-based methods and, on the other to discuss technical issues of the computational modeling.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa274"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:00 - 11:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
