	</script><div class="title">An Unstructured-Mesh Generator Based on SPH Analogy</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Lin Fu (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa274","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Lin","last_name":"Fu","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We propose a novel unstructured mesh generation method based on SPH analogy. An adapted isotropic mesh is generated by three steps. First, three field variables are introduced to define the target mesh-vertex distribution along with their governing transport equations. Second, a particle-relaxation process is defined and solved numerically by an SPH method such that the final particle distribution conforms to the mesh-quality target functions and satisfies isotropy and smoothness criteria. Third, the unstructured mesh is generated from the particle distribution by Delaunay triangulation. We demonstrate that the method produces high-quality unstructured meshes for complex domain boundaries. In particular, we find that the meshes optimally satisfy multiple quality criteria. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa175"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa175","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Smoothed Dissipative Particle Dynamics with Angular Momentum Conservation","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Smoothed dissipative particle dynamics (SDPD) combines two popular mesoscopic techniques, the smoothed particle hydrodynamics and dissipative particle dynamics (DPD) methods, and can be considered as an improved DPD approach. Despite several advantages of the SDPD method over the conventional DPD model, the current formulation of SDPD lacks angular momentum conservation, leading to unphysical results for problems where the conservation of angular momentum is essential. To overcome this limitation, we extend the SDPD method by introducing a particle spin variable such that local and global angular momentum conservation is restored.  We test the new method and demonstrate that it properly reproduces fluid transport coefficients. We also employ the new SDPD formulation for modeling the dynamics of blood cells. In conclusion, the extended SDPD method with angular momentum conservation provides a new approach to tackle fluid problems such as multiphase flows and vesicle\/cell suspensions, where the conservation of angular momentum is essential.","begin_time":"11:30","begin_timestamp":"1522229400","end_time":"12:00","end_timestamp":"1522231200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa175","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Fedosov","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa175","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Fedosov","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa175","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Davod","last_name":"Alizadehrad","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa175","title":"P