	</script><div class="title">Smoothed Dissipative Particle Dynamics with Angular Momentum Conservation</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dmitry Fedosov (Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa175","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Fedosov","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Smoothed dissipative particle dynamics (SDPD) combines two popular mesoscopic techniques, the smoothed particle hydrodynamics and dissipative particle dynamics (DPD) methods, and can be considered as an improved DPD approach. Despite several advantages of the SDPD method over the conventional DPD model, the current formulation of SDPD lacks angular momentum conservation, leading to unphysical results for problems where the conservation of angular momentum is essential. To overcome this limitation, we extend the SDPD method by introducing a particle spin variable such that local and global angular momentum conservation is restored. We test the new method and demonstrate that it properly reproduces fluid transport coefficients. We also employ the new SDPD formulation for modeling the dynamics of blood cells. In conclusion, the extended SDPD method with angular momentum conservation provides a new approach to tackle fluid problems such as multiphase flows and vesicle/cell suspensions, where the conservation of angular momentum is essential. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa288"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa288","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Hybrid Simulation of Turbulent Wake Vortices with Rain","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Wake related separations increasingly become a capacity-limiting factor in air traffic. The SESAR project aims at modernizing the European airspace and safely increasing its capacity. This includes the use, in real time, of Lidar and Radar to detect and alert of hazardous wake situations. In rainy weather, the back-scattered power seen by radar is mostly function of the raindrop concentration and diameter distribution, thus motivating the prediction of the return signal due to raindrops caught within turbulent wake vortices. The present work aims at correlating the vortex intensity and the radar signal through simulation. The large number of raindrops motivates an approach based on continuum fields. The turbulent flow and the raindrop velocities are simulated using a pseudo-spectral solver while a remeshed particle method is used for the raindrop concentration. The non-zero divergence of the raindrop velocity field imposes special treatments to prevent oscillations and negative concentrations.","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa288","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Philippe","last_name":"Billuart","affiliation":"Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa288","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Philippe","last_name":"Billuart","affiliation":"Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Hybrid Simulation of Turbulent Wake Vortices with Rain</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Philippe Billuart (Université catholique de Louvain, Belgium)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa288","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Philippe","last_name":"Billuart","affiliation":"Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain","country":"Belgium","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Wake related separations increasingly become a capacity-limiting factor in air traffic. The SESAR project aims at modernizing the European airspace and safely increasing its capacity. This includes the use, in real time, of Lidar and Radar to detect and alert of hazardous wake situations. In rainy weather, the back-scattered power seen by radar is mostly function of the raindrop concentration and diameter distribution, thus motivating the prediction of the return signal due to raindrops caught within turbulent wake vortices. The present work aims at correlating the vortex intensity and the radar signal through simulation. The large number of raindrops motivates an approach based on continuum fields. The turbulent flow and the raindrop velocities are simulated using a pseudo-spectral solver while a remeshed particle method is used for the raindrop concentration. The non-zero divergence of the raindrop velocity field imposes special treatments to prevent oscillations and negative concentrations. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa291"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
