	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We developed a coarse-grained protein model for Dissipative Particle Dynamics (DPD) method, which employs long-range electrostatics and Drude oscillators. The model allows sequence specific modeling of proteins on timescales larger than currently accessible by conventional methods. The model is also free from elastic network restraints needed to keep the secondary structure stable, which we consider as a strong advantage. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess192-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess192" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS21 Programming Models and Abstractions for Weather and Climate Models: Today and in the Future</strong>, Room B1</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess192"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Peter Bauer (ECMWF, United Kingdom)</span>, <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp140","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Peter","last_name":"Bauer","affiliation":"ECMWF","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> <div class="author"> Oliver Fuhrer (MeteoSwiss, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp140","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliver","last_name":"Fuhrer","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Climate &amp; Weather</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Progress in weather and climate modeling is tightly linked to the increase in computing resources available for such models. Emerging heterogeneous high-performance architectures are a unique opportunity to address these requirements in an energy- and time-efficient manner. The hardware changes of emerging computing platforms are accompanied by dramatic changes in programming paradigms. These changes have only just started. Adapting current weather and climate codes to efficiently exploit such architectures requires an effort which is both costly and error-prone. The long software lifecycles of weather and climate codes renders the situation even more critical, as hardware life cycles are much shorter in comparison. Furthermore, atmospheric models are developed and used by a large variety of researchers on a myriad of computing platforms, which makes portability a crucial requirement in any kind of development. Developers of weather and climate models are struggling to achieve a better separation of concerns in order to separate the high-level specification of equations and solution algorithms from the hardware dependent, optimized low-level implementation. It is probable that the solutions to achieve this will be different for different parts of the codes, due to different predominant algorithmic motifs and data-structures. On the example of concrete porting efforts, this session will illustrate different approaches used today and (possibly) in the future.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa162"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:00 - 11:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa162","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"The CLAW Compiler: Abstractions for Weather and Climate Models","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Adapting complex code to take advantage of new computing HPC architectures is a cumbersome task. The development life cycle of weather models does not match the fast pace of the new hardware releases. Therefore, restructuring the code and applying specific architecture optimization is often needed to get optimal performance when porting models to those new architectures. This leads to multiple specific versions of the same code optimized for a single target supercomputer and not portable among them. In order to keep a single source code and get performance portability on different hardware, we propose a one-column model abstraction for physical parameterizations. It supports domain scientists who do not want to be concerned about HPC optimizations for multiple columns. We are developing a directive language and a tool named CLAW that is able to apply automatic code transformation on abstracted code to produce parallelized versions for dedicated target architecture.","begin_time":"11:00","begin_timestamp":"1522227600","end_time":"11:30","end_timestamp":"1522229400","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa162","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valentin","last_name":"Cl\u00e9ment","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa162","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valentin","last_name":"Cl\u00e9ment","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa162","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sylvaine","last_name":"Ferrachat","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa162","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliver","last_name":"Fuhrer","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa162","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Xavier","last_name":"Lapillonne","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa162","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"William","last_name":"Sawyer","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]},"presentation_file":"MS21.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">The CLAW Compiler: Abstractions for Weather and Climate Models</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Valentin Clément (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa162","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Valentin","last_name":"Cl\u00e9ment","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS21.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Adapting complex code to take advantage of new computing HPC architectures is a cumbersome task. The development life cycle of weather models does not match the fast pace of the new hardware releases. Therefore, restructuring the code and applying specific architecture optimization is often needed to get optimal performance when porting models to those new architectures. This leads to multiple specific versions of the same code optimized for a single target supercomputer and not portable among them. In order to keep a single source code and get performance portability on different hardware, we propose a one-column model abstraction for physical parameterizations. It supports domain scientists who do not want to be concerned about HPC optimizations for multiple columns. We are developing a directive language and a tool named CLAW that is able to apply automatic code transformation on abstracted code to produce parallelized versions for dedicated target architecture. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa283"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa283","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Performance Portable Acceleration of Weather and Climate Dwarfs","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The life-time of weather and climate codes often spans several processor generations, making it difficult to introduce code optimizations targeting single hardware platform. And yet, the scientific missions requires these applications to run at very high performance on a broad range of hardware. Applications therefore need to be written abstractly enough to guarantee portability while expressively enough to enable high performance. OpenACC and OpenMP are well established standards for expressing parallelism and data locality, whereas data management layers like Atlas or GridTools offer target independent data structures. Within the ESCAPE project we therefore investigate whether these tools meet the performance and portability requirements of the weather and climate community. Isolating core algorithmic motifs of operational models into so-called dwarfs, we can quickly explore and compare different implementations. In this talk we will discuss results of optimization efforts on CPUs, CPU+Xeon Phi and GPUs, using different performance portable approaches.","begin_time":"11:30","begin_timestamp":"1522229400","end_time":"12:00","end_timestamp":"1522231200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa283","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Peter","last_name":"Messmer","affiliation":"NVIDIA Inc.","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa283","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Peter","last_name":"Messmer","affiliation":"NVIDIA Inc.","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa283","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alastair","last_name":"McKinstry","affiliation":"ICHEC","country":"Ireland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Performance Portable Acceleration of Weather and Climate Dwarfs</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Peter Messmer (NVIDIA Inc., Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa283","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Peter","last_name":"Messmer","affiliation":"NVIDIA Inc.","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The life-time of weather and climate codes often spans several processor generations, making it difficult to introduce code optimizations targeting single hardware platform. And yet, the scientific missions requires these applications to run at very high performance on a broad range of hardware. Applications therefore need to be written abstractly enough to guarantee portability while expressively enough to enable high performance. OpenACC and OpenMP are well established standards for expressing parallelism and data locality, whereas data management layers like Atlas or GridTools offer target independent data structures. Within the ESCAPE project we therefore investigate whether these tools meet the performance and portability requirements of the weather and climate community. Isolating core algorithmic motifs of operational models into so-called dwarfs, we can quickly explore and compare different implementations. In this talk we will discuss results of optimization efforts on CPUs, CPU+Xeon Phi and GPUs, using different performance portable approaches. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa269"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
