	</script><div class="title">Performance Portable Dynamical Cores on Irregular Grids Using Domain Specific Languages</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Carlos Osuna Escamilla (MeteoSwiss, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa269","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Carlos","last_name":"Osuna Escamilla","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Numerical weather prediction and climate models are large parallel applications that need to simulate complex physical phenomena within tight production schedules. In search of improving prediction accuracy, weather models are continuously exploring new discretization methods and increasing the spatial resolution, which results in an ever increasing demand for more computing power and efficient codes that can leverage non traditional computing architectures. Porting large weather codes to heterogeneous architectures preserving a single, efficient source code can be a daunting process. The ESCAPE project develops methods and algorithms for high performance weather applications, with an emphasis on accelerators. We show a domain specific language (DSL) for dynamical cores on regular and irregular grids, that can be used to retain a single performance portable source code. The DSL allows the implementation of grid independent numerical operators using an unstructured grid syntax, abstracting the details of the underlying grid and the architecture dependent implementation. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa284"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa284","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"LFRic and PSyclone: A Domain Specific Language Approach to Atmospheric Models for Exascale","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The large degree of parallelism and lack of common programming models between different processor architectures is forcing many scientific applications to re-write their codes. The Met Office has already completed a project to design a new, scalable dynamical core for an atmospheric model. The LFRic project, named after Lewis Fry Richardson is building a software infrastructure for an atmospheric model with a Gung Ho dynamical core. An important component of the software is PSyClone, a python code generator. Code written according to the API rules can be parsed by PSyClone and a parallel middle layer generated. Moreover, it is able to target different programming models for different architectures. This allows a single source of science code.","begin_time":"12:30","begin_timestamp":"1522233000","end_time":"13:00","end_timestamp":"1522234800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa284","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christopher","last_name":"Maynard","affiliation":"Met Office","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa284","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christopher","last_name":"Maynard","affiliation":"Met Office","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">LFRic and PSyclone: A Domain Specific Language Approach to Atmospheric Models for Exascale</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Christopher Maynard (Met Office, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
