	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The large degree of parallelism and lack of common programming models between different processor architectures is forcing many scientific applications to re-write their codes. The Met Office has already completed a project to design a new, scalable dynamical core for an atmospheric model. The LFRic project, named after Lewis Fry Richardson is building a software infrastructure for an atmospheric model with a Gung Ho dynamical core. An important component of the software is PSyClone, a python code generator. Code written according to the API rules can be parsed by PSyClone and a parallel middle layer generated. Moreover, it is able to target different programming models for different architectures. This allows a single source of science code. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess177-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess177" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS22 Quantum Monte Carlo and Many-Body Theory</strong>, Room B3</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="