	</script><div class="title">Stochastic Multi-Reference Perturbation Theory</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michel Caffarel (CNRS, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa238","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Caffarel","affiliation":"CNRS","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> I present an hybrid stochastic-deterministic approach for computing the second-orderperturbative contribution E(2) of multireference perturbation theories (MRPT). A formulaexpressing E(2) as a sum of contributions associated with each determinant of the MR wavefunction is derived and a Monte Carlo (MC) algorithm to compute E(2) is presented. To greatlyenhance the MC convergence, a hybrid scheme based on the decomposition of E(2) into astochastic and a deterministic part is introduced. In sharp contrast to purely MC schemes, thehybrid estimator converges with a typical exponential-like behavior. The method is illustrated on the F2 and Cr2 molecules. Even for the largest case corresponding to the Cr2 molecule treated with the cc-pVQZ basis set, very accurate results are obtained for E(2) for an active space of (28e,198o) (Hilbert space including more than 10^42 determinants) and a MR wave function including up to 2.8x10^7 determinants. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa239"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
