	</script><div class="title">HPC within In Silico Clinical Trials: PAEON experience</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Enrico Tronci (Sapienza University, Italy)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa229","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Enrico","last_name":"Tronci","affiliation":"Sapienza University","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In Silico Clinical Trials (ISCT) require checking that for all "virtual patients" (i.e., biologically meaningful parameters for human physiology models) the treatment being assessed meets given safety and efficacy constraints. This entails two main steps: first, generating the population of virtual patients and, second, for each virtual patient running simulations in order to check the given safety and efficacy requirements. Both above ISCT steps are computationally very intensive and thus can considerably benefit from the usage of HPC tools. Resting on PAEON project experience, in this talk we will outline HPC based methods and software tools to support both automatic generation of virtual patients and treatment assessment for each virtual patient. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa244"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">11:30 - 12:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
