	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Clinical decision support systems are increasingly finding their way into clinics. Meeting the requirements of clinical workflows renders the integration of such systems a daunting or even impossible task. Capturing clinical workflows and creating supporting data models often requires tailored solutions that impede data integration and interoperability. Here we report on our design approach based on clinical requirements and on the benefits and risks of developing and implementing a tailor made CDS System that is relevant for the health IT developer community. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa241"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:00 - 12:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa241","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"A Clinical Decision Support System for Hormonal Treatments in Reproductive Endocrinology","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Virtual physiological human (VPH) models and software tools enable in silico clinical trials by means of computer simulations over a population of virtual patients. The focus here is on the construction of VPH models for reproductive endocrinology. They are based on a mathematical model that describes the time evolution of hormones and follicles during the human menstrual cycle. The model has been tuned and validated exploiting large amounts of retrospective clinical data to ensure that it reliably mimics the natural behaviour, both with and without administration of fertility drugs. The VPH model contains many parameters. Different values to these parameters yield different model behaviours and capture the physiological differences among different women. The construction of such virtual patient populations by means of, e.g., statistical model checking or empirical Bayes methods, requires significant computational effort.","begin_time":"12:00","begin_timestamp":"1522231200","end_time":"12:30","end_timestamp":"1522233000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa241","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Rainald","last_name":"Ehrig","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa241","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Rainald","last_name":"Ehrig","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa241","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Susanna","last_name":"R\u00f6blitz","affiliation":"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">A Clinical Decision Support System for Hormonal Treatments in Reproductive Endocrinology</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Rainald Ehrig (Zuse Institute Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa241","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Rainald","last_name":"Ehrig","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Virtual physiological human (VPH) models and software tools enable in silico clinical trials by means of computer simulations over a population of virtual patients. The focus here is on the construction of VPH models for reproductive endocrinology. They are based on a mathematical model that describes the time evolution of hormones and follicles during the human menstrual cycle. The model has been tuned and validated exploiting large amounts of retrospective clinical data to ensure that it reliably mimics the natural behaviour, both with and without administration of fertility drugs. The VPH model contains many parameters. Different values to these parameters yield different model behaviours and capture the physiological differences among different women. The construction of such virtual patient populations by means of, e.g., statistical model checking or empirical Bayes methods, requires significant computational effort. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa248"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">12:30 - 13:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa248","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Integrated Physiology in Modelica: HumMod and Physiomodel","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Sophisticated medical training simulators must include models of various physiological subsystems, and also integrate them into a comprehensive whole. One of the largest models of integrated physiological systems called HumMod (http:\/\/hummod.org) is implemented as open source by thousands of XML files. Our reimplementation and extension of HumMod 1.6 in the Modelica language called PHYSIOMODEL (http:\/\/physiomodel.org), has brought a much clearer and more understandable description of the simulated complex physiological relationships than XML implementation. Modelica is well suited to exactly formalize integrative physiology. Modelica is an equation-based, and object-oriented language for hybrid ordinary differential equations. Almost every physiological term can be defined as a class in this language and can be instantiated as many times as it occurs in the body. Each class has a graphical icon for use in diagrams. These diagrams are self-describing; the Modelica code generated from them is the full representation of the underlying mathematical model.","begin_time":"12:30","begin_timestamp":"1522233000","end_time":"13:00","end_timestamp":"1522234800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa248","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Ji\u0159\u00ed","last_name":"Kofr\u00e1nek","affiliation":"Charles University","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa248","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Ji\u0159\u00ed","last_name":"Kofr\u00e1nek","affiliation":"Charles University","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa248","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Filip","last_name":"Je\u017eek","affiliation":"Czech Technical University in Prague","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"0"},{"