	</script><div class="title">Searching Stable Interface Structures with Bayesian Optimization</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Koji Tsuda (University of Tokyo, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa249","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Koji","last_name":"Tsuda","affiliation":"University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Crystalline interfaces have a tremendous impact on the properties of materials. Determination of the atomic structure of the interface is crucial for a comprehensive understanding of the interface properties. Despite this importance, extensive calculation is necessary to determine even one interface structure. In this study, we apply a machine learning technique called Bayesian optimization to accelerate the determination of the interface structure. The atomic structures of simplified coincidence-site lattice interfaces were determined using the optimization approach. Our method successfully determined the most stable interface structure with an efficiency almost 2 orders of magnitude better than the traditional “brute force” approach. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa271"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa271","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Combining Ab Initio Calculations with Electrostatic Models to Describe Defects at Surfaces at Realistic Temperature, Pressure, and Doping Conditions","scientific_track":"","abstract":"An important parameter influencing defect concentration and defect charge states is doping. Using ab-initio atomistic thermodynamics, we show [1] that (and how) charge-carrier doping influences significantly the transition levels and formation energies of defects at interfaces. In our approach, the energy density of the electric field is considered as part of the free energy of the system. Charged defects at surfaces are modelled using a variant of the virtual crystal approximation. Two main contributions to the defect formation energy are identified: (i) the interaction of a charged defect with the compensating charge and (ii) the shift in the Fermi level due to the space-charge formation. Our results for doped MgO show that the effects of charge-carrier doping on interface chemical properties can be significant, so that doping (intentional or not) must be considered as a thermodynamic variable along with temperature and pressure. \nReference: [1]Richter et al., PRL 111, 045502 (2013).","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa271","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey V.","last_name":"Levchenko","affiliation":"Fritz Haber Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa271","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey V.","last_name":"Levchenko","affiliation":"Fritz Haber Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Combining Ab Initio Calculations with Electrostatic Models to Describe Defects at Surfaces at Realistic Temperature, Pressure, and Doping Conditions</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sergey V. Levchenko (Fritz Haber Institute Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa271","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sergey V.","last_name":"Levchenko","affiliation":"Fritz Haber Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> An important parameter influencing defect concentration and defect charge states is doping. Using ab-initio atomistic thermodynamics, we show [1] that (and how) charge-carrier doping influences significantly the transition levels and formation energies of defects at interfaces. In our approach, the energy density of the electric field is considered as part of the free energy of the system. Charged defects at surfaces are modelled using a variant of the virtual crystal approximation. Two main contributions to the defect formation energy are identified: (i) the interaction of a charged defect with the compensating charge and (ii) the shift in the Fermi level due to the space-charge formation. Our results for doped MgO show that the effects of charge-carrier doping on interface chemical properties can be significant, so that doping (intentional or not) must be considered as a thermodynamic variable along with temperature and pressure. Reference: [1]Richter et al., PRL 111, 045502 (2013). </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa246"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa246","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"First-Principles Simulation of Electrochemical Reactions at Solid-Liquid Interface","scientific_track":"","abstract":"It is known that the chemical reaction at the solid-liquid interface to which a voltage is applied, that is to say, the electrochemical interface, has a significant influence on the durability and performance of the secondary battery and the fuel cell. For example, in a secondary battery, the electrode-electrolyte interface determines the durability of the battery, and in a fuel cell, the catalytic activity at the interface determines its performance. We are conducting research aiming at improving the performance of those electrochemical devices and presenting design guidelines by clarifying the microscopic process of chemical reaction at the electrochemical interface using first principles simulation. In this talk, I will introduce the simulation technique developed by us and present recent simulation results for the cyclic voltammogram of oxygen evolution reaction (OER) and oxygen reduction reaction. I will also present more recent progress of simulation techniques for the solid-liquid interface.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa246","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Minoru","last_name":"Otani","affiliation":"National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa246","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Minoru","last_name":"Otani","affiliation":"National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">First-Principles Simulation of Electrochemical Reactions at Solid-Liquid Interface</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Minoru Otani (National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa246","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Minoru","last_name":"Otani","affiliation":"National Institute of Advanced Industrial Science and Technology","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> It is known that the chemical reaction at the solid-liquid interface to which a voltage is applied, that is to say, the electrochemical interface, has a significant influence on the durability and performance of the secondary battery and the fuel cell. For example, in a secondary battery, the electrode-electrolyte interface determines the durability of the battery, and in a fuel cell, the catalytic activity at the interface determines its performance. We are conducting research aiming at improving the performance of those electrochemical devices and presenting design guidelines by clarifying the microscopic process of chemical reaction at the electrochemical interface using first principles simulation. In this talk, I will introduce the simulation technique developed by us and present recent simulation results for the cyclic voltammogram of oxygen evolution reaction (OER) and oxygen reduction reaction. I will also present more recent progress of simulation techniques for the solid-liquid interface. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa245"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa245","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Challenges in Electronic Structure Modeling of Battery Interfaces","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Structure-function relationships at interfaces are critical for electrochemical applications.  Atomic lengthscale details of buried liquid-solid and solid-solid interfaces are challenging to image. Tremendous progress has been made in DFT modeling of electrochemical interfaces, and the predictions provide crucial guiding insights. I will discuss some remaining challenges particular to modeling lithium ion battery interfaces, using published works by my group and others as illustrations. The challenges include: the inherently \u0022dirty\u0022 (solid-film-covered) nature of electrodes, and parasitic\/degradation reactions responsible for these films; the lack of Grand Canonical sampling of lithium content; and the difficulty in calibrating applied potentials, especially for small-polaron-conductor electrode materials. Modeling of solid-state-electrolyte- and liquid-based batteries will be discussed in a unified framework. Sandia National Laboratories is a multimission laboratory managed and operated by Sandia Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of Lockheed Martin Corporation, for the U.S. Department of Energy\u0027s National Nuclear Security Administration under contract DE-AC04-94AL85000.","begin_time":"15:30","begin_timestamp":"1522243800","end_time":"16:00","end_timestamp":"1522245600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa245","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Kevin","last_name":"Leung","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa245","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Kevin","last_name":"Leung","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2