	</script><div class="title">Challenges in Electronic Structure Modeling of Battery Interfaces</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Kevin Leung (Sandia National Laboratories, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa245","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Kevin","last_name":"Leung","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Structure-function relationships at interfaces are critical for electrochemical applications. Atomic lengthscale details of buried liquid-solid and solid-solid interfaces are challenging to image. Tremendous progress has been made in DFT modeling of electrochemical interfaces, and the predictions provide crucial guiding insights. I will discuss some remaining challenges particular to modeling lithium ion battery interfaces, using published works by my group and others as illustrations. The challenges include: the inherently "dirty" (solid-film-covered) nature of electrodes, and parasitic/degradation reactions responsible for these films; the lack of Grand Canonical sampling of lithium content; and the difficulty in calibrating applied potentials, especially for small-polaron-conductor electrode materials. Modeling of solid-state-electrolyte- and liquid-based batteries will be discussed in a unified framework. Sandia National Laboratories is a multimission laboratory managed and operated by Sandia Corporation, a wholly owned subsidiary of Lockheed Martin Corporation, for the U.S. Department of Energy's National Nuclear Security Administration under contract DE-AC04-94AL85000. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess181-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess181" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS25 Computational Challenges in General-Relativistic Matter Simulations</strong>, Room B3</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div c