	</script><div class="title">Simulating Generic Binary Neutron Star Mergers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Tim Dietrich (Max Planck Institute for Gravitational Physics, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa136","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tim","last_name":"Dietrich","affiliation":"Max Planck Institute for Gravitational Physics","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Binary neutron star mergers are associated with a variety of observable phenomena in the gravitational and electromagnetic spectra. We investigate binary neutron stars in the last milliseconds before and after their merger with full 3D numerical simulations. We explain how we access previously inaccessible regions of the binary neutron star parameter space, e.g. spinning and high mass ratio setups, and we discuss first simulations with generic setups. We also show that recent upgrades allow us to improve the accuracy of the simulation and decrease the phase error of the obtained gravitational waveforms. With these updates our waveforms can be used for validating and improving semi-analytical waveform models. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa272"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa272","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Entropy-Limited Hydrodynamics: A Novel Approach to Relativistic Hydrodynamics","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present entropy-limited hydrodynamics: a new approach for the computation of fluxes arising in the discretization of equations in conservation form. ELH is based on the hybridisation of a high-order scheme with the Lax-Friedrichs method. The activation of the low-order part of the scheme is driven by the generated entropy inspired by the artificial-viscosity method proposed by Guermond et al. We present ELH in the context of finite-differencing methods and of general-relativistic hydrodynamics. We study the performance of ELH in a series of astrophysical tests in general relativity. We present a comparison of ELH with the MP5 method, one of the most common schemes. We find that ELH achieves comparable or better accuracy than more traditional methods at a fraction of the computational cost. Given its accuracy and its simplicity of implementation, ELH is a promising framework for the development of relativistic hydrodynamics codes well adapted for parallel supercomputers.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa272","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Federico","last_name":"Guercilena","affiliation":"Goethe University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa272","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Federico","last_name":"Guercilena","affiliation":"Goethe University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa272","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"David","last_name":"Radice","affiliation":"Princeton University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa272","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Luciano","last_name":"Rezzolla","affiliation":"Goethe Univer