	</script><div class="title">Entropy-Limited Hydrodynamics: A Novel Approach to Relativistic Hydrodynamics</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Federico Guercilena (Goethe University, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa272","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Federico","last_name":"Guercilena","affiliation":"Goethe University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present entropy-limited hydrodynamics: a new approach for the computation of fluxes arising in the discretization of equations in conservation form. ELH is based on the hybridisation of a high-order scheme with the Lax-Friedrichs method. The activation of the low-order part of the scheme is driven by the generated entropy inspired by the artificial-viscosity method proposed by Guermond et al. We present ELH in the context of finite-differencing methods and of general-relativistic hydrodynamics. We study the performance of ELH in a series of astrophysical tests in general relativity. We present a comparison of ELH with the MP5 method, one of the most common schemes. We find that ELH achieves comparable or better accuracy than more traditional methods at a fraction of the computational cost. Given its accuracy and its simplicity of implementation, ELH is a promising framework for the development of relativistic hydrodynamics codes well adapted for parallel supercomputers. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa268"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
