	</script><div class="title">Multi-Messenger Signals from Gravitational Wave Sources</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Stephan Rosswog (Stockholm University, Sweden)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa268","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Stephan","last_name":"Rosswog","affiliation":"Stockholm University","country":"Sweden","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Mergers of neutron star binaries are exquisite multi-physics laboratories: they are strong sources of gravitational waves, they are the best models for the central trigger of short gamma-ray bursts, they emit enormous amounts of neutrinos and they are the likely sources of the heaviest elements in the Universe. In this talk, we will review the channels through which neutron star mergers expel matter and we discuss the related nucleosynthesis. We further discuss the electromagnetic emission that is expected to follow the gravitational wave chirp. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa286"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa286","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Numerical Simulations of the Magnetic Field Amplification in Neutron Stars","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Strong magnetic fields (\u003E10^15 G) are expected to be present in some class of neutron stars (magnetars) and may play an important role in the binary neutron star (BNS) model of short GRBs. However, it is still not clear how a large-scale magnetic field of such strength could be generated. I present numerical simulations of the amplification of magnetic fields in two different contexts: in the case of proto-neutron stars I present results of local simulations of the magneto-rotational instability and I discuss their implications in this context. In the case of BNS, I present high resolution GRMHD simulations of the merger of two neutron stars in which the magnetic field is amplified driven by the development of Kelvin-Helmholtz vortices. The resulting magnetic field is highly turbulent and may meet the conditions to develop a dynamo, which could generate large-scale ordered field in longer time-scales.","begin_time":"15:30","begin_timestamp":"1522243800","end_time":"16:00","end_timestamp":"1522245600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa286","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Pablo","last_name":"Cerda-Duran","affiliation":"University of Valencia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa286","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Pablo","last_name":"Cerda-Duran","affiliation":"University of Valencia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Numerical Simulations of the Magnetic Field Amplification in Neutron Stars</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Pablo Cerda-Duran (University of Valencia, Spain)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa286","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Pablo","last_name":"Cerda-Duran","affiliation":"University of Valencia","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Strong magnetic fields (>10^15 G) are expected to be present in some class of neutron stars (magnetars) and may play an important role in the binary neutron star (BNS) model of short GRBs. However, it is still not clear how a large-scale magnetic field of such strength could be generated. I present numerical simulations of the amplification of magnetic fields in two different contexts: in the case of proto-neutron stars I present results of local simulations of the magneto-rotational instability and I discuss their implications in this context. In the case of BNS, I present high resolution GRMHD simulations of the merger of two neutron stars in which the magnetic field is amplified driven by the development of Kelvin-Helmholtz vortices. The resulting magnetic field is highly turbulent and may meet the conditions to develop a dynamo, which could generate large-scale ordered field in longer time-scales. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess195-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess195" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS26 Computing Bulks of Inner Eigenpairs of Large Sparse Matrices: From Applications and Algorithms to Performance and Software Engineering (2/2)</strong>, Room B2</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g> </svg> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </a> </div> <div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess195"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Jonas Thies (German Aerospace Center, Germany)</span>, <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp143","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jonas","last_name":"Thies","affiliation":"German Aerospace Center","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> <div class="author"> Gerhard Wellein (Friedrich-Alexander-Universität Erlangen-Nürnberg, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp143","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Gerhard","last_name":"Wellein","affiliation":"Friedrich-Alexander-Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics, Physics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The computation of bulks of inner eigenpairs of large sparse matrices is known to be both an algorithmic challenge and resource intensive in terms of compute power. As the compute capabilities have continuously increased over the past decades, computational models or applications requiring information about inner eigenstates of sparse matrices have become numerically accessible in many research fields. At the same time new algorithms (e.g. FEAST or SSM) have been introduced and long-standing methods such as filter diagonalization are still being applied, improved and extended. However, the trend towards highly parallel (heterogeneous) compute systems is challenging the efficiency of existing solver packages as well as building block libraries and calls for new massively parallel solvers with high hardware efficiency across different architectures. Thus, substantial effort is put into the implementation of new sparse (eigen)solver frameworks which face challenges both in terms easy to use, extendibility, sustainability, and hardware efficiency. Software engineering and holistic performance engineering concepts are deployed to address these challenges. The significant momentum in the application fields, numerical methods, and software layers calls for a strong interaction between scientists involved in those activities to provide sustainable and hardware efficient frameworks to compute inner eigenvalues of large sparse matrices. The minisymposium offers a platform to bring together leading experts in this field to discuss recent developments at all levels: from the application down to hardware efficient implementations of basic kernel operations. Application experts will present their current and upcoming research fields requiring the computation of inner eigenvalues. State-of-the-art eigensolvers and new algorithmic developments will be discussed along with challenges faced by library developers in terms of software sustainability and hardware efficiency. Many of these topics are not limited to the inner sparse eigenvalue problems but are of general interest for sparse linear algebra algorithms for current and future HPC architectures.<br /><br />Part 2 of the minisymposium focuses on algorithms as well as software and performance aspects.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa148"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa148","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Parallel Preconditioned Iterative Solvers on Manycore Architectures","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this work, optimization and performance evaluation of ICCG solver (conjugate gradient iterative method (CG) preconditioned by incomplete Cholesky factorization (IC)) on manycore architectures are investigated, where ICCG solver solves sparse symmetric positive definite (SPD) matrices derived from Poisson\u2019s equation discretized by finite-volume method (FVM). Because ICCG includes operations with data-dependency, such as forward\/backward substitutions, and incomplete Cholesky factorization, extraction of parallelism by reordering based on CM-RCM (Cyclic Multicoloring on Reverse Cuthill-Mckee) has been applied. Effects of reordering and format for matrix storage (CRS, SELL, SELL-C-Sigma) are considered. The performance was evaluated on a single socket\/node of each of Intel Xeon\/Phi (Knights Corner, Knights Landing), Intel Xeon (Broadwell-EP), and NVIDIA Tesla P100 (Pascal). Performance of the ICCG with SELL-C-Sigma on Knights Landing was better than existing methods.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa148","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Kengo","last_name":"Nakajima","affiliation":"The University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa148","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Kengo","last_name":"Nakajima","affiliation":"The University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa148","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Toshihiro","last_name":"Hanawa","affiliation":"The University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa148","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Tetsuya","last_name":"Hoshino","affiliation":"The University of Tokyo","countr