	</script><div class="title">Batched Factorization and Inversion Routines for Block-Jacobi Preconditioning on GPUs</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Hartwig Anzt (University of Tennessee, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa123","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hartwig","last_name":"Anzt","affiliation":"University of Tennessee","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Block-Jacobi preconditioners play an important role in scientific computing. Particularly for FEM discretizations that inherently carry some block structure, block-diagonal scaling can provide significant convergence improvement. At the same time, scaling with independent diagonal blocks allows for efficient parallelization. This property makes block-Jacobi especially attractive for parallel hardware. From the algorithmic side, block-Jacobi preconditioning can be realized by explicitly inverting the diagonal blocks in the preconditioner setup and apply the scaling in terms of multiplications, or by factorizing the diagonal blocks and realizing the preconditioner application as triangular solves. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa142"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa142","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Software and Performance Engineering for Iterative Eigensolvers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The complexity of the latest HPC architectures increasingly limits the productivity of researchers in numerical algorithms and the \u2018time to market\u0027 for parallel algorithms. Implementing a new method on a supercomputer today involves at least three levels of parallelism and typically several programming models like MPI, OpenMP, and CUDA. Frameworks like Trilinos and PETSc have for many years been useful for testing new ideas in parallel algorithms. But when it comes to e.g. CPU\/GPU clusters they fail to deliver convincing performance to date. We look at sparse solvers from a software engineer\u0027s point of view and advocate a programming model we call \u2018SPMD+OK\u0027, introducing performance models in the test-driven development process and a strategy to facilitate the integration of algorithmic developments into existing applications. Harnessing the peta-scale with the block Jacobi-Davidson method is used as a running example in this talk, and the libraries GHOST and PHIST are presented (https:\/\/bitbucket.org\/essex\/).","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa142","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jonas","last_name":"Thies","affiliation":"German Aerospace Center","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa142","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jonas","last_name":"Thies","affiliation":"German Aerospace Center","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Software and Performance Engineering for Iterative Eigensolvers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Jonas Thies (German Aerospace Center, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa142","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jonas","last_name":"Thies","affiliation":"German Aerospace Center","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The complexity of the latest HPC architectures increasingly limits the productivity of researchers in numerical algorithms and the ‘time to market' for parallel algorithms. Implementing a new method on a supercomputer today involves at least three levels of parallelism and typically several programming models like MPI, OpenMP, and CUDA. Frameworks like Trilinos and PETSc have for many years been useful for testing new ideas in parallel algorithms. But when it comes to e.g. CPU/GPU clusters they fail to deliver convincing performance to date. We look at sparse solvers from a software engineer's point of view and advocate a programming model we call ‘SPMD+OK', introducing performance models in the test-driven development process and a strategy to facilitate the integration of algorithmic developments into existing applications. Harnessing the peta-scale with the block Jacobi-Davidson method is used as a running example in this talk, and the libraries GHOST and PHIST are presented (https://bitbucket.org/essex/). </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa130"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
