	</script><div class="title">Domain-Decomposition-Based Fluid Structure Interaction Methods using Nonlinear Anisotropic Arterial Wall Models</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alexander Heinlein (University of Cologne, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa171","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Heinlein","affiliation":"University of Cologne","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Stress distributions in walls of in vivo arteries (transmural stresses) are a major factor driving, e.g., arteriosclerosis and arteriogenesis. We focus on fluid-structure interaction (FSI) using sophisticated nonlinear structural models, which have already been developed and adapted to experiments in the past. In particular, we use an anisotropic, polyconvex hyperelastic structural model for FSI simulations in an idealized benchmark geometry and in realistic patient-specific geometries of coronary arteries. The coupled FSI problems are solved using a monolithic approach based on domain decomposition, i.e., overlapping Schwarz and Dirichlet-Neumann methods. Our solver environment combines the FEM software packages LifeV and FEAP, which provide the nonlinear models for the fluid and a nonlinear, polyconvex, anisotropic model for the structure. Furthermore, we discuss improvements in the computing time of our FSI simulations, e.g., due to the use of suitable parallel domain decomposition preconditioners. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa230"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa230","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"A Multiphysics Approach for Early Atherosclerosis Progression","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present a framework for a coupled multiphysics approach for early atherosclerosis progression. It consists of a fluid-structure interaction (FSI) subproblem describing the cardiovascular mechanics, which is coupled to a multiple species subproblem describing the inflammatory processes in early atherosclerosis. In this context, the challenge is the coupling of an incompressible flow with a deformable structure undergoing large deformations, where in the two scalar subproblems the shear stress dependent migration of key species from the fluid into the structure is of special interest. Migrated species react and constitute mechanobiological remodeling, change of material behavior and finally the development of a stenosis. We present a sequentially staggered solution method coupling a monolithic FSI with a monolithic species subproblem. A convergence analysis of the computational model as well as specific high performance computing aspects are addressed. Examples are given demonstrating the benefits of a multiphysics approach for modeling atherosclerosis progression.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa230","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Moritz","last_name":"Thon","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa230","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Moritz","last_name":"Thon","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa230","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael","last_name":"Gee","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa230","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andr\u00e9","last_name":"Hemmler","affil