	</script><div class="title">A Multiphysics Approach for Early Atherosclerosis Progression</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Moritz Thon (TU Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa230","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Moritz","last_name":"Thon","affiliation":"TU Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present a framework for a coupled multiphysics approach for early atherosclerosis progression. It consists of a fluid-structure interaction (FSI) subproblem describing the cardiovascular mechanics, which is coupled to a multiple species subproblem describing the inflammatory processes in early atherosclerosis. In this context, the challenge is the coupling of an incompressible flow with a deformable structure undergoing large deformations, where in the two scalar subproblems the shear stress dependent migration of key species from the fluid into the structure is of special interest. Migrated species react and constitute mechanobiological remodeling, change of material behavior and finally the development of a stenosis. We present a sequentially staggered solution method coupling a monolithic FSI with a monolithic species subproblem. A convergence analysis of the computational model as well as specific high performance computing aspects are addressed. Examples are given demonstrating the benefits of a multiphysics approach for modeling atherosclerosis progression. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa243"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa243","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"An Integrated Electro-Mechano-Fluid Model for Cardiac Simulations","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We propose an integrated cardiac model coupling the electrophysiology, the mechanics, and the fluid dynamics of the left ventricle of a human heart. Our model combines the monodomain equation for the electric activity of the tissue, an orthotropic model for the mechanical description of the muscle in both its active and passive components, and the Navier-Stokes equations in a deforming geometry representing the left ventricle chamber. We consider a spatial approximation of the differential model based on the Finite Element method and Backward Differentiation Formulas for the time discretization. We focus on the approximation of the integrated model by means of a monolithic strategy for which we exploit preconditioning strategies based on block factorization. We perform numerical simulations in a high performance computing framework with both idealized and patient-specific geometries, the latter obtained from medical MRI images.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa243","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Antonello","last_name":"Gerbi","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa243","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Antonello","last_name":"Gerbi","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa243","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Luca","last_name":"Dede\u0027","affiliation":"Politecnico di Milano","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa243","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Davide","last_name":"Forti","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa243","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Alfio","last_name":"Quarteroni","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">An Integrated Electro-Mechano-Fluid Model for Cardiac Simulations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Antonello Gerbi (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa243","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Antonello","last_name":"Gerbi","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We propose an integrated cardiac model coupling the electrophysiology, the mechanics, and the fluid dynamics of the left ventricle of a human heart. Our model combines the monodomain equation for the electric activity of the tissue, an orthotropic model for the mechanical description of the muscle in both its active and passive components, and the Navier-Stokes equations in a deforming geometry representing the left ventricle chamber. We consider a spatial approximation of the differential model based on the Finite Element method and Backward Differentiation Formulas for the time discretization. We focus on the approximation of the integrated model by means of a monolithic strategy for which we exploit preconditioning strategies based on block factorization. We perform numerical simulations in a high performance computing framework with both idealized and patient-specific geometries, the latter obtained from medical MRI images. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa234"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
