	</script><div class="title">Scalable Domain Decomposition Solvers for Cardiac Electro-Mechanical Dynamics</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Luca F. Pavarino (University of Pavia, Italy)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa234","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Luca F.","last_name":"Pavarino","affiliation":"University of Pavia","country":"Italy","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> This talk focuses on scalable domain decomposition preconditioners for cardiac electro-mechanical dynamics. The coupled 3D models considered consist of 1) the quasi-static transversely isotropic finite elasticity equations for the deformation of the cardiac tissue; 2) the active tension model for the intracellular calcium dynamics and cross-bridge binding; 3) the anisotropic Bidomain model for the electrical current flow through the deforming cardiac tissue; 4) the membrane model of ventricular myocytes, including stretch-activated channels. The proposed finite element parallel solver employs Multilevel Additive Schwarz preconditioners for the solution of the discretized Bidomain equations and Newton-Krylov methods with AMG or BDDC preconditioners for the solution of the discretized nonlinear finite elasticity equations. The results of several parallel simulations show the scalability of both linear and nonlinear solvers and their application to the study of both normal and turbulent cardiac dynamics with re-entrant scroll waves, including different mechanisms of mechano-electrical feedbacks. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess185-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess185" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS28 Kinetic Simulations on HPC Platforms for Plasma Physics Applications (3/3): Parallelization and New Hardware</strong>, Room E</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="h