	</script><div class="title">Scalable and Fault-Tolerant Simulations with GENE and the Sparse Grid Combination Technique</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Mario Heene (University of Stuttgart, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa188","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mario","last_name":"Heene","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Two of the main challenges of future exascale HPC systems are scalability and fault tolerance. To ensure scalability on such extreme scales, new numerical algorithms are required that reduce the need for global communication and synchronization and thus the amount of data that has to be communicated. To cope with predicted failure rates, the algorithms furthermore have to be able to cope with hard and silent faults. Algorithm-based fault tolerance is required instead of checkpoint-restart. For the solution of higher-dimensional PDEs such as they arise in plasma physics, hierarchical numeric methods come to the rescue. We present algorithms for the solution of high-dimensional PDEs for sparse grids which we study for gyrokinetic simulations with GENE. They exploit a hierarchical extrapolation scheme, the sparse grid combination technique. Our approach uses an extra coarse-grained level of parallelism for scalability and a new numerical fault-tolerant scheme. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa178"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa178","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Two-Species Semi-Lagrangian Simulations for Solving the Vlasov-Poisson System in 2d2v","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The goal of the present work is to achieve high performance in a hybrid MPI\/OpenMP parallel semi-Lagrangian code. The domain of application is plasma physics: the semi-Lagrangian code simulates two-species 2d2v Vlasov-Poisson systems on cartesian grids with periodic boundary conditions. We investigate and compare two parallel approaches: one in which, for each time step, we have to transpose the parallel representation of the distribution functions among MPI processes, and one in which we perform domain decomposition. Memory and communication issues are discussed, and scalability results are shown. The code is written in C, with OpenMP pragmas, suitable for Central Processing Unit (CPU) and Many Integrated Cores (MIC) architectures. One application in mind is to run simulations on the Intel Knights Landing (KNL) nodes of the Marconi supercomputer. Extensions to Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) architectures are envisaged with OpenACC directives.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa178","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yann","last_name":"Barsamian","affiliation":"University of Strasbourg","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa178","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yann","last_name":"Barsamian","affiliation":"University of Strasbourg","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa178","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michel","last_name":"Mehrenberger","affiliation":"University of Strasbourg","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Two-Species Semi-Lagrangian Simulations for Solving the Vlasov-Poisson System in 2d2v</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Yann Barsamian (University of Strasbourg, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa178","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yann","last_name":"Barsamian","affiliation":"University of Strasbourg","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The goal of the present work is to achieve high performance in a hybrid MPI/OpenMP parallel semi-Lagrangian code. The domain of application is plasma physics: the semi-Lagrangian code simulates two-species 2d2v Vlasov-Poisson systems on cartesian grids with periodic boundary conditions. We investigate and compare two parallel approaches: one in which, for each time step, we have to transpose the parallel representation of the distribution functions among MPI processes, and one in which we perform domain decomposition. Memory and communication issues are discussed, and scalability results are shown. The code is written in C, with OpenMP pragmas, suitable for Central Processing Unit (CPU) and Many Integrated Cores (MIC) architectures. One application in mind is to run simulations on the Intel Knights Landing (KNL) nodes of the Marconi supercomputer. Extensions to Graphics Processing Unit (GPU) architectures are envisaged with OpenACC directives. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa194"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa194","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Hybrid OpenMP\/MPI Parallelization of the Charge Deposition Step in the Global Gyrokinetic Particle-In-Cell Code ORB5","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Gyrokinetic simulations are computationally extremely demanding due to the high dimensionality of the physical phase space and the interplay between plasma particles and electromagnetic fields. It is thus essential to make full use of the available numerical resources to be able to simulate more complex physical problems. With the aim of optimizing the gyrokinetic Particle-In-Cell code ORB5 towards exascale computing, a particle sorting method is implemented to increase data locality. Furthermore, different algorithms are used to improve vectorization, and the MPI parallelization is complemented with OpenMP. More specifically, we shall focus on the particle to grid operations involved in the PIC charge deposition step. The latter is critical to parallelize using a shared memory paradigm due to the scatter operations involved. We will present the different algorithms and parallelization schemes implemented in the ORB5 charge deposition step and how they affect the speedup compared to the base MPI case.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa194","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Emmanuel","last_name":"Lanti","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa194","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Emmanuel","last_name":"Lanti","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa194","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stephan","last_name":"Brunner","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa194","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Claudio","last_name":"Gheller","affiliation":"ET