	</script><div class="title">Prediction of the Node to Node Communication Costs of a New Gyrokinetic Code with Toroidal Domain</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Andreas Jocksch (ETH Zurich / CSCS, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa140","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Jocksch","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Gyrokinetic codes running at large scale play a central role in plasma physics. We apply virtual decompositions of the toroidal domain in three dimensions in addition to domain cloning to existing simulations done with the Orb5 code. We determine the communication volume and the number of communication partners per timestep for every virtual subdomain (node) for the particles and the structured mesh. Thus the scaling properties of a code with the new domain decompositions and unchanged Orb5 numerics are derived for simple models of the computer network and processing units. For a typical simulation with 256 million particles and a mesh of 256x512x256 grid points scaling to the entire Piz Daint should be achieved with the new domain decompositions suggested. The knowledge obtained can be used for the design of new gyrokinetic codes and the design of new supercomputers. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess162-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess162" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS29 Mathematical Methods in Molecular Simulation for Computational Drug Design</strong>, Room C1</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right"> <