	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics, Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>This minisymposium will bring together researchers who use molecular simulation in their respected fields, in order to discuss recent advances and to exchange experiences and ideas. The focus of this minisymposium is the analysis of very huge biological and chemical data sets arising from the simulation of complex molecular systems, by means of developing efficient algorithms and their implementation on high-performance supercomputers.<br /> <br /> This approach is necessary for designing smart drug-like molecules for Precision Medicine. The tools include, but are not limited to, algebraic stochastic dimension reduction methods such as nonnegative matrix decomposition for very large data sets obtained from atomic spectroscopy, Markov State Models (MSMs), Multiscale Methods in Time and Space for studying molecular conformation, PDEs for the analysis of multivalent binding kinetics for biochemical systems, and spectral clustering.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa196"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa196","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Kinetics of Multivalent Bindings","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In medical drug design multivalent bindings of ligands and receptors is a critical biological process, i.e. inflamed tissue or viruses are receptors; and molecular drugs such as peptides act as ligands that bond with these receptors. Simultaneous or sequential binding of relatively weak binding partners increase the overall binding affinity. Therefore modern drug design tries to synthesize artificial multivalent bindings in order to increase the binding affinity of the drug to the virus. This talk aims at giving insights into the transition networks of ligand-receptor interactions and their effect on kinetics. Monovalent and also bivalent binding processes have been studied more or less extensively, but quantitative models for n-valent bindings are still missing. To bridge this gap a PDE approach for the binding and rebinding processes is used. The diffusion process is modeled by the Fokker-Planck equation. These modeled binding dynamics are compared with experimental data from organic chemistry.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa196","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa196","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Kinetics of Multivalent Bindings</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Franziska Erlekam (Zuse Institute Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa196","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In medical drug design multivalent bindings of ligands and receptors is a critical biological process, i.e. inflamed tissue or viruses are receptors; and molecular drugs such as peptides act as ligands that bond with these receptors. Simultaneous or sequential binding of relatively weak binding partners increase the overall binding affinity. Therefore modern drug design tries to synthesize artificial multivalent bindings in order to increase the binding affinity of the drug to the virus. This talk aims at giving insights into the transition networks of ligand-receptor interactions and their effect on kinetics. Monovalent and also bivalent binding processes have been studied more or less extensively, but quantitative models for n-valent bindings are still missing. To bridge this gap a PDE approach for the binding and rebinding processes is used. The diffusion process is modeled by the Fokker-Planck equation. These modeled binding dynamics are compared with experimental data from organic chemistry. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa202"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa202","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Generalized Perron Cluster Analysis for Non-Equilibrium Steady State Systems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In a Markov State Model (MSM) an underlying stochastic process is described by a (small) transition matrix between clustered states. Under the assumption that this stochastic process has a metastable character, i.e., the system stays mostly in a metastable set of states and switches only rarely between these sets, the stochastic process is described by a low dimensional basis. In this sense, an MSM is a coarse graining method. In many MSM it is assumed that the underlying process is reversible, i.e., the process meets the detailed balance condition. When considering Non-Equilibrium Steady States, the underlying Markov chain is no longer reversible and thus the eigenvalue structure, being crucial for MSM, can no longer be employed. To overcome this we present a novel MSM method (GenPCCA), which finds a low dimensional description of even nonreversible Markov processes by using a Schur decomposition instead. Applications of the method are shown.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa202","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa202","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa202","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Konstantin","last_name":"Fackeldey","affiliation":"TU Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Generalized Perron Cluster Analysis for Non-Equilibrium Steady State Systems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Franziska Erlekam (Zuse Institute Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa202","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Franziska","last_name":"Erlekam","affiliation":"Zuse Institute Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In a Markov State Model (MSM) an underlying stochastic process is described by a (small) transition matrix between clustered states. Under the assumption that this stochastic process has a metastable character, i.e., the system stays mostly in a metastable set of states and switches only rarely between these sets, the stochastic process is described by a low dimensional basis. In this sense, an MSM is a coarse graining method. In many MSM it is assumed that the underlying process is reversible, i.e., the process meets the detailed balance condition. When considering Non-Equilibrium Steady States, the underlying Markov chain is no longer reversible and thus the eigenvalue structure, being crucial for MSM, can no longer be employed. To overcome this we present a novel MSM method (GenPCCA), which finds a low dimensional description of even nonreversible Markov processes by using a Schur decomposition instead. Applications of the method are shown. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa200"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa200","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Markov State Models with Reweighting","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Molecular Dynamics simulations are characterized by metastable states and transitions that occur at different timescales. Recent studies have proven, through Markov State Models analysis, that the timescales strongly depend on the potential energy of the molecule. Even small perturbations produce large scale effects on the dynamics of the system. The potential energy perturbation has effects on the probability measure of the system. We exploit the Girsanov theorem to predict the change of measure. This leads to redefining the time correlation function under the new probability measure and to construct the MSM of the system under perturbation. The method can be used to predict the timescales of a molecular system without rerunning molecular dynamics simulations when an external force is applied to the potential energy. In particular, it is relevant to force-field optimization. We present preliminary results for alanine dipeptide and a benchmark test that shows the efficiency of the method.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa200","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Luca","last_name":"Donati","affiliation":"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa200","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Luca","last_name":"Donati","affiliation":"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Markov State Models with Reweighting</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Luca Donati (Freie Universität Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa200","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Luca","last_name":"Donati","affiliation":"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Molecular Dynamics simulations are characterized by metastable states and transitions that occur at different timescales. Recent studies have proven, through Markov State Models analysis, that the timescales strongly depend on the potential energy of the molecule. Even small perturbations produce large scale effects on the dynamics of the system. The potential energy perturbation has effects on the probability measure of the system. We exploit the Girsanov theorem to predict the change of measure. This leads to redefining the time correlation function under the new probability measure and to construct the MSM of the system under perturbation. The method can be used to predict the timescales of a molecular system without rerunning molecular dynamics simulations when an external force is applied to the potential energy. In particular, it is relevant to force-field optimization. We present preliminary results for alanine dipeptide and a benchmark test that shows the efficiency of the method. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa198"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:30 - 16:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa198","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Applications of Nonnegative Matrix Factorization in Spectroscopy","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The main objective of the analysis of time-resolved Raman spectra is to reconstruct the spectral bands of the different compounds involved in the reaction as well as the process of relative concentrations of these compounds during the reaction process. A popular approach in chemoinformatics is to factor the data matrix into the product of two non-negative matrices, one representing spectral bands and the other relative concentrations of compounds.\nGiven the data matrix, our first main treatment is to perform Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) on data matrix. The left SVD-matrix U is supposed to represent the time-resolved relative concentrations of the compounds. But this matrix may not satisfy the properties of a concentration matrix (non-negativity and row sum one). Thus, we apply a spectral clustering algorithm (Inner Simplex) on U in order to overcome this obstacle. Finally, we present a nonlinear optimization framework in order to reconstruct the spectral bands matrix.","begin_time":"15:30","begin_timestamp":"1522243800","end_time":"16:00","end_timestamp":"1522245600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa198","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Amir","last_name":"Niknejad","affiliation":"College of Mount Saint Vincent","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa198","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Amir","last_name":"Niknejad","affiliation":"College of Mount Saint Vincent","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Room C1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Applications of Nonnegative Matrix Factorization in Spectroscopy</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Amir Niknejad (College of Mount Saint Vincent, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa198","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Amir","last_name":"Niknejad","affiliation":"College of Mount Saint Vincent","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The main objective of the analysis of time-resolved Raman spectra is to reconstruct the spectral bands of the different compounds involved in the reaction as well as the process of relative concentrations of these compounds during the reaction process. A popular approach in chemoinformatics is to factor the data matrix into the product of two non-negative matrices, one representing spectral bands and the other relative concentrations of compounds.Given the data matrix, our first main treatment is to perform Singular Value Decomposition (SVD) on data matrix. The left SVD-matrix U is supposed to represent the time-resolved relative concentrations of the compounds. But this matrix may not satisfy the properties of a concentration matrix (non-negativity and row sum one). Thus, we apply a spectral clustering algorithm (Inner Simplex) on U in order to overcome this obstacle. Finally, we present a nonlinear optimization framework in order to reconstruct the spectral bands matrix. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess189-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess189" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS30 Particle-Based Methods for Simulations in Life Sciences, Fluids and Materials (2/2)</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 005</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"> <svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height