	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences, Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The main objective of this symposium is to bring international scientists together working in the area of particle-based modeling with applications in Life Sciences, Fluids, and Materials. Numerical methods include but are not restricted to Coarse-Graining Molecular Dynamics (CG-MD), Dissipative Particle Dynamics (DPD), Smoothed Dissipative Particle Dynamics (SDPD), Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH), Lattice-Boltzmann Method (LBM), Moving Particle Semi-Implicit Method (MPS), Brownian Dynamics (BD) and Stokesian Dynamics (SD). The goal of minisymposium is, on one hand, to share state-of-the-art results in various applications of particle-based methods and, on the other to discuss technical issues of the computational modeling.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa258"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa258","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Bayesian Uncertainty Quantification and Propagation for Dissipative Particle Dynamics","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Large Data, advanced sampling methods and High Performance Computing are changing the landscape of Computational Life Sciences. We integrate these three components in a Bayesian uncertainty quantification and prediction framework. In this talk we show the application of this framework to blood flow models using Dissipative Particle Dynamics (DPD). We calibrate the parameters of the DPD solvent using available data on hydrodynamic correlations. We also quantify uncertainties of the blood models using data on Red Blood Cell (RBC) stretching and its rotation frequency in the shear flow. A computational bottleneck for Bayesian inference is the cost of the DPD simulations. We implement a Neural Network surrogate model which is shown to predict the rotation frequency of a RBC in a shear flow given the model parameters. We compare the obtained DPD\/RBC parameters with those used in literature and showcase results from simulations with quantified uncertainties.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa258","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Lina","last_name":"Kulakova","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa258","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Lina","last_name":"Kulakova","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa258","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa258","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Athena","last_name":"Economides","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":