	</script><div class="title">Resilience in Extreme-Scale Iterative Linear Solvers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Wilfried Gansterer (University of Vienna, Austria)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa116","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Wilfried","last_name":"Gansterer","affiliation":"University of Vienna","country":"Austria","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Node failures, as well as increased global communication latencies, are considered important challenges for extreme-scale computing. Long-running scientific simulations often spend a considerable fraction of their runtime on solving large sparse linear systems of equations. Common iterative algorithms for solving those large sparse linear systems are Krylov solvers like the conjugate gradient (CG) and the generalized minimal residual (GMRES) methods.Pipelined variants of GMRES and CG, which overlap global communication latencies with computation and non-global communication, have been proposed. Moreover, interpolation-restart schemes have been proposed for recovering from node failures in Krylov subspace methods. For improving both scalability and resilience of Krylov solvers we investigate combining these two ideas. We illustrate how resulting resilient pipelined CG and GMRES methods behave for different node failure distributions and interpolation-restart strategies. We investigate novel interpolation-restart schemes which strive to reduce communication and analyze the trade-off between resilience, communication cost, and convergence rate. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa172"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa172","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Scaling and Energy Analysis for a Resilient ULFM-Based PDE Solver","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present a resilient task-based domain-decomposition preconditioner for PDEs built on top of User-Level Fault Mitigation Message Passing Interface (ULFM-MPI). The algorithm reformulates the PDE as a sampling problem, followed by a robust regression-based solution update that is resilient to silent data corruptions (SDCs). We adopt a server-client model where all state information is held by the servers, while clients only serve as computational units. The task-based nature of the algorithm and ULFM complement each other to support missing tasks, making the application resilient to clients failing. We present scaling results on Edison (NERSC), for a nominal and a fault-injected case, showing that even in the presence of faults, scalability tested up to 50k cores is within 90%. We quantify the scaling variability due to the presence of faults. Finally, we discuss the performance with respect to subdomain size, server\/client configuration, and the interplay between energy and resilience.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa172","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Francesco","last_name":"Rizzi","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa172","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Francesco","last_name":"Rizzi","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa172","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Brandon","last_name":"Cook","affiliation":"Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa172","title":"Ms.","bi