	</script><div class="title">CHE-01 A Molecular Dynamics Study of the Thermodynamics of Attachment of Saccharides to Halloysite</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Riccardo Innocenti Malini (Empa, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post142","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Riccardo","last_name":"Innocenti Malini","affiliation":"Empa","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post142s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Halloysites are a class of tubular alumino-silicates often integrated within polymeric matrices as mechanical reinforcement or/and as drug carriers. To maximize the strength of the final material and control drug delivery, it is important to evaluate the polymer-mineral interaction at the interface. Here, Molecular Dynamics simulations have been used to investigate the adsorption of different saccharides on the halloysite surface. By using Umbrella Sampling, we extract the change in free energy related to the attachment of protonated and unprotonated chitosan, chitin and alginate. These saccharides were chosen because of their different functionalities and their importance towards biotechnological applications. The results show that all saccharides can bind to the surface, even though alginate does so when additional cations are present in the solution. By running the free energies calculations at different temperatures, we extracted the enthalpy and entropy of reaction, thereby allowing us to understand the binding driving force. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post116"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post116","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CHE-02 DBCSR: A Sparse Matrix Multiplication Library for Electronic Structure Codes","scientific_track":"Chemistry \u0026 Materials","abstract":"Sparse matrix-matrix multiplication is an essential building block for a wide range of algorithms in various scientific fields. For this task, the sparse matrix library DBCSR [1] has been developed. Its multi-layered structure automatically takes care of and optimizes several computational aspects like parallelism (MPI, OMP, GPU), data (cache) locality and on-the-fly filtering. We introduce a framework for sparse tensor linear algebra, which enables low-scaling electronic structure methods beyond density  functional theory. This framework is based on DBCSR for mapping tensor contractions block-wise to matrix-matrix multiplications. We also report on optimizations and performance comparison of the MPI communications, based on 2.5D algorithm, and the backends, namely\nLIBXSMM and CUDA. Furthermore, in order to facilitate usability, a suite of tools has been developed to auto-generate the full documentation of the library. [1] The CP2K developers group, DBCSR is freely available from: http:\/\/dbcsr.cp2k.org\/, 2017","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post116","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Gl\u00f6ss","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post116","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Gl\u00f6ss","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post116","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"J\u00fcrg","last_name":"Hutter","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post116","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"A