	</script><div class="title">CHE-02 DBCSR: A Sparse Matrix Multiplication Library for Electronic Structure Codes</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Andreas Glöss (University of Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post116","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"Gl\u00f6ss","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post116s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Sparse matrix-matrix multiplication is an essential building block for a wide range of algorithms in various scientific fields. For this task, the sparse matrix library DBCSR [1] has been developed. Its multi-layered structure automatically takes care of and optimizes several computational aspects like parallelism (MPI, OMP, GPU), data (cache) locality and on-the-fly filtering. We introduce a framework for sparse tensor linear algebra, which enables low-scaling electronic structure methods beyond density functional theory. This framework is based on DBCSR for mapping tensor contractions block-wise to matrix-matrix multiplications. We also report on optimizations and performance comparison of the MPI communications, based on 2.5D algorithm, and the backends, namelyLIBXSMM and CUDA. Furthermore, in order to facilitate usability, a suite of tools has been developed to auto-generate the full documentation of the library. [1] The CP2K developers group, DBCSR is freely available from: http://dbcsr.cp2k.org/, 2017 </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post145"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post145","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CHE-03 First-Principles Study on Interfaces between Sulfide Electrolyte and Oxide Cathode in All-Solid-State Battery","scientific_track":"Chemistry \u0026 Materials","abstract":"All-solid-state Li-ion batteries have been regarded as promising next-generation batteries. However, large interfacial resistance for ion transport is usually observed even if promising sulfide electrolyte is set on typical oxide cathode. These phenomena have been explained with structural disorder and space-charge layer of Li ion around the interface, though little is known about the atomistic mechanism. Then, we investigated probable heterogeneous interfaces between a sulfide electrolyte (\u0026#946;-Li3PS4) and an oxide cathode (LiCoO2) by DFT+U calculations with some techniques to evaluate the stable matching of incommensurate solid-solid interface and the site-dependent chemical potential of Li ion. The results indicate that the Li depletion can proceed at the beginning of the charge process, corresponding to the space-charge layer scenario. Furthermore, we found that the Co and P mixing across the interface is preferred, while the Li-depletion tendency still exists. Therefore, the Li-depletion seems a major factor of the interfacial resistance.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post145","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yoshitaka","last_name":"Tateyama","affiliation":"National Institute for Materials Science","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post145","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yoshitaka","last_name":"Tateyama","affiliation":"National Institute for Materials Science","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post145","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jun","last_name":"Haruyama","affiliation":"National Institute for Mate