	</script><div class="title">CHE-04 Mapping and Classifying Molecules from a High-Throughput Structural Database</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Felix Musil (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post136","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Musil","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post136s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> High-throughput computational materials design promises to greatly accelerate the process of discovering new materials and compounds, and of optimizing their properties. The large databases of structures and properties that result from computational searches, as well as the agglomeration of data of heterogeneous provenance leads to considerable challenges when it comes to navigating the database, representing its structure at a glance, understanding structure–property relations, eliminating duplicates and identifying inconsistencies. Here we present a case study, based on a data set of conformers of amino acids and dipeptides, of how machine-learning techniques can help addressing these issues. We will exploit a recently-developed strategy to define a metric between structures, and use it as the basis of both clustering and dimensionality reduction techniques—showing how these can help reveal structure–property relations, identify outliers and inconsistent structures, and rationalize how perturbations (e.g. binding of ions to the molecule) affect the stability of different conformers. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post123"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post123","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CHE-05 Soft-Sphere Continuum Solvation in Electronic Structure Calculations","scientific_track":"Chemistry \u0026 Materials","abstract":"An implicit solvation approach is presented to handle solutes and surfaces in contact with dielectric environments and electrolytes in electronic-structure calculations. The interface between the quantum solute and the surrounding environment is described by a continuum and differentiable permittivity, built up with atomic-centered \u201csoft\u201d spheres. It smoothly connects the cavity inner part and the bulk solvent. The electrostatic problem is solved by means of a recently developed generalized Poisson solver based on Interpolating Scaling Functions, free of finite difference filters. The continuum permittivity allows to compute analytically the non-electrostatic contributions to the solvation free energy, function of the cavity volume and surface. The whole methodology is computationally robust and gives high accuracy and parallel efficiency, keeping computational efforts and runtime at vacuum level. Its calibration as well as several applications on reaction barriers and structure predictions in solution will be presented, which prove the powerful of such explicit\/implicit treatment.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post123","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Giuseppe","last_name":"Fisicaro","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post123","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Giuseppe","last_name":"Fisicaro","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post123","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliviero","last_name":"Andreussi","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":