	</script><div class="title">CHE-05 Soft-Sphere Continuum Solvation in Electronic Structure Calculations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Giuseppe Fisicaro (University of Basel, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post123","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Giuseppe","last_name":"Fisicaro","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post123s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> An implicit solvation approach is presented to handle solutes and surfaces in contact with dielectric environments and electrolytes in electronic-structure calculations. The interface between the quantum solute and the surrounding environment is described by a continuum and differentiable permittivity, built up with atomic-centered “soft” spheres. It smoothly connects the cavity inner part and the bulk solvent. The electrostatic problem is solved by means of a recently developed generalized Poisson solver based on Interpolating Scaling Functions, free of finite difference filters. The continuum permittivity allows to compute analytically the non-electrostatic contributions to the solvation free energy, function of the cavity volume and surface. The whole methodology is computationally robust and gives high accuracy and parallel efficiency, keeping computational efforts and runtime at vacuum level. Its calibration as well as several applications on reaction barriers and structure predictions in solution will be presented, which prove the powerful of such explicit/implicit treatment. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post132"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post132","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CHE-06 Solvent-Aware Interfaces in Continuum Solvation","scientific_track":"Chemistry \u0026 Materials","abstract":"Continuum models of solvation are well-assessed tools in chemistry and are becoming increasingly important in simulations of materials. Key ingredient of any continuum model, affecting its accuracy and faithfulness, is the definition of the cavity, i.e. the interface between what is treated with full quantum-mechanical details (solute) and what is modeled as a continuum (environment). Different methodologies introduce sharp or smooth functions of the atomic or electronic degrees of freedom of the solute. Straightforward local formulations fail in correctly describing inaccessible regions of space, in which the solvent should not be present. Typical examples of these situations include empty pockets in molecular systems and hollow sites or channels in crystals. Here we present a non-local definition of the cavity to correct artifacts coming from inaccessible regions of space smaller than a predetermined solvent radius, allowing to maintain a continuously differentiable expression of the interface with a moderate computational overhead.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post132","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliviero","last_name":"Andreussi","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post132","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliviero","last_name":"Andreussi","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post132","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Giuseppe","last_name":"Fisicaro","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post132","title":"