	</script><div class="title">CHE-06 Solvent-Aware Interfaces in Continuum Solvation</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Oliviero Andreussi (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post132","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliviero","last_name":"Andreussi","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post132s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Continuum models of solvation are well-assessed tools in chemistry and are becoming increasingly important in simulations of materials. Key ingredient of any continuum model, affecting its accuracy and faithfulness, is the definition of the cavity, i.e. the interface between what is treated with full quantum-mechanical details (solute) and what is modeled as a continuum (environment). Different methodologies introduce sharp or smooth functions of the atomic or electronic degrees of freedom of the solute. Straightforward local formulations fail in correctly describing inaccessible regions of space, in which the solvent should not be present. Typical examples of these situations include empty pockets in molecular systems and hollow sites or channels in crystals. Here we present a non-local definition of the cavity to correct artifacts coming from inaccessible regions of space smaller than a predetermined solvent radius, allowing to maintain a continuously differentiable expression of the interface with a moderate computational overhead. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post128"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post128","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CLI-03 ESCAPE: Accelerating Extreme-Scale Numerical Weather Prediction","scientific_track":"Climate \u0026 Weather","abstract":"The algorithms underlying numerical weather prediction (NWP) and climate models that have been developed in the past few decades face an increasing challenge caused by the paradigm shift imposed by hardware vendors towards more energy-efficient devices. In order to provide a sustainable path to exascale HPC, applications become increasingly restricted by energy consumption. As a result, the emerging diverse and complex hardware solutions have a large impact on the programming models traditionally used in NWP software, triggering a rethink of design choices for future software frameworks.  To address the challenge of extreme-scale, energy-efficient high-performance computing, ECMWF is leading the ESCAPE project, a European funded project involving regional NWP centres, Universities, HPC centres and hardware vendors. The aim is not to reduce the stringent requirements for Earth-system prediction but to combine scientific and computer-science expertise for defining and co-designing the necessary steps towards affordable, exascale high-performance simulations of weather and climate.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post128","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Willem","last_name":"Deconinck","affiliation":"ECMWF","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post128","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Willem","last_name":"Deconinck","affiliation":"ECMWF","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"post128s2.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">CLI-03 ESCAPE: Accelerating Extreme-Scale Numerical Weather Prediction</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Willem Deconinck (ECMWF, United Kingdom)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post128","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Willem","last_name":"Deconinck","affiliation":"ECMWF","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Climate &amp; Weather</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post128s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The algorithms underlying numerical weather prediction (NWP) and climate models that have been developed in the past few decades face an increasing challenge caused by the paradigm shift imposed by hardware vendors towards more energy-efficient devices. In order to provide a sustainable path to exascale HPC, applications become increasingly restricted by energy consumption. As a result, the emerging diverse and complex hardware solutions have a large impact on the programming models traditionally used in NWP software, triggering a rethink of design choices for future software frameworks. To address the challenge of extreme-scale, energy-efficient high-performance computing, ECMWF is leading the ESCAPE project, a European funded project involving regional NWP centres, Universities, HPC centres and hardware vendors. The aim is not to reduce the stringent requirements for Earth-system prediction but to combine scientific and computer-science expertise for defining and co-designing the necessary steps towards affordable, exascale high-performance simulations of weather and climate. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post144"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post144","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CLI-04 GridTools: A C++ Library for Computations on Grids","scientific_track":"Climate \u0026 Weather","abstract":"GridTools is a set of libraries to execute stencil-like computations on a variety of different parallel architectures. The central component of GridTools is the stencil-composition library, which allows high-level composition of multiple stencil applications while the platform specific backends deal with its efficient execution. Other components deal with inter-node communication, boundary conditions and storage infrastructure. The target applications for GridTools are regional weather models (regular grids) as well as global weather and climate simulations (irregular grids). In this poster we describe the software structure and capabilities of the GridTools libraries. Currently supported architectures are clusters of multicore (x86) and multi-GPU nodes. We are currently working on supporting additional platforms, including Xeon Phi, and ARM based machines.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mauro","last_name":"Bianco","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mauro","last_name":"Bianco","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Paolo","last_name":"Crosetto","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliver","last_name":"Fuhrer","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post144","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stefan","last_name":"Moosbrugger","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","count