	</script><div class="title">CLI-05 High-Performance C++ in Weather Prediction: Challenges, Achievements and Future Models</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Pascal Spörri (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post135","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Pascal","last_name":"Sp\u00f6rri","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Climate &amp; Weather</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post135s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Scientific codes run on a multitude of systems. Some of them are purely CPU based, others are hybrid machines containing accelerators. A performance-portable code makes it easy to transfer the code from one system to the next. We present a hybrid C++/Fortran approach that makes use of a C++ DSL called STELLA to obtain a performance portable (CPU/GPU) port of the COSMO dynamical core. The resulting code is used to compute the daily weather forecast at MeteoSwiss. We achieved a 1.5x speedup compared to the Fortran reference on CPU, and an additional 2.1x speedup on GPUs. With several extensions to STELLA we are able to automatically analyze and optimize the implementation. Enabling us to increase the performance of the code by an additional 1.4x on our production system. The project has been a success in terms of performance and maintainability. We are able to propose improvements to future implementations. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post151"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post151","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CLI-06 Large Scale Climate Simulations with COSMO","scientific_track":"Climate \u0026 Weather","abstract":"In recent years MeteoSwiss, C2SM, CSCS and ETH developed a GPU-enabled version of COSMO, a regional numerical weather prediction and climate model. A hybrid porting strategy that uses OpenACC directives for the physical parameterizations and a domain specific language for the dynamical core allows to retain a single source code that runs efficiently on traditional CPUs as well as NVIDIA GPUs. Thanks to this approach MeteoSwiss was able to increase the resolution of the operational weather forecasting model to 1.1 km. Furthermore climate simulations over Europe performed at ETH took profit from an increase in resolution to up to 2.2 km. In this work we show results on scalability of the model beyond 1000 GPUs on large domains on the Piz Daint supercomputer. Our effort demonstrates the usability of COSMO for near-global domains (excluding the poles) at high resolution, far outside the typical domain of a regional model.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post151","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hannes","last_name":"Vogt","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post151","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hannes","last_name":"Vogt","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post151","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oliver","last_name":"Fuhrer","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post151","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Torsten","last_name":"Hoefler","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post151","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Grzegorz","l