	</script><div class="title">CLI-06 Large Scale Climate Simulations with COSMO</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Hannes Vogt (ETH Zurich / CSCS, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post151","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hannes","last_name":"Vogt","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Climate &amp; Weather</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In recent years MeteoSwiss, C2SM, CSCS and ETH developed a GPU-enabled version of COSMO, a regional numerical weather prediction and climate model. A hybrid porting strategy that uses OpenACC directives for the physical parameterizations and a domain specific language for the dynamical core allows to retain a single source code that runs efficiently on traditional CPUs as well as NVIDIA GPUs. Thanks to this approach MeteoSwiss was able to increase the resolution of the operational weather forecasting model to 1.1 km. Furthermore climate simulations over Europe performed at ETH took profit from an increase in resolution to up to 2.2 km. In this work we show results on scalability of the model beyond 1000 GPUs on large domains on the Piz Daint supercomputer. Our effort demonstrates the usability of COSMO for near-global domains (excluding the poles) at high resolution, far outside the typical domain of a regional model. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post125"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post125","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CLI-07 Reproducible Climate and Weather Simulations: an Application to the COSMO Model","scientific_track":"Climate \u0026 Weather","abstract":"We define bit-reproducibility as the ability of a simulation code to produce identical results across architectures. Such a feature offers many advantages ranging from testing and debugging simplification to a deployment maintaining numerical consistency. However achieving bit-reproducibility with a full-fledged weather and climate model may be perceived as a daunting task. In the crClim project we aim to obtain identical results on CPUs and GPUs with the COSMO model. We thus analyze COSMO to identify sources of non-reproducibility and propose strategies to solve them. Key sources of non-reproducibility stem from reductions, computation of transcendental functions and floating-point operation transformations by the compiler. To address these we avoid reductions, provide portable functions and control floating-point optimizations. Results indicate that bit-reproducibility across different hardware architecture is achievable and does not necessarily imply an excessive performance penalty. The penalty of the reproducible COSMO does not exceed 26% on CPU and 11% on GPU.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christophe","last_name":"Charpilloz","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christophe","last_name":"Charpilloz","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post125","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andrea","last_name":"Arteaga","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post125","title":"Dr."