	</script><div class="title">CLI-07 Reproducible Climate and Weather Simulations: an Application to the COSMO Model</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Christophe Charpilloz (MeteoSwiss, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christophe","last_name":"Charpilloz","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Climate &amp; Weather</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post125s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We define bit-reproducibility as the ability of a simulation code to produce identical results across architectures. Such a feature offers many advantages ranging from testing and debugging simplification to a deployment maintaining numerical consistency. However achieving bit-reproducibility with a full-fledged weather and climate model may be perceived as a daunting task. In the crClim project we aim to obtain identical results on CPUs and GPUs with the COSMO model. We thus analyze COSMO to identify sources of non-reproducibility and propose strategies to solve them. Key sources of non-reproducibility stem from reductions, computation of transcendental functions and floating-point operation transformations by the compiler. To address these we avoid reductions, provide portable functions and control floating-point optimizations. Results indicate that bit-reproducibility across different hardware architecture is achievable and does not necessarily imply an excessive performance penalty. The penalty of the reproducible COSMO does not exceed 26% on CPU and 11% on GPU. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post118"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
