		{"id":"post104","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jan","last_name":"Zapletal","affiliation":"TU Ostrava","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post104s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The presented poster concentrates on an efficient implementation of quadrature routines building the core of the boundary element method (BEM) for solving partial differential equations. We discuss two popular approaches treating the singular integrals specific for BEM, namely their regularization and subsequent four-dimensional tensor Gauss-Legendre scheme and the more challenging semi-analytic quadrature. We focus on manual vectorization of the routines by appropriate refactorization of underlying data structures and the utilization of OpenMP pragmas. The proposed techniques perform well for the standard BEM assembly as well as for the assembly accelerated by the adaptive cross approximation. Numerical experiments have been performed both on multi- and many-core systems including the Knights Landing processors representing the Intel Xeon Phi architecture. The discussed approach is implemented within the BEM4I library developed by the authors at the IT4Innovations National Supercomputing Center. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post152"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
