	</script><div class="title">CSM-06 Efficient On-The-Fly Operator Assembly for HPC Finite Element codes</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Simon Bauer (Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post124","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Simon","last_name":"Bauer","affiliation":"Ludwig Maximilian University of Munich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post124s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> A current trend in high-performance finite-element codes is to use \emph{matrix-free} approaches that either use an on-the-fly evaluation of the weak-form or alternatively on-the-fly computation and application of local stencils. While this alleviates the issue of memory-boundedness of the codes,in the case of problems on non-polyhedral domains assembly of the node stencils still constitutes a major portion of the overall runtime. We, recently, proposed a novel approach that replaces this expensive assembly by a low cost polynomial approximation. In our contribution we demonstrate, how this method can be extended to systems of PDEs and problems with varying coefficients. Since actual parallel efficiency is as important as algorithmic complexity we also detail a number the performance optimizations we performed to obtain excellent code performance and scalability. Furthermore we provide results of a geophysical simulation with real Earth data and a global resolution at the kilometer scale. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post131"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post131","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CSM-07 Flexible and High-Performance Stencil Codes with GridTools4Py","scientific_track":"Computer Science \u0026 Applied Mathematics","abstract":"Stencil codes perform a series of sweeps over arrays (2D or 3D) updating most or all elements. To update a data entry, p, the code accesses a pattern of neighboring cells around p; this pattern is called a \u201cstencil\u201d. Traditionally, stencil codes are written in low-level languages such as Fortran or C\/C++ in order to achieve superior performance. These approaches, however, feature repetitive boilerplate code and face considerable challenges when implementing and validating complex scientific models. In this work, we present use cases for GridTools4Py (GT4Py), a Python package to define stencil operators at a high level, leveraging Python\u2019s features and rich ecosystem to enable a fast and interactive development cycle. Users have the flexibility of executing stencil codes directly in Python for prototyping, or compile them into a high performance module, using the GridTools C++ library, all the while working from powerful frontends like Jupyter notebooks.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post131","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alberto","last_name":"Madonna","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post131","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alberto","last_name":"Madonna","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post131","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Lucas","last_name":"Benedicic","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post131","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felipe A.","last_name":"Cruz","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ 