	</script><div class="title">CSM-07 Flexible and High-Performance Stencil Codes with GridTools4Py</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alberto Madonna (ETH Zurich / CSCS, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post131","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alberto","last_name":"Madonna","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post131s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Stencil codes perform a series of sweeps over arrays (2D or 3D) updating most or all elements. To update a data entry, p, the code accesses a pattern of neighboring cells around p; this pattern is called a “stencil”. Traditionally, stencil codes are written in low-level languages such as Fortran or C/C++ in order to achieve superior performance. These approaches, however, feature repetitive boilerplate code and face considerable challenges when implementing and validating complex scientific models. In this work, we present use cases for GridTools4Py (GT4Py), a Python package to define stencil operators at a high level, leveraging Python’s features and rich ecosystem to enable a fast and interactive development cycle. Users have the flexibility of executing stencil codes directly in Python for prototyping, or compile them into a high performance module, using the GridTools C++ library, all the while working from powerful frontends like Jupyter notebooks. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post147"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
