		{"id":"post122","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andrea","last_name":"Arteaga","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post122s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Numerical methods to solve partial differential equations are typically chosen on the basis of personal preference, experience and numerical experiments. The crucial process of selecting a solution algorithm and its parameters is subject to a significant bias if a rigorous methodology is not employed. In this contribution we develop such a methodology to select the best suited solver for a given problem. In order to choose the solver which minimizes the runtime under an accuracy constraint, we define an optimization problem. We solve this problem by introducing models for the prediction of the accuracy and the performance of Finite Difference solvers. With numerical experiments performed on different architectures, we show how our methodology can effectively guide the selection process. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post148"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
