		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post106","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CSM-12 Parallel Immersed Boundary Simulations of Worm-Like Swimmers in the Inertial Flow Regime","scientific_track":"Computer Science \u0026 Applied Mathematics","abstract":"Hydrodynamic interactions in suspensions of swimming organisms (active fluids) has been a topic of recent interest, especially  in the study of collective motion of bacteria, spermatozoa and marine worms. To accurately capture the collective behavior of swimmers in both dilute and dense suspensions, it is essential that hydrodynamic interactions be captured.  We are most interested in flows at moderate Reynolds numbers in the range from 0.1 to 100, in which both advective and diffusive effects are present and the fluid dynamics obey the Navier-Stokes equations. We employ the immersed boundary method to couple the elastic deformations of a swimming worm with the fluid, which yields a system of coupled integro-differential equations.  To solve this system numerically, we employ a parallel immersed boundary algorithm that is  implemented in C++.  We simulate individual swimmer dynamics and pairwise interactions for worm-like organisms, where both synchronization and mutual attraction of nearby swimmers are observed.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post106","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Seyedsaeed","last_name":"Mirazimi","affiliation":"Simon Fraser University","country":"Canada","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post106","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Seyedsaeed","last_name":"Mirazimi","affiliation":"Simon Fraser University","country":"Canada","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post106","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"John M.","last_name":"Stockie","affiliation":"Simon Fraser University","country":"Canada","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post106","title":"Dr.",