	</script><div class="title">CSM-13 Parallelization of Graph Partitioning using Metis and OpenMP</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Rodrigo Pinto Coelho (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post156","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Rodrigo","last_name":"Pinto Coelho","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post156s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Algorithms that find optimal partitions for highly unstructured graphs have a wide range of applications. These applications include load balancing in super-computers, fill-reducing orderings of sparse matrices and design of very large scale integrated circuits (VLSI). METIS is a well-known set of serial programs developed by the Karypis Lab designed to solve this problem. However, METIS was not originally designed to run in multiple processors. In this project we will use OpenMP (Open Multi-Processing), an API managed by the nonprofit consortium OpenMP Architecture Review Board, to parallelize METIS. We will then compare the parallelized version with the original METIS to gain an understanding of the performance improvements that can be obtained. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post155"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post155","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CSM-14 Pruning Highway Networks","scientific_track":"Computer Science \u0026 Applied Mathematics","abstract":"Neural networks trained on big datasets are usually large graphs that take up too much memory and are thus not suited for mobile devices. Recently various methods to reduce the size of these graphs have emerged which proves that this is problem is of interest for the community. The aim of this project is to develop a novel method to reduce the size of these large graphs by letting the network decide which nodes it finds most important for computation and removing the rest. Special type of neural networks called highway networks will be pruned as they allow us to find which nodes are being used most for computation for a particular input.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dhananjay","last_name":"Tomar","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dhananjay","last_name":"Tomar","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"post155s2.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">CSM-14 Pruning Highway Networks</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dhananjay Tomar (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dhananjay","last_name":"Tomar","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post155s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Neural networks trained on big datasets are usually large graphs that take up too much memory and are thus not suited for mobile devices. Recently various methods to reduce the size of these graphs have emerged which proves that this is problem is of interest for the community. The aim of this project is to develop a novel method to reduce the size of these large graphs by letting the network decide which nodes it finds most important for computation and removing the rest. Special type of neural networks called highway networks will be pruned as they allow us to find which nodes are being used most for computation for a particular input. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post130"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
