	</script><div class="title">CSM-16 Solving Large Scale Quadratic Programming Problems with PERMON</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Vaclav Hapla (IT4Innovations National Supercomputing Center, Czech Republic)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post143","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Vaclav","last_name":"Hapla","affiliation":"IT4Innovations National Supercomputing Center","country":"Czech Republic","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post143s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> PERMON forms a collection of software libraries exploiting and extending PETSc. The PermonQP module aims to be a general purpose QP solver. It can be used within many application areas where QP problems arise, such as least-squares regression, data fitting, SVM, VRP, and many others. The underlying method is an alternative to more widely used Interior Point Methods. One of its advantages is that it allows very general, possibly implicit (unassembled, matrix-free) constraint and Hessian matrices. It consists in combination of QP transforms, particularly Lagrangian dualization, an outer loop based on augmented Lagrangian (SMALXE), and specific solvers for box-constrained QP. This combination allows solving a general class of QP problems. PermonFLLOP implements the TFETI domain decomposition method. It prepares TFETI-specific objects such as the gluing matrix and kernel basis, and then calls PermonQP to solve the resulting equality-constrained problem with additional inequality constraints in case of contact problems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post138"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post138","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CSM-17 Load-Balanced Partition Refinement with the Graph p-Laplacian","scientific_track":"Computer Science \u0026 Applied Mathematics","abstract":"Spectral graph partitioning uses the second (Fiedler) eigenvector of the graph Laplacian matrix to approximate the NP-hard sparsest cut problem. Finding this eigenvector requires the minimisation of the Rayleigh quotient which is a 2-norm. We can improve on the approximation by minimising a p-norm and this defines the graph p-Laplacian eigenvalue problem. The approximation becomes sharp as the value of p is decreased from 2 to 1. During Cholesky factorisation of a sparse symmetric matrix the phenomenon of fill-in increases requirements for both memory and arithmetic operations. By permuting the matrix prior to factorisation we increase performance by maximising the sparsity of the Cholesky factor. If we consider the matrix as a sparse graph then finding  the optimal permutation is equivalent to recursively solving the sparsest cut problem.  We solve the p-Laplacian eigenvalue problem in linear time and improve on the current best fill-reducing software (METIS) by 10%.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Toby","last_name":"Simpson","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Toby","last_name":"Simpson","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"post138s2.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">CSM-17 Load-Balanced Partition Refinement with the Graph p-Laplacian</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Toby Simpson (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Toby","last_name":"Simpson","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post138s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Spectral graph partitioning uses the second (Fiedler) eigenvector of the graph Laplacian matrix to approximate the NP-hard sparsest cut problem. Finding this eigenvector requires the minimisation of the Rayleigh quotient which is a 2-norm. We can improve on the approximation by minimising a p-norm and this defines the graph p-Laplacian eigenvalue problem. The approximation becomes sharp as the value of p is decreased from 2 to 1. During Cholesky factorisation of a sparse symmetric matrix the phenomenon of fill-in increases requirements for both memory and arithmetic operations. By permuting the matrix prior to factorisation we increase performance by maximising the sparsity of the Cholesky factor. If we consider the matrix as a sparse graph then finding the optimal permutation is equivalent to recursively solving the sparsest cut problem. We solve the p-Laplacian eigenvalue problem in linear time and improve on the current best fill-reducing software (METIS) by 10%. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post119"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post119","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"CSM-18 Whole Program Generation for Complex Fluid Flow Solvers","scientific_track":"Computer Science \u0026 Applied Mathematics","abstract":"In this poster presentation, we showcase our latest advances in fully generating massively parallel multigrid solvers for fluid flow problems. As input, abstract specifications given in our domain-specific language (DSL) ExaSlang -- short for ExaStencil language -- are considered. From that, our ExaStencils framework is able to generate C++ and CUDA code implementing efficient solvers.\nWe compare two different applications, namely a simpler multigrid solver for Stokes flows and a more elaborate one for non-Newtonian fluid flows based on the full approximation scheme (FAS).\nIn both cases, the computational domain is discretized using regular, non-uniform staggered grids. On them, the governing equations are discretized using finite volumes. We show how discretization and multigrid components are expressed in our DSL. For the latter, different smoothers such as distributive and Vanka-type ones are most interesting and the focus of our poster. Lastly, we draw a comparison between different solver and grid layouts.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post119","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sebastian","last_name":"Kuckuk","affiliation":"Friedrich-Alexander-Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post119","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sebastian","last_name":"Kuckuk","affiliation":"Friedrich-Alexander-Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post119","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Harald","last_name":"K\u00f6stler","affiliation":"Friedrich-Alexander-Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnbe