		{"id":"post119","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sebastian","last_name":"Kuckuk","affiliation":"Friedrich-Alexander-Universit\u00e4t Erlangen-N\u00fcrnberg","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post119s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this poster presentation, we showcase our latest advances in fully generating massively parallel multigrid solvers for fluid flow problems. As input, abstract specifications given in our domain-specific language (DSL) ExaSlang -- short for ExaStencil language -- are considered. From that, our ExaStencils framework is able to generate C++ and CUDA code implementing efficient solvers.We compare two different applications, namely a simpler multigrid solver for Stokes flows and a more elaborate one for non-Newtonian fluid flows based on the full approximation scheme (FAS).In both cases, the computational domain is discretized using regular, non-uniform staggered grids. On them, the governing equations are discretized using finite volumes. We show how discretization and multigrid components are expressed in our DSL. For the latter, different smoothers such as distributive and Vanka-type ones are most interesting and the focus of our poster. Lastly, we draw a comparison between different solver and grid layouts. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post105"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post105","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"EMD-01 Scalable MCMC Algorithm for the Accurate Estimation of Exponential Random Graph Models","scientific_track":"Emerging Domains in HPC","abstract":"The increase in the number and size of large network data sets requires novel efficient methods for their analysis. Exponential Random Graph Models (ERGMs) are a general form of probability distribution widely applicable to the analysis of social and other networks. The scope of ERGMs is limited by the fact that existing estimation approaches rely on iterative computational methods that carry out large number of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) simulations to draw equilibrium network configurations. Estimation approaches include Bayesian, maximum likelihood and the method of moments. We propose an accurate estimation approach, based on network properties at MCMC equilibrium, and design a simple and efficient algorithm that estimates model parameters several orders of magnitude faster than existing algorithms. *Generous support from the Swiss National Platform of Advanced Scientific Computing (PASC) is gratefully acknowledged.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post105","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Maksym","last_name":"Byshkin","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post105","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Maksym","last_name":"Byshkin","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post105","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Alessandro","last_name":"Lomi","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post105","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Antonietta","last_name":"Mira","af