	</script><div class="title">ENG-01 A Multiscale Model for the Simulation of Sediment Impact Erosion of Metallic Targets</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sebastián Leguizamón (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post115","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sebasti\u00e1n","last_name":"Leguizam\u00f3n","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Engineering</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post115s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Erosion damage in hydraulic turbines is a common problem caused by the impact of small sediments entrained in the fluid. The current state-of-the-art simulations rely on CFD particle tracking coupled with erosion correlations that introduce great uncertainty and lack generality. A novel multiscale model of erosion is presented which avoids the use of correlations by explicitly simulating the sediment impacts. The problem is decoupled into its two dominant scales, each of which is solved using the Finite Volume Particle Method. On the microscale, the erosion rate is calculated by means of multi-particle impact simulations which include all the thermomechanical modeling required in the solid. On the macroscale, the sediment flux and impact condition distributions on the target are modeled through particle tracking in the fluid. Finally, a sequential multiscale algorithm allows reproducing the original coupled problem. The proposed model is validated against experimental data with satisfactory results. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post113"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post113","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"ENG-02 GPU-SPHEROS: A GPU-Accelerated Versatile Solver Based on the Finite Volume Particle Method","scientific_track":"Engineering","abstract":"The aim of the present research is to speed up a Finite Volume Particle Method (FVPM) solver utilizing GPU many-core architecture. FVPM is a conservative and consistent particle-based method which inherits interesting features of both Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics and grid-based Finite Volume Method. SPHEROS is a versatile FVPM solver which has been developed at EPFL-LMH, for hydrodynamic simulation of hydraulic turbines and sediment erosion simulation. SPHEROS is able to handle the interaction between fluid, solid, and sediment. In order to accelerate SPHEROS, GPU-SPHEROS has been developed in CUDA featuring Thrust library and highly optimized kernels for both compute-bound and memory-bound algorithms. Up to now, remarkable speedup has been achieved for some parts including particle neighbor search and computing fluxes and forces and we are now focusing our efforts on the identified bottlenecks. The bottlenecks are mostly located in the computation of particles interaction vectors, which is based on spherical-support kernels.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post113","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Siamak","last_name":"Alimirzazadeh","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post113","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Siamak","last_name":"Alimirzazadeh","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post113","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Fran\u00e7ois","last_name":"Avellan","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post113","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sebasti\u00e1n","last_nam