	</script><div class="title">ENG-02 GPU-SPHEROS: A GPU-Accelerated Versatile Solver Based on the Finite Volume Particle Method</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Siamak Alimirzazadeh (EPFL, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post113","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Siamak","last_name":"Alimirzazadeh","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Engineering</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post113s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The aim of the present research is to speed up a Finite Volume Particle Method (FVPM) solver utilizing GPU many-core architecture. FVPM is a conservative and consistent particle-based method which inherits interesting features of both Smoothed Particle Hydrodynamics and grid-based Finite Volume Method. SPHEROS is a versatile FVPM solver which has been developed at EPFL-LMH, for hydrodynamic simulation of hydraulic turbines and sediment erosion simulation. SPHEROS is able to handle the interaction between fluid, solid, and sediment. In order to accelerate SPHEROS, GPU-SPHEROS has been developed in CUDA featuring Thrust library and highly optimized kernels for both compute-bound and memory-bound algorithms. Up to now, remarkable speedup has been achieved for some parts including particle neighbor search and computing fluxes and forces and we are now focusing our efforts on the identified bottlenecks. The bottlenecks are mostly located in the computation of particles interaction vectors, which is based on spherical-support kernels. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post120"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post120","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"LS-01 Aortic Valve Hemodynamics Using Variational Transfer Immersed Boundary Method","scientific_track":"Life Sciences","abstract":"We present the hemodynamics of a bioprosthetic heart valve. The heart valve is embedded in a parametric representation of the aortic root. We make use of sophisticated finer-reinforced material models for both the aortic tissue as well as the leaflet tissue. We obtain results by employing our in-house library for FSI problems. Following the concept of the Immersed Boundary Method, we discretize the respective domains with either finite elements or finite differences. Interchange of the discrete fields is performed with a variational transfer library. To manage stiffness of our coupled system we introduce accuracy based time step control through an embedded Runge-Kutta scheme. All parts of our code are MPI parallel and being adapted to today\u2019s hybrid node supercomputers. We wish to provide this framework as an FSI library for other researchers in the future.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post120","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Barna Errol Mario","last_name":"Becsek","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post120","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Barna Errol Mario","last_name":"Becsek","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post120","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Rolf","last_name":"Krause","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post120","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Maria Giuseppina Chiara","last_name":"Nestola","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}