	</script><div class="title">LS-01 Aortic Valve Hemodynamics Using Variational Transfer Immersed Boundary Method</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Barna Errol Mario Becsek (University of Bern, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post120","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Barna Errol Mario","last_name":"Becsek","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post120s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present the hemodynamics of a bioprosthetic heart valve. The heart valve is embedded in a parametric representation of the aortic root. We make use of sophisticated finer-reinforced material models for both the aortic tissue as well as the leaflet tissue. We obtain results by employing our in-house library for FSI problems. Following the concept of the Immersed Boundary Method, we discretize the respective domains with either finite elements or finite differences. Interchange of the discrete fields is performed with a variational transfer library. To manage stiffness of our coupled system we introduce accuracy based time step control through an embedded Runge-Kutta scheme. All parts of our code are MPI parallel and being adapted to today’s hybrid node supercomputers. We wish to provide this framework as an FSI library for other researchers in the future. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post111"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
