	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post111s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Finding relevant information from complex, high-dimensional temporal series is a nontrivial task. We have recently introduced scalable data analysis tools for the unsupervised mining of such data, viz., the so-called progress index method (Bloechliger et al. (2013), Comput. Phys. Comm. 184, pp. 2446) and resultant SAPPHIRE plots. With shared memory implementations in place for the key algorithmic components, this tool as implemented in the CAMPARI software package (http://campari.sourceforge.net) is able to take advantage of modern HPC resources. It is, however, equally important to provide ease of access across platforms and devices to increase awareness and familiarity with these data mining algorithms. We thus developed and present here a salient implementation of the core algorithms in the R package CampaR1, which has been deposited on CRAN. This wrapper has been designed such that it is able to analyze any kind of data that can be processed by R. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post114"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
