	</script><div class="title">LS-03 Elucidating the Effect of Polymer Flexibility, Molecular Geometry, and Charge Neutralization on siRNA-Polycation Complexes Free Energy Landscape: A Computational Study</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Gianvito Grasso (Scuola universitaria professionale della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post114","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Gianvito","last_name":"Grasso","affiliation":"Scuola universitaria professionale della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post114s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The future success of nucleic acids as therapeutic agents is strongly related with the design of efficient drug delivery technologies. Cationic polymers represent an attractive strategy to serve as drug carriers with the envisioned advantages of efficient complexation, low cost, and ease of production. However, the balance between efficacy and toxicity of these polymers is still a bottleneck. In the present work, the binding mechanism of polyarginine, polylysine and polyethyleneimine to a model siRNA target is computationally investigated at atomistic level. Replica exchange molecular dynamics in combination with metadynamics simulations elucidate how polymer flexibility, charge density, and molecular geometry affect the siRNA-polycations free energy landscapes. The results reveal that comparable polyarginine and polylysine show advantageous binding properties compared to polyethyleneimine. In brief, significant differences among lowest energy binding modes have been detected. These results could be helpful in the future design of potent and selective nucleic acids drug carrier polymers. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post133"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post133","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"LS-04 Flow Stability and Transition Past an Aortic Valve Using a Hybrid Multicore\/Manycore Massively Parallel Navier-Stokes Solver","scientific_track":"Life Sciences","abstract":"A massively-parallel 3D Navier-Stokes solver has been accelerated on the GPUs. The solver is used for heart valve simulations, where Immersed Boundary Method is adopted for coupling the fluid and soft tissue domains. Computationally expensive routines of this solver have been  offloaded to the GPGPUs of Cray XC50 supercomputer (Piz Daint). The differential kernels such as Jacobi multigrid smoothers were developed with CUDA C API and then wrapped in FORTRAN for integration in the flow solver. The GPU-accelerated kernels were benchmarked on Fermi and Pascal GPUs, resulting in 5x and 20x speedup, respectively. Briskly on Pascal, 33x speedup was achieved by adopting CUDA multi-process service together with MPI. Finally, we performed extensive numerical simulations for investigating the flow instabilities past the aortic sinus cavity.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post133","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hadi","last_name":"Zolfaghari","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post133","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Hadi","last_name":"Zolfaghari","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post133","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Barna","last_name":"Becsek","affiliation":"University of Bern","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post133","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Rolf","last_name":"Krause","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post133","title":"Dr.","bio":"","fi