	</script><div class="title">LS-05 Focused Diversification of Biomolecules for Drug Discovery by Progress Index-Guided Sampling</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Cassiano Langini (University of Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post112","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Cassiano","last_name":"Langini","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The efficient exploration of relevant areas of phase space represents a major challenge in molecular simulations of biological systems. Enhanced sampling protocols try to address this challenge. Progress index-guided sampling evolves several copies of the system in parallel, and sampling redundancy is eliminated by periodically replacing copies exploring the same regions of phase space with less visited conformations. The discovery of new states is driven by spontaneous fluctuations alone. The reseeding heuristic relies on a representation of the system that can be tuned to obtain focused diversification of specific degrees of freedom. By coupling a molecular dynamics code that is efficient on the single node level to an MPI layer managing the reseeding heuristic, the protocol is able to take full advantage of modern HPC resources. Here, we demonstrate that we achieve the focused diversification of two distinct loops in four bromodomains, which are drug targets in epigenetics research. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post140"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post140","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"LS-06 Funnel-Metadynamics 2.0: Graphical User Interface and Implementation in Plumed 2","scientific_track":"Life Sciences","abstract":"Funnel Metadynamics (FM) is a computational method proven to be successful in obtaining an accurate estimation of the binding affinity between two molecules (Limongelli et al. PNAS 2013, Troussicot et al. JACS 2015, Comitani et al. JCTC 2016, Moraca et al. PNAS 2017). In this approach, the use of a funnel-shaped restraining potential allows enhancing the exploration of the ligand bound poses and its solvated states leading to an accurate description of the protein-ligand binding free energy surface. This approach allows investigating further important aspects of the binding process, such as the presence of alternative binding modes and the role of the solvent. FM has proven to be successful in reproducing the available experimental data, such as crystallographic binding modes and experimental binding free energies (Limongelli et al. PNAS 2013; Troussicot et al. JACS 2015), resulting a most valuable tool to study ligand\/protein and ligand\/DNA binding interactions.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post140","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stefano","last_name":"Raniolo","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post140","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stefano","last_name":"Raniolo","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post140","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Davide","last_name":"Branduardi","affiliation":"Schrodinger Inc.","country":"United Kingdom","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"post140","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Vittorio","last_name":"Limon