	</script><div class="title">LS-06 Funnel-Metadynamics 2.0: Graphical User Interface and Implementation in Plumed 2</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Stefano Raniolo (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post140","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Stefano","last_name":"Raniolo","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post140s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Funnel Metadynamics (FM) is a computational method proven to be successful in obtaining an accurate estimation of the binding affinity between two molecules (Limongelli et al. PNAS 2013, Troussicot et al. JACS 2015, Comitani et al. JCTC 2016, Moraca et al. PNAS 2017). In this approach, the use of a funnel-shaped restraining potential allows enhancing the exploration of the ligand bound poses and its solvated states leading to an accurate description of the protein-ligand binding free energy surface. This approach allows investigating further important aspects of the binding process, such as the presence of alternative binding modes and the role of the solvent. FM has proven to be successful in reproducing the available experimental data, such as crystallographic binding modes and experimental binding free energies (Limongelli et al. PNAS 2013; Troussicot et al. JACS 2015), resulting a most valuable tool to study ligand/protein and ligand/DNA binding interactions. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post117"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"post117","code":"","type":"Poster","title":"PHY-01 Formation of Solid H2 in the ISM","scientific_track":"Physics","abstract":"We study the formation of cold, substellar sized bodies due to the fragmentation of gravitationally unstable fluids in a phase transition. The main interest is the potential formation of solid H2 in the ISM. H2 condensation conditions can be reached in dense substellar structures and during a plane-parallel contraction, where the temperature rise is only of a factor 2. Linear analysis shows that fluids in a phase transition are always gravitationally unstable, because compression does not increase pressure, but the condensed phase fraction. The non-linear dynamics of fluids in and out of a phase transition are studied using the molecular dynamics code LAMMPS. Supermolecules are used to combine the Lennard-Jones and gravitational potential. The simulations confirm that fluids presenting a phase transition are gravitationally unstable, independent of the strength of the gravitational potential. The instabilities produce a wide spectrum of ice clumps, from small oligomers to gravitationally bound planetoids.","begin_time":"19:00","begin_timestamp":"1522256400","end_time":"21:00","end_timestamp":"1522263600","session_date":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"post117","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"F\u00fcglistaler","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"post117","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"F\u00fcglistaler","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"post117","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniel","last_name":"Pfenniger","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]},"presentation_file":"post117s2.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Tuesday, June 27, 2017","room":"Foyer","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">PHY-01 Formation of Solid H2 in the ISM</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Andreas Füglistaler (University of Geneva, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"post117","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andreas","last_name":"F\u00fcglistaler","affiliation":"University of Geneva","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Physics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post117s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We study the formation of cold, substellar sized bodies due to the fragmentation of gravitationally unstable fluids in a phase transition. The main interest is the potential formation of solid H2 in the ISM. H2 condensation conditions can be reached in dense substellar structures and during a plane-parallel contraction, where the temperature rise is only of a factor 2. Linear analysis shows that fluids in a phase transition are always gravitationally unstable, because compression does not increase pressure, but the condensed phase fraction. The non-linear dynamics of fluids in and out of a phase transition are studied using the molecular dynamics code LAMMPS. Supermolecules are used to combine the Lennard-Jones and gravitational potential. The simulations confirm that fluids presenting a phase transition are gravitationally unstable, independent of the strength of the gravitational potential. The instabilities produce a wide spectrum of ice clumps, from small oligomers to gravitationally bound planetoids. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post129"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
