		{"id":"post141","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Aaron","last_name":"Scheinberg","affiliation":"EPFL","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="fields tr"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s): </div> <div class="td data-multiple"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Physics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/post141s2.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Numerical plasma physics models are used to improve our understanding of transport, instability growth and other poorly understood phenomena encountered in the experimental devices edging toward viable fusion energy. Since computational expense imposes a major limitation on accurate physical modeling, computational resources must be used as efficiently as possible. Here, we examine four recent features in the particle-in-cell (PIC) code ORB5: a structural change to optimize calculations on "gyropoints" (rather than gyroaveraged particle position); array structure changes; precomputational particle sorting; and the implementation of a hybrid parallelization using OpenMP (in addition to the existing MPI parallelization). We demonstrate the speedup, and thus time and resource savings, achieved by implementing these changes in the major modules of PIC gyrokinetic codes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="post137"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">19:00 - 21:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
