	</script><div class="title">Blood Rheology in Complex Geometries</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Eva Athena Economides (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa220","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Eva Athena","last_name":"Economides","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Recent advances in medical research and bio-engineering have led to the development of devices capable of handling fluids and biological matter at the microscale. The operating conditions of such devices are constrained in order to ensure that the mechanical properties and local hemodynamics of blood are not altered during operation. These properties are a consequence of the red blood cell (RBC) microstructure, which changes according to the device geometry. The understanding of the mechanics and dynamics that govern the interactions between the RBCs is crucial for the quantitative characterization of blood flow. Through simulations of individual RBCs, a detailed characterization of the suspended blood cells can be made and directly connect the macroscopic properties (e.g. viscosity) to specific RBC conformations. In this work we present a quantification of the microstructure in high and low hematocrit blood flows in wall bounded geometries, and make connections to the measured viscosity. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa183"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa183","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Numerical Simulation of a Compound Capsule in a Constricted Microchannel","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Simulations of the passage of eukaryotic cells through a constricted channel aid in studying the properties of cancer cells and their transport through the bloodstream. Compound capsules, which explicitly model the outer cell membrane and nuclear lamina, have the potential to improve fidelity of computational models. However, general simulations of compound capsules through a constricted microchannel have not been conducted and the influence of the compound capsule model on computational performance is not well known. In this study, we extend a parallel hemodynamics application to simulate the fluid-structure interaction between compound capsules and fluid. With this framework, we compare the deformation of simple and compound capsules in constricted microchannels, and explore how this deformation depends on the capillary number and on the volume fraction of the inner membrane. The parallel performance of the computational framework in this setting is evaluated and lessons for future development are discussed.","begin_time":"09:30","begin_timestamp":"1522222200","end_time":"10:00","end_timestamp":"1522224000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa183","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"John","last_name":"Gounley","affiliation":"Duke University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa183","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"John","last_name":"Gounley","affiliation":"Duke University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa183","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Erik W.","last_name":"Draeger","affiliation":"Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa183","title":"Prof