	</script><div class="title">Precision Medicine: Paving the way for Responsible Data Access and Governance</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alessandro Blasimme (University of Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa266","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alessandro","last_name":"Blasimme","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Precision medicine relies on the availability of multiple data types, collected from a host of different sources. The prospect of circulating large amounts of personal data, or making them widely available for analysis generates a host of novel ethical issues, spanning from appropriate consent mechanisms to privacy protection and accountability. As a consequence, establishing an ethically sound framework for responsible data access is going to be key for the successful development of precision medicine. To this aim, we present the results of a comprehensive analysis of international guidelines and policies concerning access to health data in the context of research. Drawing on such analysis, we also set out to offer an ethical framework for responsible data access within precision medicine data infrastructures. Our framework, we argue, can help overcome the limitations of current ethical tools, and cope with the new challenges posed by data-intense biomedical research. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa113"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa113","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Leonhard Med: ETH\u0027s Answer to the IT Challenges of Personalized Health Research","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Research in personalized health requires a robust, performant and safe data and computing environment. Interoperability between participating medical and academic research centers is key as data come from many and heterogeneous sources, e.g. hospital patient data, personalized OMICS data, systems biology research data and reference data. Bringing those data together, analyzing them and maintaining the data provenance while ensuring legal and ethical compliance is a challenging task. When building up a suitable environment at ETH, we found three areas to require special attention: (i) making a high-performance computing environment fit for handling sensitive patient data, (ii) design of inter-operable data analysis pipelines to allow moving analysis code to data rather than vice versa; (iii) managing data and tracking the data provenance for large-scale sensitive data analysis across institutions. In this talk, we will report on our progress on dealing with these areas in ETH\u2019s new \u201cLeonhard Med\u201d medical data and computing environment. Emphasize will be given to the interdependence among such efforts and thus the need of a high level of integration in order to enable this highly interdisciplinary domain of research.","begin_time":"09:30","begin_timestamp":"1522222200","end_time":"10:00","end_timestamp":"1522224000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Bernd","last_name":"Rinn","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Bernd","last_name":"Rinn","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christian","last_name":"Bollinger","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Balazs","last_name":"Laurenczy","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Diana Coman","last_name":"Schmid","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"W\u00fcst","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">Leonhard Med: ETH's Answer to the IT Challenges of Personalized Health Research</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Bernd Rinn (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa113","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Bernd","last_name":"Rinn","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Research in personalized health requires a robust, performant and safe data and computing environment. Interoperability between participating medical and academic research centers is key as data come from many and heterogeneous sources, e.g. hospital patient data, personalized OMICS data, systems biology research data and reference data. Bringing those data together, analyzing them and maintaining the data provenance while ensuring legal and ethical compliance is a challenging task. When building up a suitable environment at ETH, we found three areas to require special attention: (i) making a high-performance computing environment fit for handling sensitive patient data, (ii) design of inter-operable data analysis pipelines to allow moving analysis code to data rather than vice versa; (iii) managing data and tracking the data provenance for large-scale sensitive data analysis across institutions. In this talk, we will report on our progress on dealing with these areas in ETH’s new “Leonhard Med” medical data and computing environment. Emphasize will be given to the interdependence among such efforts and thus the need of a high level of integration in order to enable this highly interdisciplinary domain of research. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa270"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa270","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"The Swiss Personalized Health Network Data Coordination Center - Enabling Research in Personalized Health by Establishing Interoperability of Health-Related Information","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The Swiss Personalized Health Network (SPHN) initiative aims to bring Switzerland to the forefront of personalized health research by establishing nationwide interoperability of biomedical information. Thanks to advances in life sciences, analytical techniques and information technology, both the quality and quantity of data relevant for biomedical research have been increasing dramatically in recent years. Besides systematic research projects, increasing amounts of data are generated as part of routine clinical care, observational studies, and even by individual citizens monitoring themselves (\u0022quantified self\u0022). The \u0022SPHN Data Coordination Center (DCC)\u0022 at the SIB Swiss Institute of Bioinformatics will address the technical and semantic challenges of data interoperability to enable scientists to efficiently use and analyze Swiss health-related data in a meaningful way. The growing amount of detailed information on individuals provides an unprecedented opportunity for advancing biomedical research and answering today\u2019s research questions with respect to precision medicine and human health.","begin_time":"10:00","begin_timestamp":"1522224000","end_time":"10:30","end_timestamp":"1522225800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa270","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Torsten","last_name":"Schwede","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa270","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Torsten","last_name":"Schwede","affiliation":"University of Basel","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday,