	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We review the most recent development of a data-driven approach to causality inference in multivariate time series, improving on classical approaches to causality analysis such as Granger causality by accommodating general forms of nonstationarity and non-homogeneity resulting from unresolved and latent-scale effects. Emerging causality framework results in, and is implemented by way of, a clustering of time series based on a minimization of the averaged clustering functional, which describes the mean distance between observation data and its representation in terms of given number of abstract Bayesian causality models of a certain predefined class. The time series analysis and clustering FEM-H1 framework is implemented through a new open-source HPC library using the PETSc framework to target multiple platforms, such as CPU, GPU, and Xeon Phi. We demonstrate the efficiency of the method and our implementation for solving challenging large-scaled benchmarks on CSCS Piz Daint supercomputer. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa127"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
