	</script><div class="title">The Quiet Atmosphere: Data-Driven Ideas for Bridging the Gap Between Observed and Modeled Nocturnal Turbulence.</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Nikki Vercauteren (Freie Universität Berlin, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa127","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Nikki","last_name":"Vercauteren","affiliation":"Freie Universit\u00e4t Berlin","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Boundary-layer turbulence at night, in stably stratified weak-wind conditions, is typically intermittent and generated partly by shear associated with propagating non-turbulent motions on the so-called submesoscales (corresponding roughly to scales smaller than 2km). These non-turbulent motions can include ramp-cliff patterns, waves or microfronts and are commonly denoted as submesomotions. The diversity of submesomotions complicates the identification of specific physical mechanisms that would potentially trigger intermittent turbulence, making the representation of nocturnal turbulence in weather forecasting models a challenging task. In this context, recently developed methods of nonstationary data analysis represent a promising tool to extract knowledge about yet unknown turbulence triggering mechanisms from observational datasets of atmospheric turbulence. We will show that a combination of clustering methods developed for nonstationary data analysis and taking into account external influences can identify different flow regimes and give insights about the patterns of flow motions susceptible to influence turbulent mixing. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa111"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa111","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"On Memory, Dimension, and Atmospheric Teleconnections","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Using an atmospheric reanalysis and applying multi-scale approximations to non-stationary dynamical processes, the role of memory and dimensionality in defining the metastable states of the troposphere is examined. The impact of various strategies for dimension reduction based on PCA, diagonalisation, and truncation are considered. Memory effects are modeled by VAR processes. We separate barotropic and baroclinic processes and test models sensitivity to the number and type of retained principal components. The identified tropospheric physical modes depend on the number of PCs and lags. We find circumglobal teleconnections in both hemispheres at lags \u003C 2 and contrast the transient nature and zonal structure of the Southern Hemisphere patterns with their Northern Hemisphere counterparts. Overfitted models yield structures consistent with the major teleconnection modes, replaced by zonally oriented wavetrains when memory effects are ignored or when the dimension is reduced via diagonalising. Where baroclinic processes are emphasized, circumpolar wavetrains are manifest.","begin_time":"10:00","begin_timestamp":"1522224000","end_time":"10:30","end_timestamp":"1522225800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa111","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Didier Paolo","last_name":"Monselesan","affiliation":"Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation","country":"Australia","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa111","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Didier Paolo","last_name":"Monselesan","affiliation":"Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation","country":"Australia","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script><div class="title">On Memory, Dimension, and Atmospheric Teleconnections</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Didier Paolo Monselesan (Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation, Australia)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa111","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Didier Paolo","last_name":"Monselesan","affiliation":"Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organisation","country":"Australia","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script></div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Using an atmospheric reanalysis and applying multi-scale approximations to non-stationary dynamical processes, the role of memory and dimensionality in defining the metastable states of the troposphere is examined. The impact of various strategies for dimension reduction based on PCA, diagonalisation, and truncation are considered. Memory effects are modeled by VAR processes. We separate barotropic and baroclinic processes and test models sensitivity to the number and type of retained principal components. The identified tropospheric physical modes depend on the number of PCs and lags. We find circumglobal teleconnections in both hemispheres at lags < 2 and contrast the transient nature and zonal structure of the Southern Hemisphere patterns with their Northern Hemisphere counterparts. Overfitted models yield structures consistent with the major teleconnection modes, replaced by zonally oriented wavetrains when memory effects are ignored or when the dimension is reduced via diagonalising. Where baroclinic processes are emphasized, circumpolar wavetrains are manifest. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa121"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:30 - 11:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa121","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Deep Learning Classification of Radio Astronomy Images","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The challenge for future radio observations is the detection of the faint gas emission from cosmological filaments, at the edge of detectability by instruments like LOFAR or SKA. This requires specific software to be disentangled from the noise that dominates the images.  The software not only have to de-noise images, but also to support automatic classification, since the expected overwhelming data volumes rule out any human supervision. These characteristics can be found in Deep Learning algorithms. We aim at applying a Convolutional Neural Network algorithm to images from radio telescopes, focusing on the detection of faint extended sources. Once properly trained, the network can automatically and quickly analyze images. All the relevant features and parameters of the network have been tuned to work effectively on our low signal-to-noise images. The Tensorflow library was adopted being open source, supporting a broad variety of machine learning algorithms and running effectively on GPUs.","begin_time":"10:30","begin_timestamp":"1522225800","end_time":"11:00","end_timestamp":"1522227600","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa121","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Claudio","last_name":"Gheller","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa121","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Claudio","last_name":"Gheller","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Deep Learning Classification of Radio Astronomy Images</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Claudio Gheller (ETH Zurich / CSCS, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa121","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Claudio","last_name":"Gheller","affiliation":"ETH Zurich \/ CSCS","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The challenge for future radio observations is the detection of the faint gas emission from cosmological filaments, at the edge of detectability by instruments like LOFAR or SKA. This requires specific software to be disentangled from the noise that dominates the images. The software not only have to de-noise images, but also to support automatic classification, since the expected overwhelming data volumes rule out any human supervision. These characteristics can be found in Deep Learning algorithms. We aim at applying a Convolutional Neural Network algorithm to images from radio telescopes, focusing on the detection of faint extended sources. Once properly trained, the network can automatically and quickly analyze images. All the relevant features and parameters of the network have been tuned to work effectively on our low signal-to-noise images. The Tensorflow library was adopted being open source, supporting a broad variety of machine learning algorithms and running effectively on GPUs. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess164-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess164" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS35 High-Throughput Computing on Emerging HPC Platforms for Particle Detectors at The Large Hadron Collider (1/2): Online Computing</strong>, Room B2</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g>	</g></svg></div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g></svg></div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </a>	</div>	<div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess164"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Omar Awile (CERN, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp111","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Omar","last_name":"Awile","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Physics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Understanding the basic building blocks of matter is amongst the most formidable ventures humanity has undertaken. The Large Hadron Collider (LHC) and its associated experiments have allowed us to observe the particles and processes that lie at the foundation of our current understanding of the physical world. Furthermore, the LHC and other high-energy physics (HEP) facilities continue to produce data at an ever increasing rate, allowing us to peer beyond the Standard Model.<br /><br />In order to filter, process, and analyze the data captured at particle detectors, the HEP community has had over the last decades an insatiable appetite for computing power. Today the LHC experiments record around 150 PB/year. The rate of interactions to be studied will increase by a factor of 100 in the next 10 to 15 years.<br /><br />Computing at the LHC experiments happens mostly in two domains. In Online Computing, data captured at the detector must be processed and filtered using near-realtime, high-throughput computing software frameworks. The reconstruction of a particle collision event employs a large number of complex algorithms before the results are stored for further analysis. Offline computing deals with the physics analysis of the large data sets captured by the detector and retained by the online computing software. <br /><br />In this session we take a closer look at detector simulation and data analysis in HEP experiments. Much work has been devoted in recent years to further develop&nbsp;the existing software frameworks to better take advantage of modern hardware architectures. This includes shared-memory parallelism, vectorization and support for coprocessors and accelerators. Furthermore, the recent advancements in the field of machine learning are finding a number of applications in high-energy physics. The presentations discuss these simulation and data-analysis frameworks in the context of high-performance computing and modern hardware architectures.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa292"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:00 - 09:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
