	</script> <div class="title">Computing at CERN: Challenges and Opportunities</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Omar Awile (CERN, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa292","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Omar","last_name":"Awile","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS35_01.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> As the demand for computing power and throughput grows, propelled by increasing particle detector output, computing in high-energy physics must continue innovating. At CERN, a distinction is made between online and offline computing. Online computing is the processing, filtering, and storage of data acquired through the particle detectors at near realtime: current-generation detectors produce ca. 100TB/s data combined, reduced to 25 PB/year. Offline computing is the statistical analysis of stored experimental data, and performed on a worldwide computing grid of 150 participating institutions. The continued increase in detector data output and a shift in computer hardware design from serial/scalar to parallel/vectorized architectures pose significant challenges to the HEP computing community. Changes in hardware and software infrastructures should allow experiments to continue to collect, process, and analyze data for years to come. I will give a brief overview of the LHC and CERN's computing history and discuss current and future challenges. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa179"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa179","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"HEP Realtime Analysis: Scaling Beyond Embarrassing Parallel","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The LHC collides bunches of protons every 25 ns. This is reflected in the data stream generated by its detectors: it can be chopped up into so-called events, each corresponding to the data generated in 25 ns intervals. Historically, events have been the basic \u0027quantum\u0027 of scheduling the processing of this data stream, as each event can be analyzed separately. HEP has been able to take advantage of the embarrassingly parallel nature of this problem to scale up its data processing to the systems in use today. But as the intensity of the LHC increases, events become more complex, and their analysis becomes more intricate. When combined with the changing computing landscape it has become clear that just scaling the existing architecture will no longer suffice. This talk will address the challenges posed and describe how the LHCb collaboration is changing its online data processing strategy to meet them.","begin_time":"09:30","begin_timestamp":"1522222200","end_time":"10:00","end_timestamp":"1522224000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa179","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Gerhard","last_name":"Raven","affiliation":"VU University Amsterdam","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa179","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Gerhard","last_name":"Raven","affiliation":"VU University Amsterdam","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"MS35_02.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">HEP Realtime Analysis: Scaling Beyond Embarrassing Parallel</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Gerhard Raven (VU University Amsterdam, Netherlands)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa179","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Gerhard","last_name":"Raven","affiliation":"VU University Amsterdam","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS35_02.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The LHC collides bunches of protons every 25 ns. This is reflected in the data stream generated by its detectors: it can be chopped up into so-called events, each corresponding to the data generated in 25 ns intervals. Historically, events have been the basic 'quantum' of scheduling the processing of this data stream, as each event can be analyzed separately. HEP has been able to take advantage of the embarrassingly parallel nature of this problem to scale up its data processing to the systems in use today. But as the intensity of the LHC increases, events become more complex, and their analysis becomes more intricate. When combined with the changing computing landscape it has become clear that just scaling the existing architecture will no longer suffice. This talk will address the challenges posed and describe how the LHCb collaboration is changing its online data processing strategy to meet them. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa197"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa197","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"High Performance Computing Meets High Energy Physics","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In 2020, the LHCb detector will be upgraded, and as a consequence, it will generate a data throughput of up to 30 Tbit\/s. The data will then be filtered in a software-based trigger for interesting particle collisions. The design of such a system poses performance challenges in the interconnect, compute hardware platforms and software infrastructure. The High Throughput Computing Collaboration (HTCC) is investigating the use of next-generation Intel hardware technologies in this context. In this presentation we will show results from our network infrastructure feasibility studies on 100 G interconnects. In addition, we present new developments on vectorized and thread-parallelized algorithms used in the Online reconstruction software. In order to fully take advantage of modern hardware platforms, alternatives to the existing implementations that exploit SIMD capabilities and multi\/manycore architectures are being explored. Performance is measured and compared across a variety of architectures taking into account the cost and energy requirements.","begin_time":"10:00","begin_timestamp":"1522224000","end_time":"10:30","end_timestamp":"1522225800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa197","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniel Hugo","last_name":"Campora Perez","affiliation":"University of Seville","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa197","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniel Hugo","last_name":"Campora Perez","affiliation":"University of Seville","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"MS35_04.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">High Performance Computing Meets High Energy Physics</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Daniel Hugo Campora Perez (University of Seville, Spain)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa197","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniel Hugo","last_name":"Campora Perez","affiliation":"University of Seville","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS35_04.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In 2020, the LHCb detector will be upgraded, and as a consequence, it will generate a data throughput of up to 30 Tbit/s. The data will then be filtered in a software-based trigger for interesting particle collisions. The design of such a system poses performance challenges in the interconnect, compute hardware platforms and software infrastructure. The High Throughput Computing Collaboration (HTCC) is investigating the use of next-generation Intel hardware technologies in this context. In this presentation we will show results from our network infrastructure feasibility studies on 100 G interconnects. In addition, we present new developments on vectorized and thread-parallelized algorithms used in the Online reconstruction software. In order to fully take advantage of modern hardware platforms, alternatives to the existing implementations that exploit SIMD capabilities and multi/manycore architectures are being explored. Performance is measured and compared across a variety of architectures taking into account the cost and energy requirements. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa125"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:30 - 11:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa125","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Heterogeneous Event Selection at the CMS Experiment","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Starting from 2020, during the Large Hadron Collider Runs 3 and 4, the increased accelerator luminosity with the consequently increased number of simultaneous proton-proton collisions (pile-up) will pose significant new challenges for the CMS experiment. The reconstruction of the trajectories of charged particles recorded in the silicon pixel and strip detectors is one of the most important components of the interpretation of the detector information of a proton-proton collision. The increasing complexity of events, due to the growing number of simultaneous proton-proton collisions, will make track reconstruction especially challenging. GPUs are becoming wider, and their width is expected to increase in the following years. A many-threads-per-event approach would scale with the pileup, by offloading the combinatorics to the number of threads available on the GPU. This would allow a faster execution of track reconstruction and physics selection algorithms in charge of accepting the events with the most interesting physics content.","begin_time":"10:30","begin_timestamp":"1522225800","end_time":"11:00","end_timestamp":"1522227600","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felice","last_name":"Pantaleo","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felice","last_name":"Pantaleo","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"MS35_03.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B2","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Heterogeneous Event Selection at the CMS Experiment</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Felice Pantaleo (CERN, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa125","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felice","last_name":"Pantaleo","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS35_03.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Starting from 2020, during the Large Hadron Collider Runs 3 and 4, the increased accelerator luminosity with the consequently increased number of simultaneous proton-proton collisions (pile-up) will pose significant new challenges for the CMS experiment. The reconstruction of the trajectories of charged particles recorded in the silicon pixel and strip detectors is one of the most important components of the interpretation of the detector information of a proton-proton collision. The increasing complexity of events, due to the growing number of simultaneous proton-proton collisions, will make track reconstruction especially challenging. GPUs are becoming wider, and their width is expected to increase in the following years. A many-threads-per-event approach would scale with the pileup, by offloading the combinatorics to the number of threads available on the GPU. This would allow a faster execution of track reconstruction and physics selection algorithms in charge of accepting the events with the most interesting physics content. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess166-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess166" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS36 In-Silico Biochemistry: From Quantum Mechanics to Coarse-Grained High-Performance Computing Simulations</strong>, Room E</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g>	</g></svg></div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g></svg></div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </a>	</div>	<div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess166"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Daniele Di Marino (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span>, <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp112","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Daniele","last_name":"Di Marino","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> <div class="author"> Vittorio Limongelli (Università della Svizzera italiana, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp112","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Vittorio","last_name":"Limongelli","affiliation":"Universit\u00e0 della Svizzera italiana","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Life Sciences, Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>The elucidation of biological processes passes through different experimental protocols that are used to dissect intricate reactions in several small pieces, thus obtaining simplified models of the entire process. Computer simulations have been used since the early 70s to study the physical and chemical properties of biomolecules and they have played in the recent years an even more relevant role in elucidating, complementing and also predicting the experimental observables. The chemical reactivity of biomolecules can be studied in-silico at different levels of accuracy and dimension using electron-based, atom-based, and multiscale models. The choice among the different approaches depends on the property of the system the scientists aim to investigate. Electron transfer reactions, ligand/protein binding, and protein-protein interactions are only a few examples of the biological processes that can be investigated through computer simulations.<br /><br />The main limitations of the computational approaches are represented by:<br />- Timescale of the biological processes;<br />- Size of the system to simulate;<br />- Accuracy in the system&rsquo;s description;<br /><br />The continuous effort of the scientific community to overcome such limitations has led to important advances represented by the development of novel methods and the improved performance of the simulation codes on the modern-day computer architectures such as high-performance computing (HPC) clusters. The scientific literature shows many successful examples where simulations unravel complex biochemical problems and some of those are illustrated in the present minisymposium.<br /><br />The minisymposium also represents an opportunity, particularly for young researchers, to discuss with some of the word-leading scientists in the field the state-of-the-art simulation techniques and draw a line towards the future of biomolecular simulations.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa259"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:00 - 09:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa259","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Computational Challenges in Photobiology and Ultrafast Spectroscopy","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Light-induced reactions are ubiquitous in biological processes, including vision, DNA\/RNA photodamage, photosynthesis and bioluminescence. Understanding the fundamental mechanisms regulating these natural processes is of great importance for developing innovative technologies in biomedical and energy sciences. Accurate characterization of photophysical properties and photochemical pathways occurring in photo-induced processes is quite challenging, even for the most advanced computational and experimental techniques. First-principles simulations ensuring reliable description of excited states and ultrafast laser spectroscopies are indeed necessary to gain insights into complex light-induced processes. I will illustrate applications of hybrid quantum-mechanical\/molecular-mechanics methods and ab initio on-the-fly semiclassical dynamics techniques to the study of retinal photochemistry in solution and in biological pigments involved in ultraviolet vision. Our recent developments of computational tools and protocols for first-principles simulations of ultrafast bidimensional electronic spectra will be also introduced along with their application to the study of proteic systems, retinals, organic fluorescent probes and DNA\/RNA nucleobases.","begin_time":"09:00","begin_timestamp":"1522220400","end_time":"09:30","end_timestamp":"1522222200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa259","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ivan","last_name":"Rivalta","affiliation":"\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure de Lyon","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa259","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ivan","last_name":"Rivalta","affiliation":"\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure de Lyon","country":"France","is_presenter