	</script> <div class="title">Computational Challenges in Photobiology and Ultrafast Spectroscopy</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Ivan Rivalta (École normale supérieure de Lyon, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa259","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Ivan","last_name":"Rivalta","affiliation":"\u00c9cole normale sup\u00e9rieure de Lyon","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Light-induced reactions are ubiquitous in biological processes, including vision, DNA/RNA photodamage, photosynthesis and bioluminescence. Understanding the fundamental mechanisms regulating these natural processes is of great importance for developing innovative technologies in biomedical and energy sciences. Accurate characterization of photophysical properties and photochemical pathways occurring in photo-induced processes is quite challenging, even for the most advanced computational and experimental techniques. First-principles simulations ensuring reliable description of excited states and ultrafast laser spectroscopies are indeed necessary to gain insights into complex light-induced processes. I will illustrate applications of hybrid quantum-mechanical/molecular-mechanics methods and ab initio on-the-fly semiclassical dynamics techniques to the study of retinal photochemistry in solution and in biological pigments involved in ultraviolet vision. Our recent developments of computational tools and protocols for first-principles simulations of ultrafast bidimensional electronic spectra will be also introduced along with their application to the study of proteic systems, retinals, organic fluorescent probes and DNA/RNA nucleobases. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa281"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa281","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"High-Resolution, Integrative Modeling of Biomolecular Complexes From Fuzzy Data","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The prediction of the quaternary structure of biomolecular macromolecules is of paramount importance for fundamental understanding of cellular processes and drug design. In the era of integrative structural biology, one way of increasing the accuracy of modelling methods used to predict the structure of biomolecular complexes is to include as much experimental or predictive information as possible in the process. We have developed for this purpose a versatile flexible information-driven docking approach HADDOCK (http:\/\/www.bonvinlab.org\/software\/haddock2.2). HADDOCK can integrate information derived from biochemical, biophysical or bioinformatics methods to enhance sampling, scoring, or both. The information that can be integrated is quite diverse: interface restraints from NMR, mutagenesis experiments or bioinformatics predictions; shape data from small-angle X-ray scattering, and, recently, cryo-electron microscopy experiments. In my talk, I will illustrate HADDOCK\u2019s capabilities with various examples, including protein-peptide and protein ligand complexes.","begin_time":"09:30","begin_timestamp":"1522222200","end_time":"10:00","end_timestamp":"1522224000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa281","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexandre","last_name":"Bonvin","affiliation":"Utrecht University","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa281","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexandre","last_name":"Bonvin","affiliation":"Utrecht University","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">High-Resolution, Integrative Modeling of Biomolecular Complexes From Fuzzy Data</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alexandre Bonvin (Utrecht University, Netherlands)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa281","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexandre","last_name":"Bonvin","affiliation":"Utrecht University","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The prediction of the quaternary structure of biomolecular macromolecules is of paramount importance for fundamental understanding of cellular processes and drug design. In the era of integrative structural biology, one way of increasing the accuracy of modelling methods used to predict the structure of biomolecular complexes is to include as much experimental or predictive information as possible in the process. We have developed for this purpose a versatile flexible information-driven docking approach HADDOCK (http://www.bonvinlab.org/software/haddock2.2). HADDOCK can integrate information derived from biochemical, biophysical or bioinformatics methods to enhance sampling, scoring, or both. The information that can be integrated is quite diverse: interface restraints from NMR, mutagenesis experiments or bioinformatics predictions; shape data from small-angle X-ray scattering, and, recently, cryo-electron microscopy experiments. In my talk, I will illustrate HADDOCK’s capabilities with various examples, including protein-peptide and protein ligand complexes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa236"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
