	</script> <div class="title">Densities of States: Algorithms and Applications in Linear Algebra</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Yousef Saad (University of Minnesota, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa120","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yousef","last_name":"Saad","affiliation":"University of Minnesota","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> This talk will first discuss how the basic tool of trace estimation has been exploited to compute densities of states, i.e., spectral densities. Then various effective algorithms to estimate thesedensities will be presented. Approximate densities of states can be very helpful in a variety of situations and the second part of the talk will cover a few of these. The first application we discuss is that of determining the number of eigenvalues of a matrix that are located in a given interval. A special case of this is the approximation of the rank of a matrix. The density of states is also an ideal tool for "spectrum slicing", i.e., the technique of subdividing a given interval into sub-intervals in which different parts of the spectrum are computed independently. Finally, a somewhat related problem is that of developing low-rank approximate inverse preconditioners for solving linear systems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa187"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:30 - 11:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
