	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Realistic first-principle quantum simulations applied to large-scale atomistic systems pose unique challenges in the design of numerical algorithms that are both capable of processing a considerable amount of generated data, and achieving significant parallel scalability on modern high-end computing architectures. From atoms and molecules to nanostructures, we discuss how the FEAST eigensolver has considerably broadened the perspectives for enabling reliable and high-performance large-scale first-principle all-electrons DFT and real-time TDDFT calculations. Parallel performances and various numerical electronic spectroscopy results will be presented and discussed. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess206-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess206" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS38 Modeling and Simulations of Active Matter</strong>, Room C2-3</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g>	</g></svg></div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down"> <g id="Page-1" stroke="none" stroke-width="1" fill="none" fill-rule="evenodd"> <g id="arrow-down" fill="#000000"> <polygon id="Shape" points="14.9042553 19.7178256 15.9574468 18.6646341 24.5 27.4412299 33.0425532 18.6646341 34.0957447 19.7178256 24.5 29.6646341"/> </g> </g></svg></div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </a>	</div>	<div class="collapse" id="collapse-sess206"> <div class="session-body"> <div class="table organizer-items session-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Organizer(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="organizers inline"> <div class="author"> Alexander Alexeev (Georgia Institute of Technology, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp154","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"Georgia Institute of Technology","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Physics, Engineering</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Active Matter is an emerging field of Physics that studies a variety of systems composed of entities that can actively consume energy to convert it into motion. Biological examples of active matter range in scale by many orders of magnitude from swarms of motile bacteria to schools of fish. They can together exhibit such phenomena as collective motion and dynamic self-organization. Understanding the basic principles governing inherently non-equilibrium active matter is a difficult challenge. One of the approaches to achieve this goal is to create synthetic systems that can reproduce behaviors typical for living matter, which can be studied to understand complex phenomena emerging in active matter. Computational modeling plays a critical role in this process enabling both better understanding of biological systems and devising synthetic systems that can be then experimentally tested. This minisymposium will discuss recent computational advances and challenges in the field of Active Matter.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa165"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:00 - 09:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa165","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Collective Motion of Gel-Actuated Micro-Swimmers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Advances in polymers have enabled the development of novel materials that can reversibly change the shape controlled by external stimuli. We use mesoscale modeling to probe how these stimuli-sensitive synthetic materials can be used to design self-propelling microscopic swimmers. Our swimmers are made of a bi-layered hydrogel sheet composed of layers with distinct sensitivities to external stimuli. When a stimulus is introduced, one of the layers swells causing the body of our X-shaped micro-swimmer to bend. Upon stimulus removal, the responsive layer contracts and the micro-swimmer recovers its initial flat shape. We first use dissipative particle dynamics to model hydrogel swimmer and explore the physics of its propulsion through a viscous solvent. We use the computational model to probe how material properties affect the swimming speed. We then employ lattice-Boltzmann simulations to investigate the collective behavior of suspensions of these swimmers in confined and unbounded environments.","begin_time":"09:00","begin_timestamp":"1522220400","end_time":"09:30","end_timestamp":"1522222200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa165","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"Georgia Institute of Technology","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa165","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"Georgia Institute of Technology","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Collective Motion of Gel-Actuated Micro-Swimmers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Alexander Alexeev (Georgia Institute of Technology, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa165","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Alexander","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"Georgia Institute of Technology","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Advances in polymers have enabled the development of novel materials that can reversibly change the shape controlled by external stimuli. We use mesoscale modeling to probe how these stimuli-sensitive synthetic materials can be used to design self-propelling microscopic swimmers. Our swimmers are made of a bi-layered hydrogel sheet composed of layers with distinct sensitivities to external stimuli. When a stimulus is introduced, one of the layers swells causing the body of our X-shaped micro-swimmer to bend. Upon stimulus removal, the responsive layer contracts and the micro-swimmer recovers its initial flat shape. We first use dissipative particle dynamics to model hydrogel swimmer and explore the physics of its propulsion through a viscous solvent. We use the computational model to probe how material properties affect the swimming speed. We then employ lattice-Boltzmann simulations to investigate the collective behavior of suspensions of these swimmers in confined and unbounded environments. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa174"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
