	</script> <div class="title">Equilibrium Physics Breakdown Reveals the Active Nature of Red Blood Cell Flickering</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dmitry Fedosov (Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa174","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Fedosov","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Red blood cells are seen to flicker under optical microscopy, a phenomenon initially described as thermal fluctuations of the cell membrane. However, recent studies have suggested the involvement of non-equilibrium processes, without definitively ruling out equilibrium interpretations. Using active and passive microrheology to directly compare the membrane response and fluctuations on single cells, we find a violation of the fluctuation–dissipation relation, which is a direct demonstration of the non-equilibrium nature of flickering. With realistic stochastic simulations and an analytical model of the composite erythrocyte membrane, we show that several molecular mechanisms (e.g., spectrin network remodeling and ion pumps) may explain the active fluctuations, and we predict their kinetics. We are also able to quantitatively extract RBC membrane properties including shear elasticity, bending rigidity, and membrane viscosity. Our findings provide solid experimental and theoretical frameworks for future investigations of the origin and function of active motion in cells. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa177"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa177","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Prediction of Salt-Responsive Behavior of Polyelectrolyte Micelles and Gels","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Responsive materials will play an increasingly important part in a diverse range of applications. However, the mechanisms of responsiveness are difficult to characterize due to its inherent complexity and multiscale nature. Modeling a responsive material presents a challenge with a large number of unknown variable parameters, such as chemical reactions and kinetic or conformational changes as a function of environment, which are hard to measure directly. We have recently developed a method that is parameterized based on a single set of parameters, which allows for large-scale simulations of self-assembling polyelectrolyte materials and their morphological response to the changes in salt concentration. In this talk, I will illustrate our recent progress in prediction of responsive morphologies of DNA-based micelles and gels. Our methodology permits us to construct a morphological diagram of polyelectrolyte or DNA-block copolymers and evaluate the size of aggregates obtained along with their responsive morphological transitions and scaling relations.","begin_time":"10:00","begin_timestamp":"1522224000","end_time":"10:30","end_timestamp":"1522225800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room C2-3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa177","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yaroslava G.","last_name":"Yingling","affiliation":"North Carolina State University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa177","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Yaroslava G.","last_name":"Yingling","affiliation":"North Carolina State University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room C2-3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Prediction of Salt-Responsive Behavior of Polyelectrolyte Micelles and Gels</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Yaroslava G. Yingling (North Carolina State University, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
