		{"id":"symp148","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dominik","last_name":"Goeddeke","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> <div class="author"> Michael A. Heroux (Sandia National Laboratories, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp148","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael A.","last_name":"Heroux","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Current and future computing systems are becoming increasingly unreliable and unpredictable: It is expected that at scale, errors will become the rule rather than the exception, and already today, severe performance fluctuations can be observed. In addition, the heterogeneity of the hardware mandates robustness, asynchrony, and communication-avoiding to be built directly into the methods, in order to achieve close to peak performance. Consequently, reliability and robustness must be built directly into scientific computing applications and numerical algorithms. In this minisymposium, we discuss the state of the art in fault-tolerant, communication-avoiding and asynchronous methods, focusing on, but not necessarily limiting the scope to, iterative solvers. The invited talks emphasize proven or provable novel algorithms and mathematical techniques beyond redundancy. Recent developments towards interactions with middleware and operating systems, as well as analytical or parameterised models, will also be highlighted. This workshop, a synthesis of the state of the field, will be accessible to non-experts and experts alike.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa108"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:00 - 09:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa108","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Resilient Constructs for Parallel Applications","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Over the last few years, the question of resilience evolved from \u0022will there be a need for resilience\u0022 toward a more pragmatic version asking how often the fault will impact the outcome of the application. In all cases, such an approach assumes that detection and recovery constructs are available either in the programming paradigm or at the system level, guaranteeing a complete protection of the application and its data. This talk will highlight available techniques to survive faults, their expect costs at scale, as well as present more application-driven approaches and the necessary support from the programming paradigms and their runtimes.","begin_time":"09:00","begin_timestamp":"1522220400","end_time":"09:30","end_timestamp":"1522222200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa108","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"George","last_name":"Bosilca","affiliation":"University of Tennessee","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa108","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"George","last_name":"Bosilca","affiliation":"University of Tennessee","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Resilient Constructs for Parallel Applications</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> George Bosilca (University of Tennessee, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
