	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Over the last few years, the question of resilience evolved from "will there be a need for resilience" toward a more pragmatic version asking how often the fault will impact the outcome of the application. In all cases, such an approach assumes that detection and recovery constructs are available either in the programming paradigm or at the system level, guaranteeing a complete protection of the application and its data. This talk will highlight available techniques to survive faults, their expect costs at scale, as well as present more application-driven approaches and the necessary support from the programming paradigms and their runtimes. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa103"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">09:30 - 10:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa103","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fault Detection and Mitigation for Multigrid Solvers","scientific_track":"","abstract":"We present techniques to detect and repair hard and soft faults in multigrid schemes. For hard faults, we exploit the multigrid hierarchy to generate exponentially smaller checkpoints and demonstrate that restarting from coarse approximations only mildly degrades convergence. The approach is automatically applicable in asynchronous settings. For soft faults, we use ideas from classical algorithm-based fault tolerance (ABFT) and nonlinear multigrid to derive indicators for fault detection that even work if only a single multigrid cycle is performed. Numerical results indicate a near-optimal tradeoff between overhead and robustness for a wide range of standard test problems.","begin_time":"09:30","begin_timestamp":"1522222200","end_time":"10:00","end_timestamp":"1522224000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa103","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dominik","last_name":"G\u00f6ddeke","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa103","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dominik","last_name":"G\u00f6ddeke","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa103","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mirco","last_name":"Altenbernd","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Fault Detection and Mitigation for Multigrid Solvers</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dominik Göddeke (University of Stuttgart, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
