	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> We present techniques to detect and repair hard and soft faults in multigrid schemes. For hard faults, we exploit the multigrid hierarchy to generate exponentially smaller checkpoints and demonstrate that restarting from coarse approximations only mildly degrades convergence. The approach is automatically applicable in asynchronous settings. For soft faults, we use ideas from classical algorithm-based fault tolerance (ABFT) and nonlinear multigrid to derive indicators for fault detection that even work if only a single multigrid cycle is performed. Numerical results indicate a near-optimal tradeoff between overhead and robustness for a wide range of standard test problems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa131"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:00 - 10:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa131","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Urgency and Progress in Application Level Fault Tolerance","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The relationship between computer system reliability and application resilience is nuanced. Most of our scientific application base requires the practical equivalent of a reliable, digital computer. Therefore, computer system vendors will strive to deliver this kind of platform, knowing that users are unprepared for faults. At the same time, preserving reliability is becoming increasingly expensive, in system engineering costs, schedule delays and adoption of the latest component parts. Algorithmic and software preparations are urgently needed so that future applications are more resilient to failure, enabling computer system developers to relax their constraints. In this presentation, we provide abstract frameworks for resilient algorithms and show progress on the local-failure, local-recovery model for single-program, multiple-data (SPMD) applications. We also discuss the opportunities for addressing resilience as we move toward task-based execution environments, where new approaches to resilience become possible.","begin_time":"10:00","begin_timestamp":"1522224000","end_time":"10:30","end_timestamp":"1522225800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa131","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael A.","last_name":"Heroux","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa131","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael A.","last_name":"Heroux","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Urgency and Progress in Application Level Fault Tolerance</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Michael A. Heroux (Sandia National Laboratories, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa131","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael A.","last_name":"Heroux","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The relationship between computer system reliability and application resilience is nuanced. Most of our scientific application base requires the practical equivalent of a reliable, digital computer. Therefore, computer system vendors will strive to deliver this kind of platform, knowing that users are unprepared for faults. At the same time, preserving reliability is becoming increasingly expensive, in system engineering costs, schedule delays and adoption of the latest component parts. Algorithmic and software preparations are urgently needed so that future applications are more resilient to failure, enabling computer system developers to relax their constraints. In this presentation, we provide abstract frameworks for resilient algorithms and show progress on the local-failure, local-recovery model for single-program, multiple-data (SPMD) applications. We also discuss the opportunities for addressing resilience as we move toward task-based execution environments, where new approaches to resilience become possible. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa107"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">10:30 - 11:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa107","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Resilience Enhancement Using Discrete A Priori Bounds for the Detection of Faulty PDE Solutions","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Resilience represents one of the many challenges to be anticipated and addressed before viable exascale systems can emerge. In this context, we focus on the problem of resilience to silent data corruption (SDC) in elliptic partial differential equation (PDE) solvers. We derive a priori bounds for the discrete solution of second-order elliptic partial differential equations (PDEs). The bounds are then incorporated into a task-based domain decomposition framework, in order to verify the admissibility of local (i.e., at the subdomain level) PDE solutions. We demonstrate that these a priori bounds are able to detect most of system faults, and thus considerably enhance the resilience and the overall performance of the solver.","begin_time":"10:30","begin_timestamp":"1522225800","end_time":"11:00","end_timestamp":"1522227600","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa107","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Paul","last_name":"Mycek","affiliation":"CERFACS","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa107","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Paul","last_name":"Mycek","affiliation":"CERFACS","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa107","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Bert","last_name":"Debusschere","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa107","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Omar","last_name":"Knio","affiliation":"King Abdullah University of Science and Technology","country":"Saudi Arabia","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa107","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Olivier","last_name":"Le Ma\u00eetre","affiliation":"LIMSI","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa107","title":"Dr.","bio":