	</script> <div class="title">Resilience Enhancement Using Discrete A Priori Bounds for the Detection of Faulty PDE Solutions</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Paul Mycek (CERFACS, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa107","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Paul","last_name":"Mycek","affiliation":"CERFACS","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS40_107.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Resilience represents one of the many challenges to be anticipated and addressed before viable exascale systems can emerge. In this context, we focus on the problem of resilience to silent data corruption (SDC) in elliptic partial differential equation (PDE) solvers. We derive a priori bounds for the discrete solution of second-order elliptic partial differential equations (PDEs). The bounds are then incorporated into a task-based domain decomposition framework, in order to verify the admissibility of local (i.e., at the subdomain level) PDE solutions. We demonstrate that these a priori bounds are able to detect most of system faults, and thus considerably enhance the resilience and the overall performance of the solver. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head simple"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>11:00 - 11:30</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>Coffee Break</strong>, Foyer</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> </div> </div> </div>	</div>	</div> <div class="session-head simple"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>11:30 - 12:30</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>CSCS Update</strong>, Room A</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> </div> </div> </div>	</div>	</div> <div class="session-head simple"> <di