	</script> <div class="title">Measuring the Ankle-Brachial Index with Massively Parallel Simulations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Amanda Randles (Duke University, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa180","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Amanda","last_name":"Randles","affiliation":"Duke University","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The ankle-brachial index (ABI), relating arterial blood pressure in the upper arm and ankle, is used to diagnose peripheral arterial disease. Computational simulations of ABI have the potential to determine the parameters which produce an abnormal or ischemic ABI. While zero- and one-dimensional schemes to compute ABI exist, three-dimensional computational fluid dynamics simulations are capable of higher simulation fidelity and can incorporate patient-derived imaging data. We introduce highly parallelized and scalable methods for generating the simulation domain of the full arterial system and efficiently distributing the computational load among 1.6 million tasks. We conduct simulations of flow in a full arterial system and demonstrate adequate numerical convergence for ABI at 50&#956;m simulation resolution. We study the dependence of ABI on stenoses by modifying the arterial geometry. Further, by incorporating gravity as an external force, we consider the influence of body posture on ABI. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa201"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
