	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The waLBerla software framework provides efficient parallel methods that can be used to simulate flows on adaptive meshes in complex domains. It is thus well suited for flow scenarios as they arise in hemodynamics. In biomedical applications both strong and weak scalability are important. We will discuss data structures, algorithms, and novel software techniques based on automatic program transformations that additionally help to achieve excellent in-core and intra-node performance. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa208"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa208","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Numerical Lab-On-a-Chip: High-Throughput Simulation and Optimization of Microfluidic Devices","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Microfluidic devices, such as lab-on-a-chip, transport and manipulate nanoliter quantities of fluids to perform tasks like blood separation and detection of Circulating Tumor Cells (CTCs). However, fast computer aided design of the chips remains a formidable task due to the complexity and scale of involved processes. We present uDeviceX (ACM Gordon Bell Prize Finalist 2015), a high-throughput software designed for accurate simulations of microconfined blood flows at large scales using state-of-the art DPD (Dissipative Particle Dynamics) models. Targeted and carefully optimized for GPU-enabled supercomputers, uDeviceX is capable of unprecedented simulations of blood flows at sub-micron resolution in realistic microfluidic geometries. Following recent experimental studies, we have built and tested a virtual microfluidic device that separates RBCs from WBCs and CTCs in the high-hematocrit solution using the Deterministic Lateral Displacement principle. Moreover, the fast time-to-solution allowed us to computationally optimize design of the device and achieve enhanced filtering speed and purity.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa208","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa208","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa208","title":"Ms.","bio":"","first_name":"Eva Athena","last_name":"Economides","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presente