	</script> <div class="title">Numerical Lab-On-a-Chip: High-Throughput Simulation and Optimization of Microfluidic Devices</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Dmitry Alexeev (ETH Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa208","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Dmitry","last_name":"Alexeev","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Microfluidic devices, such as lab-on-a-chip, transport and manipulate nanoliter quantities of fluids to perform tasks like blood separation and detection of Circulating Tumor Cells (CTCs). However, fast computer aided design of the chips remains a formidable task due to the complexity and scale of involved processes. We present uDeviceX (ACM Gordon Bell Prize Finalist 2015), a high-throughput software designed for accurate simulations of microconfined blood flows at large scales using state-of-the art DPD (Dissipative Particle Dynamics) models. Targeted and carefully optimized for GPU-enabled supercomputers, uDeviceX is capable of unprecedented simulations of blood flows at sub-micron resolution in realistic microfluidic geometries. Following recent experimental studies, we have built and tested a virtual microfluidic device that separates RBCs from WBCs and CTCs in the high-hematocrit solution using the Deterministic Lateral Displacement principle. Moreover, the fast time-to-solution allowed us to computationally optimize design of the device and achieve enhanced filtering speed and purity. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa242"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa242","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fully Coupled Fluid-Electro-Mechanical Cardiac Problems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this work, we present a fully coupled fluid-electro-mechanical cardiac simulation amenable to be used in parallel computers. The coupled 3-field problem is solved using Alya, which is the in-house BSC\u0027s parallel multi-physics simulation code. The examples we show are done on a biventricular geometry to study the effect of transcatheter medical devices implanted in the cardiac cavities in the flow around them. The problems are large enough to be solved in parallel computers, the scalability of the fully-coupled algorithm being a decisive issue. Therefore, we explain details of the parallel implementation of the code not only for the individual problems but also for the coupling schemes, which includes an interface quasi-Newton scheme specifically designed for efficient parallel runs in large-scale cases.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa242","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jazmin","last_name":"Aguado","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa242","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jazmin","last_name":"Aguado","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa242","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Mariano","last_name":"V\u00e1zquez","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 005","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Fully Coupled Fluid-Electro-Mechanical Cardiac Problems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Jazmin Aguado (Barcelona Supercomputing Center, Spain)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa242","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Jazmin","last_name":"Aguado","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this work, we present a fully coupled fluid-electro-mechanical cardiac simulation amenable to be used in parallel computers. The coupled 3-field problem is solved using Alya, which is the in-house BSC's parallel multi-physics simulation code. The examples we show are done on a biventricular geometry to study the effect of transcatheter medical devices implanted in the cardiac cavities in the flow around them. The problems are large enough to be solved in parallel computers, the scalability of the fully-coupled algorithm being a decisive issue. Therefore, we explain details of the parallel implementation of the code not only for the individual problems but also for the coupling schemes, which includes an interface quasi-Newton scheme specifically designed for efficient parallel runs in large-scale cases. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess191-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess191" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS42 Earth System Modeling: HPC Bringing Together Weather and Climate Prediction</strong>, Room A</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" p