	</script> <div class="title">ESiWACE: The Center of Excellence in Simulation of Climate and Weather in Europe</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Joachim Biercamp (German Climate Computing Centre, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa157","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Joachim","last_name":"Biercamp","affiliation":"German Climate Computing Centre","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> A particular challenge for weather and climate simulation is comprehensive global models with spatial resolutions that allow simulating convective clouds and small-scale ocean eddies. These simulations would produce better predictions of trends and provide much more fidelity in the representation of high-impact regional events. However, running such models in operational mode clearly require exascale computing and data handling capability. We will discuss the ESiWACE initiative and relate it to work in progress on high-resolution simulations in Europe. We present strong scalability measurements to demonstrate current computability in weather and climate simulation. Special focus is on the Icosahedal Nonhydrostatic (ICON) model used for high-resolution global and regional simulations. We demonstrate that close-to-optimal parallel efficiency can be achieved in strong scaling global experiments, e.g. 94% for 5km resolution using 36k cores. Based on scalability and high-resolution experiments we extrapolate future capabilities for ICON expected for weather and climate research at exascale. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa166"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
