	</script> <div class="title">IS-ENES Coupling Technology Benchmarks</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Sophie Valcke (CERFACS, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa160","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Sophie","last_name":"Valcke","affiliation":"CERFACS","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Within the European IS-ENES2 project we are developing coupling technology benchmarks based on simplified model components which capture the essence of the coupling without the complexities of the science. Today, five simple coupled configurations are available for testing. The components of these configurations run on regular latitude-longitude grids with up to 3000x3000 grid points. All configurations implement the same coupling algorithm (i.e. fields are sent back and forth between the components) using either the OASIS3-MCT, OpenPALM, ESMF, MCT only or YAC coupling technologies. The time for the coupling initialization and for the coupling exchanges was measured for the configurations running with up to O(10000) cores on three different platforms: Bullx at CINES in France, Cray XC40 at the UK Met Office, and the Broadwell partition of Marconi at CINECA in Italy. These results and lessons learned from this first benchmark experience will be discussed and future plans will be presented. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa203"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa203","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"How to Escape from the Data Avalanche of High-Resolution Climate Models?","scientific_track":"","abstract":"There are large efforts towards refining the horizontal resolution of climate models to O(1 km) with the intent to represent convective clouds explicitly rather than using semi-empirical parameterizations. This refinement would move the governing equations closer to first principles and is expected to reduce the uncertainties of climate models. However, the output volume of climate simulations would dramatically grow, and storing it for later analysis would likely become impractical, due to limited I\/O bandwidth and mass-storage capacity. In this presentation we discuss possible solutions to this challenge. Key elements of the proposed strategy are the exploitation of online analysis in combination with rerunning the simulation, as well as the use of bit-reproducible codes and a data virtualization layer. The work is based on an ongoing project that uses a GPU-enabled version of the COSMO model as a regional climate model at 2.2 km resolution on a European domain.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room A"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa203","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Christoph","last_name":"Sch\u00e4r","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa203","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Christoph","last_name":"Sch\u00e4r","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa203","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Andrea","last_name":"Arteaga","affiliation":"ETH Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"0"},{"id":"msa203","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Christophe","last_name":"Charpilloz","affiliation":"MeteoSwiss","country":"Switzerland","is_pre