	</script> <div class="title">Stitched the Multi-Threaded CMS Framework: Strategy and Performance on HPC Platforms</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Vincenzo Innocente (CERN, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa124","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Vincenzo","last_name":"Innocente","affiliation":"CERN","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS43_02.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Simulation and Data processing in High Energy Physics is blessed by natural parallelism at many levels of granularity: down to single particle in the case of Detector Simulation. This has allowed it to exploit farm parallelization as long as memory per core was abundant. This came with the cost of a poor usage of SIMD and SIMT architectures as farm parallelization is intrinsically incoherent. In this presentation, we will discuss the evolution of the software framework of the CMS experiment to adapt to HPC platforms where memory per core is scarce and where exploiting SIMD and SIMT is essential to leverage the full computing power available. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess202-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess202" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS44 Modeling, Computational Methods and Applications of Fluorescence-Mediated Tomography</strong>, Villa Ciani, Room 205</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygo