		{"id":"symp150","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Martin","last_name":"Frank","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Emerging Domains in HPC, Life Sciences</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Fluorescence-mediated tomography (FMT) is an optical imaging technique to access the three-dimensional distribution of a fluorescent in a few centimeters depth. The main application is for preclinical drug development, but the technology is also potentially applicable for human hand and breast imaging. In FMT, a light source shines onto the object and the light propagates into the object, where it scatters and is absorbed. It triggers a fluorescent material, which emits light at a different wavelength. The remaining light and the emitted light can be measured on the other side of the object. From the measurements, the fluorescence distribution should be reconstructed as accurately as possible. This is not only a relevant medical problem but also leads to a current topic of mathematical research. One important aspect is an accurate optical model containing information about the shape and heterogeneous scattering and absorption maps. Mathematically, the process can be described by the Boltzmann transport equation, which itself is expensive to solve.&nbsp;Furthermore, due to the high scattering in the near-infrared wavelengths, the inverse problem of fluorescence reconstruction is a mathematically and computationally challenging problem, requiring HPC.&nbsp;<br /><br />The purpose of this minisymposium is to report on the continuing progress on mathematical and computational methods that aim at an improvement of the quality of the FMT image reconstruction.&nbsp;It brings together researchers from applied mathematics, computational science, as well as industry&nbsp;to discuss their work and exchange ideas.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa204"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa204","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fluorescence-Mediated Tomography in Pharmacology Research","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Fluorescent-mediated tomography (FMT) can provide quantitative in-vivo assessment of fluorescent-labeled probes, therefore allowing for many preclinical applications in pharmacological research. In a study investigating the impact of tumor microenvironment on tumor invasion, a significantly higher matrix metalloproteinases (MMP)-activity, indication of tumor invasion, was detected in-vivo in late-stage tumors compared to intermediate- and early-stage tumors. Moreover, significantly reduced MMP-activity was monitored post sunitinib-treatment. All in-vivo findings were confirmed by ex-vivo immunohistochemistry analysis. \u00b5CT-FMT was applied in another study to assess elimination routes and organ bio-distribution of various fluorescent model drugs and drug-delivery systems. ICG demonstrated hepatobiliary elimination and complete clearance from the body at 48h. NanoGels showed similar but slower hepatobiliary elimination due to size-dependent degradation. OsteoSense was strongly located in bones and rapidly cleared renally and MicroBubbles showed the longest retention in liver and spleen and low signal in the kidneys likely caused by fragment-retention.","begin_time":"13:30","begin_timestamp":"1522236600","end_time":"14:00","end_timestamp":"1522238400","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa204","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa204","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa204","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Wa\u0027el","last_name":"Al Rawashdeh","affiliation":"Miltenyi Biotec","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Fluorescence-Mediated Tomography in Pharmacology Research</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Felix Gremse (RWTH Aachen University, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa204","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Fluorescent-mediated tomography (FMT) can provide quantitative in-vivo assessment of fluorescent-labeled probes, therefore allowing for many preclinical applications in pharmacological research. In a study investigating the impact of tumor microenvironment on tumor invasion, a significantly higher matrix metalloproteinases (MMP)-activity, indication of tumor invasion, was detected in-vivo in late-stage tumors compared to intermediate- and early-stage tumors. Moreover, significantly reduced MMP-activity was monitored post sunitinib-treatment. All in-vivo findings were confirmed by ex-vivo immunohistochemistry analysis. µCT-FMT was applied in another study to assess elimination routes and organ bio-distribution of various fluorescent model drugs and drug-delivery systems. ICG demonstrated hepatobiliary elimination and complete clearance from the body at 48h. NanoGels showed similar but slower hepatobiliary elimination due to size-dependent degradation. OsteoSense was strongly located in bones and rapidly cleared renally and MicroBubbles showed the longest retention in liver and spleen and low signal in the kidneys likely caused by fragment-retention. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa154"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa154","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Improving Resolution and Sensitivity of Fluorescence-Mediated Tomography using GPU-Accelerated Image Reconstruction","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Fluorescence-mediated tomography (FMT) enables non-invasive three-dimensional assessment of the near-infrared fluorescence distribution in human body parts or small laboratory animals. The combination with micro-computed tomography (\u00b5CT) provides anatomical information, enabling improved reconstruction and analysis. Fluorescence reconstruction involves solving a dense least squares system, whose explicit representation requires large amounts of memory, limiting the achievable resolution in practice. We propose an implicit representation where the matrix-vector product is computed using GPU-accelerated adjoint algorithmic differentiation, reducing memory requirements and allowing higher resolution reconstructions. The least squares problem is minimized using the Multiplicative Updates method, which constrains the minimization to non-negative solutions. Phantom measurements show that the non-negativity constraints are essential for fluorescence reconstruction. \u00b5CT-FMT in vivo experiments with rectal insertions containing fluorescence and CT contrast agent show that the implicit version achieves better signal localization compared to an explicit version.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa154","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa154","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","r