	</script> <div class="title">Improving Resolution and Sensitivity of Fluorescence-Mediated Tomography using GPU-Accelerated Image Reconstruction</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Felix Gremse (RWTH Aachen University, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa154","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Felix","last_name":"Gremse","affiliation":"RWTH Aachen University","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Fluorescence-mediated tomography (FMT) enables non-invasive three-dimensional assessment of the near-infrared fluorescence distribution in human body parts or small laboratory animals. The combination with micro-computed tomography (µCT) provides anatomical information, enabling improved reconstruction and analysis. Fluorescence reconstruction involves solving a dense least squares system, whose explicit representation requires large amounts of memory, limiting the achievable resolution in practice. We propose an implicit representation where the matrix-vector product is computed using GPU-accelerated adjoint algorithmic differentiation, reducing memory requirements and allowing higher resolution reconstructions. The least squares problem is minimized using the Multiplicative Updates method, which constrains the minimization to non-negative solutions. Phantom measurements show that the non-negativity constraints are essential for fluorescence reconstruction. µCT-FMT in vivo experiments with rectal insertions containing fluorescence and CT contrast agent show that the implicit version achieves better signal localization compared to an explicit version. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa252"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
