		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa139","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"On Inexact Geometry Treatment in Fluorescence Molecular Tomography","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In many applications the treatment of interfaces is challenging. A particular difficulty arises if the geometry is only defined imprecisely. In this case, it is desirable to use methods which are robust and efficient. To this aim, we propose in this talk a diffuse interface method as a tool for the solution of variational inverse problems. The main idea is to replace variational integrals of the original problem by a weighted average of integrals of perturbed domains. This allows, for example, the use of structured grids in subsequent discretization procedures, which in turn might be used in the construction of very efficient methods. As a particular example of a variational regularization method, we will discuss Tikhonov regularization when applied to fluorescence optical tomography.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa139","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Schlottbom","affiliation":"University of Twente","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa139","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Schlottbom","affiliation":"University of Twente","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Villa Ciani, Room 205","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">On Inexact Geometry Treatment in Fluorescence Molecular Tomography</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Matthias Schlottbom (University of Twente, Netherlands)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa139","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Matthias","last_name":"Schlottbom","affiliation":"University of Twente","country":"Netherlands","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In many applications the treatment of interfaces is challenging. A particular difficulty arises if the geometry is only defined imprecisely. In this case, it is desirable to use methods which are robust and efficient. To this aim, we propose in this talk a diffuse interface method as a tool for the solution of variational inverse problems. The main idea is to replace variational integrals of the original problem by a weighted average of integrals of perturbed domains. This allows, for example, the use of structured grids in subsequent discretization procedures, which in turn might be used in the construction of very efficient methods. As a particular example of a variational regularization method, we will discuss Tikhonov regularization when applied to fluorescence optical tomography. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess201-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess201" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS45 Recent Advances in Fault-Tolerant, Asynchronous and Communication-Avoiding Algorithms (2/2)</strong>, Room B3</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points