		{"id":"symp149","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Dominik","last_name":"Goeddeke","affiliation":"University of Stuttgart","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> <div class="author"> Michael A. Heroux (Sandia National Laboratories, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"symp149","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Michael A.","last_name":"Heroux","affiliation":"Sandia National Laboratories","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Computer Science &amp; Applied Mathematics</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Current and future computing systems are becoming increasingly unreliable and unpredictable: It is expected that at scale, errors will become the rule rather than the exception, and already today, severe performance fluctuations can be observed. In addition, the heterogeneity of the hardware mandates robustness, asynchrony, and communication-avoiding to be built directly into the methods, in order to achieve close to peak performance. Consequently, reliability and robustness must be built directly into scientific computing applications and numerical algorithms. In this minisymposium, we discuss the state of the art in fault-tolerant, communication-avoiding and asynchronous methods, focusing on, but not necessarily limiting the scope to, iterative solvers. The invited talks emphasize proven or provable novel algorithms and mathematical techniques beyond redundancy. Recent developments towards interactions with middleware and operating systems, as well as analytical or parameterised models, will also be highlighted. This workshop, a synthesis of the state of the field, will be accessible to non-experts and experts alike.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa144"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa144","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fault-Tolerant Parallel-In-Time Integration with PFASST","scientific_track":"","abstract":"For time-dependent PDEs, parallel-in-time integration using the \u0022parallel full approximation scheme in space and time\u0022 (PFASST) is a promising way to accelerate existing space-parallel approaches beyond their scaling limits. Inspired by non-linear multigrid ideas, PFASST allows integration of multiple time-steps simultaneously. Its multigrid-in-time nature can be exploited to recover from hard faults and subsequent data loss, preventing a breakdown of the time integration process. Since PFASST stores solutions at multiple time steps on different processors, information from adjacent steps can be used to recover after a processor has failed. The multigrid hierarchy allows one to use the coarse level for correcting the reconstructed solution, which can help minimize overhead. We present various recovery strategies and sketch a theoretical model for linking the overhead to the number of additional iterations required for convergence after a fault. The efficiency of the different strategies is assessed for examples of diffusive and advective type.","begin_time":"13:30","begin_timestamp":"1522236600","end_time":"14:00","end_timestamp":"1522238400","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Fault-Tolerant Parallel-In-Time Integration with PFASST</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Robert Speck (Forschungszentrum Jülich, Germany)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa144","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Robert","last_name":"Speck","affiliation":"Forschungszentrum J\u00fclich","country":"Germany","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> For time-dependent PDEs, parallel-in-time integration using the "parallel full approximation scheme in space and time" (PFASST) is a promising way to accelerate existing space-parallel approaches beyond their scaling limits. Inspired by non-linear multigrid ideas, PFASST allows integration of multiple time-steps simultaneously. Its multigrid-in-time nature can be exploited to recover from hard faults and subsequent data loss, preventing a breakdown of the time integration process. Since PFASST stores solutions at multiple time steps on different processors, information from adjacent steps can be used to recover after a processor has failed. The multigrid hierarchy allows one to use the coarse level for correcting the reconstructed solution, which can help minimize overhead. We present various recovery strategies and sketch a theoretical model for linking the overhead to the number of additional iterations required for convergence after a fault. The efficiency of the different strategies is assessed for examples of diffusive and advective type. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa112"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa112","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Reducing Data Movement by Exploiting Computation Dependencies","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this talk we describe techniques based on graph partitioning methods to efficiently mitigate the impact of NUMA effects on parallel applications\u0027 performance. We dynamically exploit information regarding control or data dependencies between sequential pieces of code to efficiently reduce data transfers across the whole parallel run. Our approach adds negligible overhead and is able to significantly improve the execution time of relevant OpenMP parallel codes when run on architectures with several NUMA domains and large remote memory access latencies.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa112","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Marc","last_name":"Casas","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa112","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Marc","last_name":"Casas","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Reducing Data Movement by Exploiting Computation Dependencies</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Marc Casas (Barcelona Supercomputing Center, Spain)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa112","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Marc","last_name":"Casas","affiliation":"Barcelona Supercomputing Center","country":"Spain","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this talk we describe techniques based on graph partitioning methods to efficiently mitigate the impact of NUMA effects on parallel applications' performance. We dynamically exploit information regarding control or data dependencies between sequential pieces of code to efficiently reduce data transfers across the whole parallel run. Our approach adds negligible overhead and is able to significantly improve the execution time of relevant OpenMP parallel codes when run on architectures with several NUMA domains and large remote memory access latencies. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa155"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa155","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Fault Tolerance with High Performance for Matrix Multiplication","scientific_track":"","abstract":"General-purpose hard-error resiliency solutions such as checkpoint-restart, severely degrade performance. For numerical linear algebra, efficient solutions based on distributed 2D algorithms incur lower overhead and guarantee optimal performance for minimal memory size only. Furthermore, they require significant increase in the number of processors. We obtain fault tolerant matrix multiplication algorithms that reduce resource overhead: minimizing both the number of additional processors and the communication costs. Particularly, for 2D case, we reduce the number of additional processors required from \u0026#952;(sqrt(P)) to 1 (or from \u0026#952;(h sqrt(P)) to h, where h is the maximum number of simultaneous faults). For larger local memories, we obtain a fault tolerant adaptation of 2.5D algorithm, significantly reducing the communication costs, with very little additional processors required. Finally, we show how to obtain resiliency for Strassen and Strassen-like algorithms, with little overhead. We demonstrate that most of our algorithms are optimal or close to being optimal.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Noam","last_name":"Birnbaum","affiliation":"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem","country":"Israel","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Noam","last_name":"Birnbaum","affiliation":"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem","country":"Israel","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa155","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Oded","last_name":"Schwartz","affiliation":"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem","country":"Israel","is_presenter":"0"}