	</script> <div class="title">Fault Tolerance with High Performance for Matrix Multiplication</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Noam Birnbaum (The Hebrew University of Jerusalem, Israel)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa155","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Noam","last_name":"Birnbaum","affiliation":"The Hebrew University of Jerusalem","country":"Israel","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> General-purpose hard-error resiliency solutions such as checkpoint-restart, severely degrade performance. For numerical linear algebra, efficient solutions based on distributed 2D algorithms incur lower overhead and guarantee optimal performance for minimal memory size only. Furthermore, they require significant increase in the number of processors. We obtain fault tolerant matrix multiplication algorithms that reduce resource overhead: minimizing both the number of additional processors and the communication costs. Particularly, for 2D case, we reduce the number of additional processors required from &#952;(sqrt(P)) to 1 (or from &#952;(h sqrt(P)) to h, where h is the maximum number of simultaneous faults). For larger local memories, we obtain a fault tolerant adaptation of 2.5D algorithm, significantly reducing the communication costs, with very little additional processors required. Finally, we show how to obtain resiliency for Strassen and Strassen-like algorithms, with little overhead. We demonstrate that most of our algorithms are optimal or close to being optimal. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa138"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">15:00 - 15:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa138","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Enlarged Krylov Subspace Methods for Reducing Communication","scientific_track":"","abstract":"In this talk we discuss enlarged Krylov subspace methods for reducing communication when solving large sparse linear systems of equations. Those methods rely on adding at each iteration of the iterative method t vectors instead of one as in classic methods.  They lead to a faster convergence and thus an important reduction in the number of global communications while increasing arithmetic intensity. We present experimental and parallel performance results that show the efficiency of the methods.","begin_time":"15:00","begin_timestamp":"1522242000","end_time":"15:30","end_timestamp":"1522243800","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Olivier","last_name":"Tissot","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Olivier","last_name":"Tissot","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"},{"id":"msa138","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Laura","last_name":"Grigori","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"0"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B3","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Enlarged Krylov Subspace Methods for Reducing Communication</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Olivier Tissot (INRIA, France)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa138","title":"Mr.","bio":"","first_name":"Olivier","last_name":"Tissot","affiliation":"INRIA","country":"France","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> In this talk we discuss enlarged Krylov subspace methods for reducing communication when solving large sparse linear systems of equations. Those methods rely on adding at each iteration of the iterative method t vectors instead of one as in classic methods. They lead to a faster convergence and thus an important reduction in the number of global communications while increasing arithmetic intensity. We present experimental and parallel performance results that show the efficiency of the methods. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess170-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess170" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>MS46 Still Toward First-Principles Simulations on Exascale Supercomputers</strong>, Room B1</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-right"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" version="1.1" id="Ebene_1" x="0px" y="0px" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" style="enable-background:new 0 0 48 48;" xml:space="preserve" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-right">	<g id="Page-1"> <g id="arrow-left"> <polygon id="Shape-Copy-3" points="20.1,33.2 19,32.1 27.8,23.6 19,15.1 20.1,14 30,23.6 "/> </g>	</g></svg></div> <div class="spotws-svg arrow-down" style="display: none;"><svg xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" xmlns:xlink="http://www.w3.org/1999/xlink" width="48px" height="48px" viewBox="0 0 48 48" version="1.1" class="spot-svg spot-svg-arrow-down">