		{"id":"symp116","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Yoshitaka","last_name":"Tateyama","affiliation":"National Institute for Materials Science","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="tr fields"> <div class="td td-label">Track(s):</div> <div class="td"> <div class="field"> <div class="field-name">Chemistry &amp; Materials</div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="abstract"> <div class="text"> <p>Although it seems difficult for any hardware to reach real exaflops at the moment, developments of first-principles calculation codes in this direction are still very important in the community of materials science, chemistry, and condensed matter physics. The Swiss National Computing Centre, which has the world No.8 Piz Daint (9.7 PFlops), announced that it will adopt NVIDIA Pascal GPU in conjunction with Intel Haswell CPU. On the other hand, in Japan, the Joint Center for Advanced High-Performance Computing and FUJITSU launched world No.6 Oakforest-PACS (13.5 PFlops), consisting of Intel Xeon Phi, and RIKEN, the centre of world No.7 K-computer (10.5 PFlops) by FUJITSU, announced that it will adopt ARM processors for the Post-K exascale supercomputer. Namely, there are two different directions: GPU-CPU and many-cores. In this trend, first-principle (mainly DFT) calculations codes need to be adjusted to either or both in the coding stage or the methodology. This minisymposium is designed to bring developers facing these issues in Switzerland and Japan together, and discuss the future directions with an audience from domain science and computer science.</p> </div> </div> <div class="submissions"> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa221"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">13:30 - 14:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa221","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Large Scale Electronic Structure Calculations with CP2K","scientific_track":"","abstract":"New developments in the electronic structure code CP2K have been focusing on algorithms for large-scale simulations using density functional (DFT) methods and wavefunction correlation methods. For both methods, the key to efficient massively parallel algorithm is the handling of sparse tensors. For DFT the algorithms need the evaluation of matrix functions (e.g. the matrix sign function) using as building block matrix-matrix multiplication. Wavefunction correlation methods can be cast into tensor reductions that can be mapped onto matrix multiplications. An efficient and versatile sparse matrix multiplications library is, therefore, the main building block for further developments in this field. We developed a massively parallel library (DBCSR) for sparse block matrix multiplication. The library allowed us to use high-performance computers for large-scale applications and to investigate limitations of currently algorithms and to design new algorithms for the use of the new generation of supercomputers.","begin_time":"13:30","begin_timestamp":"1522236600","end_time":"14:00","end_timestamp":"1522238400","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa221","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Juerg","last_name":"Hutter","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa221","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Juerg","last_name":"Hutter","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Large Scale Electronic Structure Calculations with CP2K</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Juerg Hutter (University of Zurich, Switzerland)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa221","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Juerg","last_name":"Hutter","affiliation":"University of Zurich","country":"Switzerland","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> New developments in the electronic structure code CP2K have been focusing on algorithms for large-scale simulations using density functional (DFT) methods and wavefunction correlation methods. For both methods, the key to efficient massively parallel algorithm is the handling of sparse tensors. For DFT the algorithms need the evaluation of matrix functions (e.g. the matrix sign function) using as building block matrix-matrix multiplication. Wavefunction correlation methods can be cast into tensor reductions that can be mapped onto matrix multiplications. An efficient and versatile sparse matrix multiplications library is, therefore, the main building block for further developments in this field. We developed a massively parallel library (DBCSR) for sparse block matrix multiplication. The library allowed us to use high-performance computers for large-scale applications and to investigate limitations of currently algorithms and to design new algorithms for the use of the new generation of supercomputers. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa199"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
