	</script> <div class="title">NTChem: A High-performance Software Package for Quantum Chemistry Simulation</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Takahito Nakajima (RIKEN, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa199","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Takahito","last_name":"Nakajima","affiliation":"RIKEN","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Quantum chemistry software comprises immensely useful tools in material and biological science research. Widely diverse programs have been developed in many countries, though Japan has lagged behind. In the early stages of the K computer project, no quantum chemistry software was available for general purpose and massively parallel computation on the K computer. Therefore, we have chosen to develop a new comprehensive ab initio quantum chemistry software: NTChem. It is a completely new software package that implements not only standard quantum chemistry approaches, but also original and improved theoretical methods that we have developed in our research work. We hope that NTChem will be an important tool leading the way toward a new frontier of computational molecular science. In this talk, I will present an overview of NTChem software and its applications. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa193"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa193","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Large-Scale Static and Dynamic Density-Functional Calculations in a Real-Space Scheme: New Physical Properties of Two-Dimensional Systems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"To face current and future massively parallel architectures of supercomputers requires close collaboration between the fields of physical science and computer science, and one such collaboration has been established, named COMPUTICS (http:\/\/computics-material.jp\/index-e.html). This collaboration has enabled us to perform static and dynamic electronic-structure calculations based on the density-functional theory (DFT) for tens-of-thousands of atom systems. The scheme we have adopted is the real-space (RS) scheme. We will describe how we are able to perform such large-scale computations efficiently in this RSDFT scheme and report the electronic properties obtained by the RSDFT calculations performed for two-dimensional systems such as bilayer graphene, silicene on substrates, and atomic steps on semiconductor surfaces.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa193","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Atsushi","last_name":"Oshiyama","affiliation":"University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa193","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Atsushi","last_name":"Oshiyama","affiliation":"University of Tokyo","country":"Japan","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room B1","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Large-Scale Static and Dynamic Density-Functional Calculations in a Real-Space Scheme: New Physical Properties of Two-Dimensional Systems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Atsushi Oshiyama (University of Tokyo, Japan)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
