	</script> <div class="title">Using Constrained, High-Order Subgrid Structure to Address Interaction of Turbulence with Unstable Multi-Fluid Interfaces in Uniform-Grid Eulerian Simulations</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Paul R. Woodward (University of Minnesota, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa215","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Paul R.","last_name":"Woodward","affiliation":"University of Minnesota","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Researchers wishing to simulate multifluid flows whose dynamics are dominated by the nonlinear behavior of unstable multifluid interfaces have struggled to enjoy the benefits of a Lagrangian treatment within an Eulerian code. I am using constrained PPB advection for this purpose. I will describe this technique briefly, and then introduce two well-studied test problems that can be used in future code comparison studies to assess the costs and benefits of this and other approaches. The first test is an idealized inertial confinement fusion (ICF) problem and the second is the entrainment of stably stratified gas in a stellar interior at the top of a turbulent convection zone. Both of these problems have been “solved” using Eulerian PPB advection in a PPM gas dynamics context with fine, uniform grids of up to a trillion cells. Materials will be made available on-line for interested researchers to try their hand at these problems. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa182"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:00 - 14:30</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa182","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Smooth Particle Hydrodynamics: Methods and Astrophysical Applications","scientific_track":"","abstract":"The strengths of Smooth Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) include low advection errors, the handling of arbitrary geometries and free surfaces, and naturally adapting to large density contrasts. These strengths, combined with its natural unification with the N-body techniques used for self-gravitating systems made SPH a common technique for numerical hydrodynamics in astrophysics. In the mid 2000s it became generally known that the commonly used SPH algorithms suppressed the growth of instabilities and gas mixing at phase boundaries. Since then, a number of improvements have been made to SPH algorithms to address these and other issues. Even with these improvements, SPH is still more diffusive and slower to converge than other methods, but ongoing algorithm development continues to address these shortcomings.  These advantages and challenges will be discussed and illustrated with the problem of the dissolution of a cold cloud moving through a hot medium, and the modeling of protoplanetary disks.","begin_time":"14:00","begin_timestamp":"1522238400","end_time":"14:30","end_timestamp":"1522240200","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa182","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Quinn","affiliation":"University of Washington","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa182","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Quinn","affiliation":"University of Washington","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]}},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Smooth Particle Hydrodynamics: Methods and Astrophysical Applications</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Thomas Quinn (University of Washington, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa182","title":"Prof.","bio":"","first_name":"Thomas","last_name":"Quinn","affiliation":"University of Washington","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> The strengths of Smooth Particle Hydrodynamics (SPH) include low advection errors, the handling of arbitrary geometries and free surfaces, and naturally adapting to large density contrasts. These strengths, combined with its natural unification with the N-body techniques used for self-gravitating systems made SPH a common technique for numerical hydrodynamics in astrophysics. In the mid 2000s it became generally known that the commonly used SPH algorithms suppressed the growth of instabilities and gas mixing at phase boundaries. Since then, a number of improvements have been made to SPH algorithms to address these and other issues. Even with these improvements, SPH is still more diffusive and slower to converge than other methods, but ongoing algorithm development continues to address these shortcomings. These advantages and challenges will be discussed and illustrated with the problem of the dissolution of a cold cloud moving through a hot medium, and the modeling of protoplanetary disks. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="submission item" data-id="msa223"> <div class="item-warp"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="time">14:30 - 15:00</div> </div> <div class="td"> <div class="submission-body"> <script class="pasc-abstract-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"submission":{"data":{"id":"msa223","code":"","type":"Minisymposium Presentation","title":"Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian Hydrodynamics: Recent Development and Test Problems","scientific_track":"","abstract":"Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian (ALE) methods for multimaterial, multiphysics simulation attempt to combine the material-modeling strengths of Lagrangian techniques with flexible, robust strategies for advection and other mesh optimizations. The Lagrangian Applications Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory develops the FLAG ALE radiation hydrodynamics code, including staggered-grid and cell-centered hydrodynamics, radiation diffusion, magnetohydrodynamics, and a wide variety of material models, on unstructured meshes that support relaxation, remapping, reconnection, and slide surfaces. I will review recent work on ALE methods and propose (or revisit) test problems of interest.","begin_time":"14:30","begin_timestamp":"1522240200","end_time":"15:00","end_timestamp":"1522242000","session_date":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E"},"authors":{"primary":[{"id":"msa223","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Gabriel","last_name":"Rockefeller","affiliation":"Los Alamos National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}],"secondary":[{"id":"msa223","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Gabriel","last_name":"Rockefeller","affiliation":"Los Alamos National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}]},"presentation_file":"MS47.pdf"},"sessionDate":"Wednesday, June 28, 2017","room":"Room E","settings":null}
	</script> <div class="title">Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian Hydrodynamics: Recent Development and Test Problems</div> <div class="table author-items submission-introduction"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td td-label">Presenter:</div> <div class="td"> <div class="authors inline"> <div class="author"> Gabriel Rockefeller (Los Alamos National Laboratory, United States of America)</span> <script class="pasc-biography-item-json" type="text/template">
		{"id":"msa223","title":"Dr.","bio":"","first_name":"Gabriel","last_name":"Rockefeller","affiliation":"Los Alamos National Laboratory","country":"United States of America","is_presenter":"1"}
	</script> </div> </div> </div>	</div> </div> <a href="javascript:void(0);" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-abstract" title="Abstract">+ Abstract</a> <a href="/fileadmin/user_upload/pasc17/program/MS47.pdf" target="_blank" class="btn btn-primary btn-extra-small show-pdf" title="Presentation">+ Presentation</a> <div class="abstract hidden"> Arbitrary Lagrangian-Eulerian (ALE) methods for multimaterial, multiphysics simulation attempt to combine the material-modeling strengths of Lagrangian techniques with flexible, robust strategies for advection and other mesh optimizations. The Lagrangian Applications Project at Los Alamos National Laboratory develops the FLAG ALE radiation hydrodynamics code, including staggered-grid and cell-centered hydrodynamics, radiation diffusion, magnetohydrodynamics, and a wide variety of material models, on unstructured meshes that support relaxation, remapping, reconnection, and slide surfaces. I will review recent work on ALE methods and propose (or revisit) test problems of interest. </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div>	</div> <div class="session-head simple"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>15:30 - 16:00</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>Coffee Break</strong>, Foyer</span> </div> </div> </div> </div> </div> <div class="td icon"> <div class="collapse-icon"> </div> </div> </div>	</div>	</div> <div class="session-head submission" id="collapse-sess213-head"> <a href="#collapse-sess213" data-toggle="collapse" aria-expanded="false" aria-controls="collapseExample"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td"> <div class="collapse-text"> <div class="table"> <div class="tr"> <div class="td time"> <span>16:00 - 16:50</span> </div> <div class="td title"> <span><strong>Invited Plenary - Towards Quantum High Performance Computing</strong>, Room A</span> </div> </div> </di